<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS TOOK EASY WAY OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Twenty-thousand dollars could solve a few household
problems, no? That's an impressive pile of loot, especially if you
happened to wake up one day to find that crisp stack of green
suddenly bulging from your bank account. Or missing from it. Wave
around cash like that and you could buy yourself into many options.
</P>
<P>
   But $20,000 is not enough to buy you out of one thing:
insincerity. Last time we checked, insincerity didn't have a price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Gorter obviously doesn't understand that, even though he
is $20,000 poorer than he was this time last week. Gorter, a New
England Revolution midfielder, came to town with a reputation as a
creative playmaker. Apparently he is not as skilled with his choice
of words. Or maybe he is, as long as the person he is talking to
isn't wearing dark skin.
</P>
<P>
   During a Revolution practice last week, Gorter got into an
argument with teammate David Nakhid and eventually called him a
``black (expletive).'' The men then exchanged punches before being
separated. Nakhid is a black man from Trinidad and Tobago. Gorter
is a white man from Holland. The Revolution quickly alerted Major
League Soccer about the incident, and 48 hours later, Gorter was
ordered to pay the largest fine in league history ($20,000). He
also was suspended for two games and told to issue a public apology
to Nakhid.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it. So now everyone is supposed to move on and
maybe pay attention to the league's conference finals. All
consciences are supposed to be clear. Maybe someone can dig into
their record crates, find an extended remix of ``We Are The
World,'' and arrange for a group shot of the Revolution holding
hands.
</P>
<P>
   How foolish. How incomplete. How typical of well-intentioned
people who truly cannot grasp their ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   You can start with the act itself. Many Revolution players can
tell you that there has always been tension between Gorter and
Nakhid. Apparently, Gorter had been upset with his teammate, also a
midfielder, for not switching to sweeper early in the season when
it was obvious defensive help was needed. So Gorter played the
position for a while, unhappily. It is possible that Gorter
believed his teammate to be selfish, regardless of his complexion.
But the fact that he felt it necessary to put ``black'' in front of
his insult makes him at least color-struck, if not a racist.
</P>
<P>
   For those wondering, Gorter did not use the n-word but he did
use an obscenity that refers to female anatomy. His vocabulary is
his business. But if his true problem with his teammate was that he
thought he was a jerk, why not say that? Here's one reason: That
wasn't the only problem. And that's something the MLS should have
considered.
</P>
<P>
   But after all the proper words from the league, the fine, and
the prepared apology from Gorter, guess what still hasn't happened?
Gorter still hasn't apologized personally to Nakhid. According to
Nakhid, the men have not spoken since the incident. That's why I
say forget the apology, especially if Gorter doesn't know what he
is apologizing for. If he truly meant what he said, it would be
smarter for the league to confront the problem rather than bury it
under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to see the Revolution and the league set up a
televised press conference in a section of Boston where Caribbean
people live, maybe in Mattapan where Nakhid eats and gets his hair
cut. Invite the community. Then ask Gorter to repeat what he said
to Nakhid and ask him why he said it. And then allow the public to
ask both parties questions.
</P>
<P>
   Risky? No doubt. The league would have to provide a virtual
security army. But at least Gorter would truly be accountable for
his words (he certainly isn't accountable now). This session would
not heal him, of course. Racism and its byproducts travel through
bodies like a raging virus. But the result would be more lasting
than a flimsy apology. The result, in fact, could educate people on
the worldwide epidemic of hate and supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Such a forum could happen if the MLS were interested in change.
But the league followed a connect-the-dots grid to dealing with the
problem. Act quickly. Impose a fine. Issue a public statement. All
of that happened, but what didn't happen was a lengthy discussion
with Nakhid and his representatives. Nakhid's agent and lawyer are
based in Los Angeles and said they needed more time to travel
across the country. The league didn't get it; it should have. There
should have been no deadlines on finding the truth. But the league
had to get this incident out of the news so the soccer public could
focus on the games.
</P>
<P>
   After all its failings, the MLS still has a chance to do
something right. It can take Gorter's $20,000 and turn it into a
scholarship fund for a Caribbean student. And when it came time for
presenting the check, Gorter could hand over the money and explain
to the student why his $20,000 was going to someone else's fund
rather than to his own bank account. If that happened, the
Revolution midfielder might be on his way to understanding the true
meaning of a personal revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
