<HEADLINE>
RANGER REMARKS SIMPLY PRICELESS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a mind-boggling development, right up there with
man biting dog, Dewey defeating Truman, the Titanic missing the
iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   Someone has accused the Bruins of being generous, bank-breaking
spendthrifts! Quick, call the cops!
</P>
<P>
   After the Bruins' final exhibition game against the Rangers in
Hartford a week ago, New York general manager Neil Smith railed
about Harry Sinden to the New York media.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who to that point had been unable to sign center Manny
Malhotra, the club's first-round pick (No. 7 overall) in the June
draft, was furious that the Bruins had, in Smith's mind, screwed up
the entry-level system with their signings of first-round picks
Sergei Samsonov and Joe Thornton a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston coughed up bonuses on Thornton and Samsonov and now the
floodgates are open,'' said Smith, who is against giving players
individual bonuses. ``The Bruins ruined it for everybody because
they paid Samsonov and Thornton all that money. Now, we're all
fighting tooth and nail with every high-level player.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden was both incredulous and amused, considering the Bruins'
longstanding (and not necessarily accurate) reputation for being
cheap. So, the Boston president/GM replied to Smith via fax
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote him a letter and asked his forgiveness,'' said Sinden.
``I really did. I hoped he could find a small place in his heart to
forgive me. I said, `Having set such an exemplary reputation as to
do with players' salaries, to upset you over this aspect of the
business is really bothering me.' From now on, before we do
anything like that or before we ever behave like that again, we'll
call him first.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden's tongue-in-cheek response reflects the irony of the
situation. Smith's Rangers have one of the highest payrolls in the
league, which ownership told him to cut. In the past, that club has
overpaid for some over-the-hill free agents and absorbed some
less-than-worthwhile contracts. So the pot calling the kettle black
was worth more than a few guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is funny,'' said Sinden. ``He couldn't get his player
signed so he had to turn somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, at the 11th hour, the Rangers did sign Malhotra,
giving him slightly more than Samsonov's package.
</P>
<P>
   When a Newsday reporter asked Sinden if it was the right
decision to keep Thornton up last year rather than send him back to
juniors, the Bruins' boss didn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``we probably should have checked with the
Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russian defenseman  &UR; Maxim Galanov  &LR; was snagged in the waiver
draft by Pittsburgh a week ago. One minute he was a Ranger on the
way to the first tee at the club's golf outing in Westchester
County, the next minute, he was an ex-Ranger. ``I'm not a good
golfer,'' said Galanov ... Straight man  &UR; Ron MacLean &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who cohosts
``Coaches Corner'' on CBC's ``Hockey Night in Canada'' with former
Bruin coach  &UR; Don Cherry &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said Cherry's personality makes him
think of a close relative. ``He reminds me of my mother,'' MacLean
said. ``Same blue eyes, same temper. My Mom probably thinks I'm
giving her a knock by saying she reminds me of Don, but I get a big
joy out of people like that. I'm glad somebody vents and feels free
to do it. I would hate us all to be too plastic.'' ... Bruins
forward  &UR; Ted Donato  &LR; set up a goal in his only exhibition game,
last Sunday against the Rangers. Do-nato, who had a good first half
last year and a rocky second half that led him to ask for a trade,
was walking out of Hartford Civic Center after the game and was
told that after just two practices he looked to be in midseason
form. ``Geez,'' he joked, ``did I look that bad?'' ... Give  &UR; Steve
Leach  &LR; credit for perseverance. The former Bruin forward had neck
surgery in March and was bought out by Carolina in the offseason.
He went to the Senators as a free agent and was impressive enough
in training camp to win a job. ``There was a big question mark
hanging over my career for a while there,'' said Leach, 32. ``I had
to wait and see how it was going to heal up. I knew how I would
have to feel to play again and that moment came at one point in the
summer. I knew then that I'd be playing again.'' ... Defenseman
 &UR; Stan Neckar  &LR; was the last of the Ottawa free agents to agree to
terms, but that doesn't mean he liked the pact. In fact, he hates
it. ``I'm not happy with it at all,'' said Neckar. ``But I came to
Ottawa to play hockey, not just sit around. I'm happy I can play
hockey again. I'm happy I'm going to be back with the team.''
Neckar will make $700,000 US this season, some $300,000 less than
he wanted. He could collect $75,000-$100,000 more in bonuses. The
22-year-old, who has a history of knee problems, played a total of
just 65 games in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second season in a row, the NHL has sent teams to start
the year in Japan. And for the second season in a row, lots of
people who had to travel that far are not happy about it. ``It's
ridiculous,'' said Sharks center  &UR; Bernie Nicholls &LR; . ``A fast start
is so important to having a good year, and we're traveling 10-11
hours, flying across the world to play two games in a city that
we'll never, ever see again. You tell me this makes any sense. It's
just another example of Western teams getting shafted. They say
that one day we'll see two New York teams going over there to play
_ yeah, sure, not in my lifetime.'' Nicholls's point is well taken.
The Bruins set themselves up very well last season by going 6-2-0
on their first trip of the year in October. Sharks coach  &UR; Darryl
Sutter  &LR; was even more pointed about the journey: He said it
wouldn't be a bad idea for the Sharks and Flames, coached by his
brother  &UR; Brian &LR; , &UR;  &LR; to go to Hawaii, spend the time on the beach, and
tell the league they'd gone to Japan and split the games.
Reportedly, the league then told Sutter to button his lip. Sutter
is one of the few NHLers who have experience in Japan. He started
his pro hockey career there, from August 1978 to February 1979, and
became rather fluent in the language. He played for a team in
Iwakura, not far from Sapporo, before coming home to join the
Blackhawks' farm team in New Brunswick and working his way up to
the NHL ... Kings coach  &UR; Larry Robinson  &LR; said during the offseason
that he considered not returning for the fourth and final year of
his contract. `` &UR; Cal Ripken  &LR; had that (consecutive games) record
going for so long and then decided enough was enough,'' said
Robinson. ``He finally just said, `I'm going to sit this game out.'
In my case, there's going to come a time when enough is enough.
There have been a lot of sacrifices made by this organization to
build a good team. They made a big commitment to me when I first
came here because I had never coached before. They saw enough in me
to make a commitment to hire me for four years to work with the
young kids for the future and I thought I owed it to them to also
make that commitment. That's why I kind of changed my mind and
decided to stick it out.'' ... The Penguins petitioned the league
to allow them to retain the rights to retired superstar  &UR; Mario
Lemieux &LR;  without having to protect him in the waiver draft. ``Mario
hasn't signed his voluntary retirement papers, and this would have
been our fourth draft with us having to protect him,'' said
Pittsburgh GM  &UR; Craig Patrick &LR; . ``We just thought it was unfair so
we appealed to the league and they made a deal with the Players
Association which allowed him to be exempt from the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Islanders star  &UR; Zigmund Palffy  &LR; is in a contract
dispute, but this time it appears more serious, as Palffy has
requested a trade. There have been reports that the Islanders
offered to sell his rights for $20 million-$25 million. Palffy's
agent,  &UR; Paul Kraus &LR; , &UR;  &LR; said talks with team president  &UR; David Seldin
 &LR; have yielded nothing. ``It's like negotiating with oatmeal,'' said
Kraus. ``There's no point, there's no point at all. It's not going
to happen. We've asked for a trade.'' Palffy, who has scored better
than 40 goals each of the last three seasons, is seeking a
three-year deal worth $6.8 million a year. The Isles reportedly
have countered with $4 million, $4.25 million, and $4.5 million.
Palffy remains at home in Slovakia, training with 15- and
16-year-old junior players ...  &UR; Pat Falloon &LR; , who was San Jose's
first choice (No. 2 overall behind  &UR; Eric Lindros &LR; ) in the 1991
draft, is hoping to revitalize his career in Edmonton. Falloon, 26,
who has played for the Sharks, Flyers, and Senators, went shopping
for a new team in the offseason when it was clear Ottawa had no
room for him. So far, it has worked out well with the Oilers. ``I
had some ups and downs,'' said Falloon. ``Some really good times
and some really tough times. Last year was tough for me. After
being traded from Philadelphia to Ottawa it was the toughest time
of my career. I was getting the opportunity to play, I was playing
quite a bit in Ottawa and just didn't score goals. Talk about being
snakebit. That was the toughest stretch I went through in my
career.'' His futility resulted in a stretch of eight goals in 58
games ... Once  &UR; Marty McSorley's  &LR; playing days are over, he might
have a career as an actor. He made his debut in the 1997 film ``Con
Air,'' which starred  &UR; Nicolas Cage &LR; . McSorley's part was, well,
small. And he got killed. He played a pilot who was flying a group
of violent criminals to a new prison but met with a violent end
himself. ``It was a great experience, a lot of fun,'' said
McSorley, who has shed plenty of blood for real as an enforcer
during his NHL career, which is entering its 16th year. The Oilers
defenseman was selected for the part after getting to know producer
 &UR; Jerry Bruckheimer  &LR; during his days with the Kings ... 105 days to
the All-Star Game.
</P>
</TEXT>
