<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--PADRES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Padres again dominate with stubborn pitching
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Believe it or not, these are the Atlanta Braves gasping
for life before your very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres all but pulled the plug Saturday with a 4-1
gut-check victory before a rowdy crowd of 62,779 at Qualcomm
Stadium. The Braves are not quite dead, but it wouldn't be a bad
idea to start notifying their next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have a commanding 3-0 lead in the best-of-seven
National League Championship Series and are just one victory shy of
winning their first NL pennant since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could ask for a better situation,'' Padres
manager Bruce Bochy said.
</P>
<P>
   Who said these guys can go only as far as Kevin Brown's mighty
right arm can take them? It doesn't seem to matter who the Padres
trot out to the mound; they just keep shutting down the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it was Sterling Hitchcock's turn to play enforcer. He
didn't have top-notch command, but his effort was good enough to
keep a lid on the Braves' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, who battled control problems most of the game,
scattered three hits in five innings and worked around five walks
for his second upset victory of the postseason. After beating Randy
Johnson and the Astros in the decisive game of the Division Series,
Hitchcock was ready for the challenge of facing Greg Maddux, who
couldn't overcome two fifth-inning runs and had no luck in
reversing the Braves' fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their pitching was just better than ours again,'' said Maddux,
who allowed five hits before being lifted for a pinch hitter with
the bases loaded in the sixth inning. ``We're down, but we're not
out.''
</P>
<P>
   A little optimism never hurt anyone, but the Braves will need
divine intervention from the baseball gods to dig themselves out of
this hole.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams _ the current Padres and the 1995 Braves _ have
held 3-0 leads in the NLCS, and no team in the history of baseball
has overcome a 3-0 deficit in any best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely do (believe the Braves can still win the
series),'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``We can win two here and
go back to our place. We could make it very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they should tackle a couple of smaller chores first:
getting hits and scoring runs. The Braves had only eight hits
Saturday, and they are hitting a weak .200 in the series. Their
combined run production in the three games? Three.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've shut us down completely,'' Cox said. ``We have good
matchups going into situations, and we can't smell a hit. Their
pitching is awfully strong, but we really have to hit in the
clutch. We can't leave the bases loaded every inning without doing
some damage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves loaded the bases three times Saturday and came up
empty every time. The most crucial instance was in the sixth inning
when Hitchcock issued a leadoff walk to Andres Galarraga, prompting
Bochy to summon former Astros righthander Donne Wall from the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Wall allowed a single to Andruw Jones and intentionally walked
pinch hitter Ryan Klesko after catcher Eddie Perez had put down a
sacrifice bunt. Klesko's walk loaded the bases, and then Wall got
tough. He struck out pinch hitters Michael Tucker and Greg Colbrunn
to escape the jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wall) was outstanding,'' Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart
said. ``He's been that way for us all year. I'll tell you what;
he's going to be a part of this staff as long as I'm coaching
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock retired five of the first six batters he faced, but
got himself into trouble by walking Tony Graffanino _ a .211 hitter
in the regular season _ to lead off the third inning. Graffanino
moved to second on a sacrifice bunt by Maddux and scored on Walt
Weiss' single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Great defensive plays by Padres reserves John Vander Wal and Jim
Leyritz prevented the Braves from scoring in the third. Weiss tried
to score from second on Chipper Jones' two-out single to left, but
Vander Wal made a perfect throw to the plate, and Leyritz held on
to the ball despite a collision with Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock reached on a one-out single in the fifth and scored on
Steve Finley's double into the left-field gap. Then Ken Caminiti
singled up the middle after Maddux had intentionally walked
eight-time batting champion Tony Gwynn to score Finley.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres added two runs in the eighth _ as if closer Trevor
Hoffman needed any insurance _ to end any hopes of the Braves
staging a comeback. Hoffman struck out three of the five batters he
faced and pushed the Braves one step closer to elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the playoffs,'' Braves center fielder Andruw Jones
said. ``Anything can happen, but we have to make some things
happen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Braves, they're running out of time.
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
