<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL MADDUX GETS PADRES HOT AT WRONG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - Mr. Cool, lost his cool.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the Atlanta Braves, the epitome of the
never-let'em-see-you-sweat corporate outfit, are just one game away
from starting their winter vacations far earlier than they ever
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Why, oh, why did Greg Maddux ever poke a stick into San Diego's
sleepy dugout in the bottom of the fourth inning? Maddux was the
losing pitcher in San Diego's 4-1 victory Saturday afternoon. His
National League Championship Series record is a very mortal 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, as composed as they come in this game, let Jim Leyritz
of all people, get under his skin in the bottom of the fourth
inning. Maddux became so agitated with Leyritz, he wound up
plunking him with the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made a habit of getting under people's skin,'' Leyritz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he stepped into the batter's box that inning, Leyritz
requested home-plate umpire Tom Hallion to check the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wiped under his cap and went to his mouth,'' Leyritz said
of Maddux. ``I just wanted the ball checked. Apparently, he took
offense to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's very first pitch to Leyritz sailed high and tight and
smacked him in the left shoulder. The two exchanged words, mostly
unprintable ones, as Leyritz walked toward first base.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, a four-time Cy Young Award winner, insisted the pitch
simply got away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to come in and it got away,'' Maddux said. ``I don't
care what (Leyritz) says. He didn't call the pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who could consistently hit a dime, anywhere you
place it, from 60-feet, 6 inches away. He had just retired seven
consecutive Padres when Leyritz stepped to the plate with two outs
and nobody on base at the time. John Vander Wal was due up next.
</P>
<P>
   An even more startling statistic: Maddux has hit a
preposterously tiny 0.01 percent _ and that's rounding up _ of the
11,517 batters he's faced in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nolan Ryan in his day, Maddux takes exception when an
opposing batter, especially one with a big mouth like Leyritz,
questions his actions. Ryan routinely hit batters if they asked for
the ball to be checked for possible cheating.
</P>
<P>
   The potential damage from hitting Leyritz was minimal.
Basically, Maddux let pride overtake his usually stoic and
deliberate manner.
</P>
<P>
   The wild and raucous crowd's volume level had come down a few
decibels. The Padres were slowly being put to sleep by Maddux's
pinpoint control and ever-effective changing of speeds.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Maddux had the Padres exactly where he wanted them,
especially considering he also had a 1-0 lead at the time and had
nearly set down the entire lineup in order before Leyritz's
prodding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he hit me it kind of ignited us,'' Leyritz said. ``It
excited us. We're a close team here. I know he did it on purpose.
If it had been during the regular season I wouldn't have been able
to finish the game. I'd have been at the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Vander Wal struck out looking and Maddux
needed only four pitches to put him away. You could almost sense
Maddux saying, ``All right, I'll hit this big mouth and get out of
the inning with Vander Wal. No big deal and maybe it'll shut this
guy up.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Maddux wasn't counting on the Padres banding together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great time for it to happen to us,'' said San Diego
center fielder Steve Finley. ``Anytime you get any extra incentive,
you take it.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego came up the next inning and scored twice, taking the
lead for good. Both runs scored after two outs. After each RBI hit
Maddux could be seen cussing and muttering to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leyritz came into the dugout screaming,'' said Padres third
baseman Ken Caminiti, whose fifth-inning single scored Finley with
the go-ahead run. ``I liked it. It lit me up. I think it got us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux can deny he hit Leyritz on purpose until the end of time.
The reality is that Maddux let his ego and pride get in the way of
what could have been Atlanta's turnaround game in this series.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the same Maddux and these certainly are not the same
Atlanta Braves, who are definitely perspiring right about now. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
