<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY BEATEN BY LONG SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
 CLUB-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's no such thing as a sure thing in horse
racing. In fact, there's no such thing as two sure things.
Saturday's $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup, the highlight of
Breeders' Cup Preview Day at Belmont Park, provided more evidence
as 34-1 shot ($70 to win) Wagon Limit blew past superstars
Gentlemen and Skip Away to triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions for a monumental upset were in place. The track,
officially labeled sloppy, was actually wet/fast and most of the
winners had shown early speed along the rail. When the gates opened
for the Gold Cup, Jerry Bailey, aboard prohibitive 1-5 favorite
Skip Away, and Corey Nakatani, aboard 2-1 second choice Gentlemen,
acted as if they were in a two-horse race, going head-to-head from
the outset. Meanwhile, Robbie Davis and Wagon Limit, who had won
one of nine races this year, were biding their time.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, who was on the inside, began to get away from Skip
Away turning for home and for an instant looked like a winner.
However, Wagon Limit came storming down the stretch to tally by 5
1/2 lengths in 2:003/5 for 1 1/4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd get a piece of the purse, especially with the
track the way he likes it,'' said Allen Jerkens, Wagon Limit's
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Jerkens, a Hall of Famer who twice engineered upsets of
Secretariat in 1973 (with Onion and Prove Out), had once again
spotted one of his charges perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skip Away did not run the way he has been running for some
reason,'' said Jerkens. ``Gentlemen had to do a lot to put away
Skip Away and that left it open for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, who had won the previous two Gold Cups, came in
riding a nine-race winning streak. He missed a chance to pass Cigar
in all-time earnings as the $110,000 for third left him at
$9,616,360 to Cigar's $9,999,815. Skip Away will get a last chance
to break the record in the Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs
Nov. 7. After that, the presumptive Horse of the Year, despite the
loss, will be retired to stud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually is smoking through the lane, but today he just
galloped home,'' said Bailey. ``He didn't run his race. He's
handled a wet track before. I can't blame the loss on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have put away the horse that is the one to beat, it's
real tough to get caught like we did and lose the race,'' said
Nakatani. ``I didn't want to give up any ground, but he started to
get in the deep going of the track. I couldn't move him out and the
winner just sat in a great spot and made his run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Hine, who trains Skip Away, checked him out after the race
and the big gray was doing well. ``He's very sound, but we found a
little filing in his leg,'' said Hine. ``At the moment, he's not
lame. We'll just have to wait and see. He might have jammed himself
a little in the race. Right now, he's walking fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This injury is cosmetic, believe me,'' said Jim Hunt, the
attending veterinarian. ``It looks a lot worse than it is. He
should be all right in a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Groom is Red, owned by Rick Pitino's Celtics Pride Stable
and trained by Nick Zito, came out of the clouds with Corey
Nakatani aboard to take the $400,000 Champagne Stakes for
2-year-old colts.
</P>
<P>
   Running against the grain of the track, which had favored speed
all day, The Groom is Red came from last to prevail by 2 3/4
lengths in 1:424/5 for 11/16 miles. Pitino was on hand and led the
horse into the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   The Groom is Red, who was more than 15 lengths behind down the
backstretch, was 6-1 and returned $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was way out in the back, I was a bit nervous,'' said
Pitino. ``But to see him coming around the way he did was
unbelievable. It was such an exciting moment. All I can say is that
I'm a very lucky man and I'm having a great ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito indicated that The Groom is Red, who has won three in a
row, would start next in the $1 million Breeders' Cup Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sharp Cat ran her season record to 4 for 4 with an easy tally in
the $400,000 Beldame Stakes for fillies and mares. Ridden by
Nakatani, Sharp Cat simply ran away from her opponents, scoring by
11 lengths in 1:461/5 for 1 1/8 miles. Off at 2-5, Sharp Cat,
trained by Wally Dollase, returned $2.90 ... There was an upset in
the $400,000 Frizette Stakes for 2-year-old fillies as Confessional
defeated 2-5 choice Things Change. Ridden by Jerry Bailey,
Confessional romped to a 10 1/2-length victory in 1:424/5 for 11/16
miles. Off at 6-1, Confessional, trained by Bill Mott, paid $14.40
... Buck's Boy, the 7-5 pick ($4.90 to win), went wire to wire over
1 1/2 miles to capture the $500,000 Turf Classic by 3 lengths under
Shane Sellers. Trained by Noel Hickey, Buck's Boy prevailed by a
comfortable margin despite Sellers dropping his whip in midstretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
