<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0548 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-NBA-LOCKOUT-A     10-11 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NBA-LOCKOUT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT GIVES NHL A HEAD START  
 BUT HOCKEY SAYS IT WON'T BE A VULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockout? What NBA lockout?
</P>
<P>
   The NHL season opens in Phoenix tonight, and Shawn Hunter said
it will be business as usual for his Coyotes, who are trying to
skate their way into the Valley's heart.
</P>
<P>
   The hockey players undoubtedly will enjoy being the only active
pro sport tenants at America West Arena, where the team landed
three seasons ago after emigrating from Winnipeg, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's Phoenix Suns won't be around to steal their thunder.
</P>
<P>
   But fans like Sheila Howard, who regularly attends Suns and
Coyotes games, will feel the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I'll have some place to go watch (sports),'' Howard
said. ``I may not have my Suns, but I know I'll have my Coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, the Coyotes president, said, ``We might fill an
entertainment void for some people, and by that, I mean we might
win over some Suns fans who haven't been to a Coyotes game before.
But we're certainly not counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   No NBA can only help the NHL, right? Like it or not, isn't it
perfect timing for a Canadian-born sport that still is trying to
establish itself in many U.S. markets, still has to explain its
quirky rules to first-time fans, and long has been considered No. 4
among the four major professional sports?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no question about it,'' superstar center Mike Modano of
the Dallas Stars said. ``You hate to see a work stoppage in any
sport, but how can it not help the NHL? You'd just naturally assume
we're going to attract a lot more fans this year if there's no
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter emphasized that the Coyotes will not try to profit from
the NBA's misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're plowing ahead without even thinking about the NBA,'' he
said. ``Their situation isn't a positive for us. If anything, it
can have a negative impact on us and the other teams because it's a
potential black eye for all the pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope each year more and more people will get a chance to
see us, and that's probably the greatest challenge. But we're still
only 2{ years old. We have very high expectations to be a leader
quickly, but sometimes you have to practice a little bit of
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman indicated the league has no plans
to do anything different. There will be no massive marketing
campaign, no tactically increased advertising revenues, no extra
hawking of NHL merchandise, no parading star players around cities
that house both NHL and NBA franchises.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bettman, the NHL is fine the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great game that, when people pay attention to it, we
think sells itself,'' Bettman said. ``We are just going to continue
to do our own thing. We think labor unrest is bad for all the
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes' season ticket holder William K. Smith of Phoenix can't
believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's really the case, then they're totally missing the
boat,'' Smith said. ``They have a tremendous opportunity here to
market the game like never before. I'm not saying they have to act
like a vulture and pick on the bones of the NBA, but for heaven's
sake, don't they realize what they're missing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, some hockey markets really could use the extra
attention. Especially the new cities like Carolina and Nashville,
which I'm not sure are ready for the NHL. I'm not worried about
Phoenix. This is a great hockey town, going all the way back to
1967 with the old Phoenix Roadrunners. But come on, Bettman can't
really be serious when he says they're going to do nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne, a star forward for the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim,
agrees with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we had our lockout (in 1994-95), a lot of
hockey fans went to basketball. I think this is a chance for hockey
to show to other fans that we have a great sport, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of fans out there that still haven't been
reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing research by the Coyotes a year ago is proof. Surveys
showed that 30 percent of all fans who went to a Coyotes game at
America West Arena were attending their first NHL game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an exciting, very positive statistic,'' Hunter said.
``It tells us we're still in the phase of introducing ourselves to
the marketplace. We're trying to grow our fan base one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes enjoyed an 85 percent season ticket renewal rate
after last season and this year will continue programs designed to
make the team a greater part of the community. The Coyotes:
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor a popular weeklong street hockey event in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Conduct frequent ice hockey clinics and make countless
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Hold their annual Family Carnival in the spring, which drew a
crowd of almost 50,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Pleased fans by not raising ticket prices for this season's
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, a former executive vice president of the NBA's Denver
Nuggets and before that, a corporate account executive for the
NBA's Minnesota Timberwolves, agrees with Bettman's tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never allow external forces we can't control affect how
we control our own business and how we market it.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL players, however, from superstars Modano and teammate Brett
Hull, to Selanne and teammate Paul Kariya, said hockey is losing
out if it doesn't act fast and gain whatever it can by entering a
season without any head-to-head competition with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good opportunity for us,'' Kariya said. ``The NBA
has done exceptionally well in the past five, six years, and we had
a lot of momentum going for us until we had our lockout. We were
really gaining, I think, but then we lost it. Maybe this will bring
back that momentum we had.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' Jeremy Roenick, though, said the NHL/NBA lockout
connection may be overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lockout's not going to affect us,'' Roenick said. ``Our
sport, I think is doing just fine. Sure, it's not great for them.
But how does it help us?''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter only can think of one way it could help the Coyotes,
whether the NBA season is canceled or not. It has to do with 4,300
sight-obstructed seats for Coyotes' games at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a nice season to have full-court hockey,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
