<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCONN-HOFSTRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WINS, BUT LOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ When can you consider a victory over a ranked
opponent a loss? When you lose your star quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to the University of Connecticut Saturday
as it upended Hofstra, 40-18, at soggy Memorial Stadium for its
fourth victory in five games. It was billed as a matchup between
Division 1-AA powers, Hofstra (13th) and UConn (25th) each ranked
in the national polls. Both had record-setting quarterbacks, and
Shane Stafford and Giovanni Carmazzi were supposed to have a
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood of the 4,476 on hand turned as dark as the clouds
that hovered over the stadium as Stafford exited with a broken
right collarbone and damaged shoulder late in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   However, the loss of Stafford had a profound effect on his
teammates, who took their game to another level.
</P>
<P>
   The injury sparked a 24-point outburst in the second quarter
that put the game away. ``I thought a lot of people played well,''
said UConn (4-1) coach Skip Holtz. ``Not just the offense. The
defense kept Hofstra out of the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flying Dutchmen piled up a lot of yards, but interceptions
by Percy Price, Jordan Younger, Eric Younger, and Ron Gamble killed
any chance of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford's replacement, sophomore Brian Hoffman (9 for 17, 141
yards, 1 TD) did a solid job, directing the Huskies to a 31-6
halftime advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But it got close. Carmazzi (30 for 53, 306 yards) hit Charlie
Adams with a 46-yard TD strike to cut UConn's lead to 4.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hoffman drove the Huskies on a nine-play, 66-yard drive
capped by a 1-yard plunge by Chad Martin to give UConn a
comfortable margin. After Jordan Younger's 24-yard TD interception
return, Mike Burton finished off Hofstra before the half ended by
scoring on an 8-yard pass from Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian did a pretty good job. He missed a few reads, but he
really hasn't had enough reps in practice,'' said Holtz of his
sophomore quarterback from Orlando, Fla. ``We didn't see any point
to putting him in the pocket, we ran a pretty basic game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra worked its run-and-shoot, which averages 40 points per
game, in the second half, but the defense held. The Dutchmen's
final two drives ended with interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss and we have no excuses,'' said Hofstra coach
Joe Gardi. ``UConn whipped us in just about every category. We were
outcoached and outplayed.''
</P>
<P>
   But what was impressive was that UConn did it without Stafford.
How good is he? Just 24 hours earlier he was named to UConn's 100th
anniversary all-time team. The honor is deserved. Stafford was on a
pace to complete his collegiate career ranked in the top two on
UConn's all-time list in practically every QB category. Breaking
records has been the usual for Stafford, who broke most of the
marks set by Kerry Collins at the Wilson School in West Lawn, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford, who started 34 straight games, was hurt late in the
first quarter. After rolling to the left on a play-action pass, he
was pounded as he waited until the last possible moment to toss a
46-yard completion to Carl Bond that set up a field goal and gave
the Huskies a 10-0 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Stafford gave UConn its first points when he connected
on a 45-yard strike to John Fitzsimmoms. It was the 30th straight
game Stafford completed a pass of 35 yards or longer and the 17th
straight game he had a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors are saying it will be 4-6 weeks before he is
back,'' said Holtz. ``Shane says two weeks. Of course I'm going to
go with what the doctors say, but I'm not going to bet against
Shane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
