<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEUD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW WORK FOR COUNTY ATTORNEY, SHERIFF TAKES BACK SEAT TO FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 and DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick doesn't like the way Joe runs his jails.
</P>
<P>
   Joe says Rick is just jealous because people like him better.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is mad because he thinks Rick snitched on him to Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Rick is upset because Joe accused him of being a lousy lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes in the political sand-kicking between the
Valley's two top law officers, Sheriff Joe Arpaio and County
Attorney Richard Romley.
</P>
<P>
   For five years they've been at each other's throats, publicly
and privately sabotaging one another with venomous determination.
But the feud boiled over last week following recent clashes over
the arrest of a hairdresser, a postal worker pepper-spraying a dog,
and a plan to bust people who steal off-road vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the latest episodes in a soap-operatic feud between
two elected officials who not only wield tremendous power but also
are among Arizona's most influential politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio, a former Drug Enforcement Administration special agent
turned travel agent, won election after his predecessor was accused
of badly botching an investigation into the massacre of nine people
at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   Romley, an Arizona native and ex-Marine who lost both legs above
the knee in Vietnam, first took office as county attorney nearly 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both are aggressive crime fighters and savvy politicians who are
adept at using the media.
</P>
<P>
   Both grant that the public is the big loser in their fight.
</P>
<P>
   But neither will back down.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the sheriff sat in his downtown Phoenix office and
erupted at the mention of Romley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's jealousy!'' Arpaio said loudly. ``The polls always have
me at an 80 or 90 percent approval rating. The polls don't even
show he is respected by the voters!''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, on another day, Romley countered: ``Joe takes
everything personally. But also, I'm not sure Joe understands the
law or knows a great deal about law enforcement. When was his last
major case?
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has are gimmicks: pink underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Other law-enforcement officials want no part of this fight,
declining to be quoted. Privately, however, they say Arpaio vs.
Romley is a big, embarrassing distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obsessed with each other,'' said one top law officer.
``They can't even be in the same room together. . . . The problem
is, they don't trust each other.''
</P>
<P>
   One example: Arpaio, who has been besieged with death threats in
the past year, asked Attorney General Grant Woods to investigate
rather than Romley, who would normally take the case.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from isolated cases, insiders say the conflict has not
deterred sheriff's deputies and county prosecutors from cooperating
to catch and convict criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mary Rose Wilcox said Arpaio and Romley have great
staffs, and the bosses' quibbling doesn't filter into day-to-day
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both really good people,'' Wilcox added. ``It's sad
that they can't seem to get along. But it doesn't seem to effect
their work.'' &QL; 
BONES OF CONTENTION
</P>
<P>
   Flash points between Romley and Arpaio have ranged from trivial
to serious:
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the sheriff announced he was going to ``surround the
county'' with roadblocks and search vehicles for drugs. Romley
publicly denounced the plan as unconstitutional, forcing the Arpaio
to back off.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1996, Romley called for a state audit of the sheriff's Jail
Enhancement Fund based on allegations of inappropriate spending.
Among other things, Romley said Arpaio should not have used $39,000
for private legal counsel to sue the Board of Supervisors over his
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio suggests that Romley ratted on him to the U.S. Justice
Department, prompting a two-year investigation of alleged inmate
abuse and civil-rights violations in Maricopa County jails. That
case ended this year with a settlement between Arpaio and the U.S.
Attor ney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Romley believes Arpaio's inves tigators bungled the probe into
the 1996 death of jail inmate Scott Norberg. Arpaio accuses Romley
of delaying resolution of an investiga tion into Norberg's death.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff claims that an inves tigative staff at Romley's
office constitutes a force of ``secret po lice.'' But Romley said
his investi gators do such work as looking into actions by other
law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   He also says Romley endangered law officers with critical
comments in a radio interview during a 1996 riot in the Tent City
jail.
</P>
<P>
   _Romley criticized Arpaio after the case of military impostor
David Michael Pecard, who had deserted the Army and was arrested in
1996 after conning his way into the Sheriff's Office. Charges
against Pecard were dismissed because sher iff's officers violated
his civil rights in Tent City by eavesdropping on phone
conversations with his lawyer. &QL; 
Petty issues
</P>
<P>
   While those disputes involve major issues, the conflicts have
grown increasingly petty.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, after Arpaio and a top aide got into a fight
with an intoxicated hairdresser, the sher iff said he couldn't rely
on Romley for ``fair and impartial prosecu tion.'' He tried to get
the county attorney to withdraw, but Romley refused.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Arpaio announced plans to pull over off-road vehicles
in an effort to stop a spree of theft. Romley's office promptly
declared the idea unconstitutional: ``The answer is no,'' said
spokesman Bill FitzGerald. ``You can't just pull over vehicles for
random searches.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley also irked the sheriff by refusing to file animal-cruelty
charges against mailman Wayne Bates for using pepper spray on a
fenced dog. Arpaio, who had used Bates' arrest as an opportunity to
publicize his pet-protecting posse, was livid.
</P>
<P>
   So was his publicity director, Lisa Allen. ``This man Romley!''
she fumed. ``He won't prosecute Bates because it will make Sheriff
Arpaio look good. But he'll take cases . . . where he hopes Sheriff
Arpaio will look like a big creep.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at his office, Romley sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This dog case, I mean _ Let it go, Joe! Yes, I think the
mailman overreacted, but to put him in jail? Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the conflict seems to involve a question of allegiance.
``The county attorney is supposed to be my attorney,'' Arpaio says.
``But he has been unethical and is always critical of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Arpaio's office filed a state Bar complaint against
Rom ley, accusing him of a ``blatant conflict of interest'' because
he continually spoke out against sher iff's employees.
</P>
<P>
   Romley, whose credits include the AzScam political-corruption
sting and his order to release four Tucson men falsely accused of
the Buddhist temple murders, said he is confident the complaint
will be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not his personal attorney. I have an obligation to speak
out when I see problems, and he's trying to muzzle me with this,
and I refuse to be,'' Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dispute arises from problems in the Maricopa County
jail system.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio says Romley publicly un dercut him during the riots two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was being interviewed on KTAR during the riot, and he
couldn't even wait until after the riot to get me,'' Arpaio said.
``. . . I think it's almost criminal what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley's explanation: ``I was on the radio, and when they asked
me about the situation I said we in law enforcement have been
concerned about the jails. I wasn't trying to make it more
difficult for the sheriff, just to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley said he believes the riot was started ``by a guard who
overreacted with a prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Aide Barnett Lotstein added: ``The guard pepper sprayed a guy
who was on the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the sheriff's complaints about Romley's legal work,
Romley said, ``We are the people's lawyer, not Joe Arpaio's lawyer.
He doesn't understand the role of the county attorney. I don't work
for him. I work for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   While the sheriff and prosecutors shoot it out, other law
officers steer clear of cross fire.
</P>
<P>
   One, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said, ``As long as Joe
is in there you will see problems between his outfit and other
agencies: He just marches to a different drummer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another noted that Romley wields considerable power. ``Every
agency wants to have a good working relationship with Romley's
office. I can't imagine them fooling with our lower-level cases.
But if they are angry at you, they could scrutinize reports to
death, nitpick them to the nth degree, beyond what is reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio and Romley agree on one thing: The 1996 death of inmate
Norberg marked the end of their cordiality. A drug user who was
arrested for assault, Norberg suffocated during a scuffle with
guards in the Madison Street Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the relationship with Joe began to break with the
issue of brutality in the jails,'' Romley said. ``I was getting a
dozen letters a week with specific examples of brutality. We had
video tapes. I prosecuted several of his detention officers. Then,
with the Norberg incident, the problems elevated to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   ``His investigation co-mingled a criminal investigation with an
internal investigation, and was poorly done.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arpaio aide Jack MacIntyre said there was no mixing of
internal and a criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation wasn't either of those things,'' MacIntyre
said. ``It was what we call a `critical incident investigation.'
There was no indication of criminal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley had refused to close the Norberg investigation until a
$30 million civil suit filed by family members was resolved. Last
week, with the case still pending, he decided to open a criminal
investigation of detention officers. Arpaio was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in two and a half years has not one of my employees been
cleared in the Norberg case?'' asked the sheriff. ``How long must
this take?''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio also suspects Romley of treachery in the 1995 jail
investigation by the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust him,'' Arpaio said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking dramatically toward the ceiling, he added, ``Now, who
asked the Justice Department to come in?'' The sheriff shrugged,
then smiled knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre said, ``When the Department of Justice looked at the
jails there was supposed to be an attorney-client relationship
between Romley's office and us. But Romley handed out copies of
that report like a deck of cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Jesus H. Christ!'' Arpaio said, jumping up and
thrusting his arms into the air. ``Romley has his own secret police
force! He has 60 of his own investigators! He even changed their
badges so it says Maricopa County Attorney's Police Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley said he has investigators to follow up on police work _
and to investigate law enforcement agencies, including the
Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not above the law, and every time I raise an issue that
perhaps he doesn't like, he says it's just a pissing match,''
Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said he's getting weary of Arpaio's anger, ``his hunger
for publicity,'' his charges. But not especially surprised, because
there were hints early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago I got a flavor of what it would be like with Joe
when he wanted to surround the county with law officers and stop
every third car and look for drugs,'' Romley said. ``It definitely
would have violated the Constitution. I told him he couldn't do it,
and he got very mad.''
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre said ``the tragedy of this thing'' is that relations
between the two agencies are so bad that the public is being poorly
served.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the threat of prosecution being dangled over detention
officers in the Norberg case, with investigators being smeared by
Romley, it does nothing for a sense of trust between the two
offices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Romley insists that most business between the two agencies is
going on very well. But he also said he won't back down in the face
of an angry Arpaio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Joe exceeds or misuses his power I'm going to call him on
it,'' Romley said. ``Joe is not going to bully me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
