<HEADLINE>
FROGS' PAST DEFEATS JUST FADE TO BLACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All I want for Christmas, Coach Fran, is my
own black shirt.
</P>
<P>
   You know, one of those black jerseys that turns Frogs into
princes.
</P>
<P>
   Or losers into winners. Yeah, that's even better.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be the shirts, right? How else to explain the
phenomenon of TCU being 4-1 as you wake up on this bright and sunny
fall Sunday morning?
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, rub your eyes and read it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four-and-one!''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, they're still celebrating in College Station and the road
from Dallas to Austin is bathed in an orange glow, but nobody in
college football is any happier today _ or any more joyously
stunned _ than the folks in Frogland.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's 21-10 victory over Fresno State at Amon Carter
Stadium quadrupled the Frogs' victory total over last season.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't sit around and think we were going to be 4-and-1
at this point in time,'' first-year Frogs coach Dennis Franchione
admitted with a rueful grin, after the Frogs had rallied in the
fourth quarter to defeat the visiting Bulldogs. ``But I believe it
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is a lot mental.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the black shirts come in, of course. It's a mental
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line TCU supporters still cringe at the idea of the Frogs
wearing black jerseys and leggings with their purple pants. Why,
it's a complete break with tradition, they sputter.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   It ain't 1950 any more, sports fans. Frogs' football tradition
hasn't been much to brag about since the 1984 season went spiraling
down that cesspool of scandal and NCAA gumshoes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last year? It was a 1-10 disaster, you may recall.
Saturday after Saturday, after another late-game collapse, poor Pat
Sullivan would wander off into the night, mumbling about his team
just having to learn how to win.
</P>
<P>
   What the Frogs needed was someone who could first teach them how
to compete until the clock read 0:00.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is, I don't talk to them a lot about
winning,'' Franchione said. ``I don't put pressure on them about
that. I talk to them about playing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys know that if don't play our guts out, if we don't
play hard on every play, we're just another ballclub. Right now,
we're doing that as well as anyone in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione, a proven master at turning programs around,
understood immediately that his first challenge at TCU was to work
on his players' heads and hearts before he worried about blocking
schemes or their times in the 40.
</P>
<P>
   He brings the ability to motivate, to deal with problems, to
recognize what needs to be said and to say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious when I got here that the team had a low
confidence level and low self-esteem,'' Franchione said. ``I told
them that the most important player in a football game is the next
one. That's the motto we live by.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've kind of quit looking at the scoreboard and just
played. We talk a lot about passion, now, how you have to have a
deep emotional feeling, a thirst for something. How bad do you want
to be 4-and-1?''
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough to shrug off the kind of bad breaks and letdowns that
would have buried last season's team.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs trailed, 10-7, as the final period began last night,
but this TCU team has made a habit of making the fourth quarter its
own this season. Instead of panicking or just flat quitting, as
they surely would have a year ago, the Frogs found a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   LaDainian Tomlinson took an option pitch from quarterback
Patrick Batteaux, the converted wide receiver, cut inside two
Fresno State defenders and raced 33 yards for the go-ahead
touchdown on the Frogs' first drive of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth-and-three, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   Will miracles never cease?
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, cornerback Kendrick Patterson scooped up a fumble
by Fresno State tight end Scott Thompson _ replays showed he
probably should have been ruled down _ and returned it 29 yards for
the clinching TD.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the kinds of plays that always seemed to go against
the Frogs over the past 20 years, give or take a decade or two.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a disappointment, it was that the Frogs continue to
play in relative anonymity. Only 28,013 fans showed up, despite a
conveniently early 6:05 kickoff, the third consecutive home crowd
under 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it may take a while to make believers out of all the
skeptics. Cynicism tends to pile up after a while, like leaves gone
long unraked.
</P>
<P>
   But believe. The Frogs are 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   There's a rumor that Coach Fran even has a black shirt that'll
fit you, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
