A0552 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX     10-11 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HULL, DEFENSE IS ANOTHER GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Brett Hull gained a souvenir in his first regular
season-game with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bucket full of hats for scoring three times. Not even a
puck from his first goal with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   No, Hull's souvenir was something he's just as soon do without.
He sported a big red gash on his chin, courtesy of a high stick
late in the second period that took three or four stitches to
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a part of the game I like,'' Hull said. ``I have a
hard enough time looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock disagreed. Even though the
15th-leading goal scorer in NHL history did not put the puck in the
net, and even though he got the cut on the chin, Hitchcock said
Hull looked very good in the Stars' 4-1 victory last night against
the Buffalo Sabres at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did some really good things,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Like playing defense.
</P>
<P>
   That's a must in Hitchcock's system, and when the Stars signed
Hull to a big-money, free-agent contract some wondered if Hull
would buy into it.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't fly all over the ice hitting people, Hull
ably handled that part of the game. He blocked a shot and had two
takeaways, including one in the Stars' defense zone when he hustled
back and took the puck from Miroslav Satan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brett Hull can play both ways,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's very
capable. He knows when he has to come back, and he knows how to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, Hull said. Defense? Of course I play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the game is now,'' he said. ``You've got to
play defense to create more chances offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Hull earns the big bucks, though, is on offense. And while
he didn't score, there's nothing wrong with that part of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Hull took six shots, the most on the team. A couple of them were
slap shots right on goal, but they were stopped by Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lots of chances, and couldn't buy one,'' he said. ``I'm
always trying hard to get one, but they don't always go in.''
</P>
<P>
   He did get an assist, though, when linemate Mike Modano scored
off a rebound from one of Hull's shots.
</P>
<P>
   What might have been his best play of the night involved neither
offense nor defense, but rather acting skills. Hull went down after
minimal contact in front of the net _ some might have called it
taking a dive _ midway through the second period, drawing a penalty
and a power play. Pat Verbeek converted with a goal that made it
2-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
