<HEADER>
A0553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NORTHEASTERN-VILL     10-11 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHEASTERN-VILLANOVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLEMIC MAKES FAST WORK OF VILLANOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Move over 'Nova. Make room for Dave Klemic.
</P>
<P>
   Klemic, the Northeastern wide receiver who is a blur to
defenders, caught three touchdown passes Saturday, equaling the
Huskies career mark with 19. And he's only a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Klemic's heroics, plus some great plays by linebackers Brian
Hayden and Zach Falconer, tackle Pat Auguste, and defensive backs
Jabari Powell and Andre Dixon, highlighted the Huskies' eighth
straight home victory, over No. 11 Villanova, 28-17.
</P>
<P>
   All the Huskies' 28 points at rainy Parsons Field came in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Klemic, the slim (6 feet, 171 pounds) and bubbly player from
Somers Point, N.J., smiled and said, ``Hey, those were neat passes.
I just had to be there to catch them.'' Klemic grabbed two from
Fred Vallett and one from Jason Quinlan in tying Jeremy Gobeil
(1990-1993), on the Huskies' all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klemic never ceases to amaze me,'' said NU coach Barry Gallup.
``He just gets the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   New England hasn't been kind to Villanova (3-3) this season.
Last Saturday, ranked fourth nationally, the Wildcats visited
Orono, Maine, and were shocked, 44-10. You can believe they are not
looking forward to visiting UMass-Amherst next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very important game for us,'' said Gallup. ``We
lost close conference games to William and Mary (24-21) and
Delaware (27-20) and now we're 2-2 in the Atlantic 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good football. The guys are focused and they are
not in awe of any opponent. I feel when you believe in yourself you
play better, and we as a team certainly believe we can beat any
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, believe me, Villanova is a very good team with good
coaching and talented players. But we're improving too. We were
missing some key people and still got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (4-2) scored 43 seconds into the second when
redshirt freshman L.J. McKanas of Saugus scored from the 2 to cap a
seven-play, 36-yard drive. Joe Connolly's point-after try was wide
right. The drive started when Hayden recovered a 'Nova fumble and
returned it 22 yards to the Wildcat 36.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies got a major break moments later when Auguste tipped
and intercepted a 'Nova pass and returned it to the 23. On the
first play from scrimmage, Quinlan tossed a 23-yard pass to the
streaking Klemic in the right corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Then Quinlan hit Klemic for a 2-point conversion and a 14-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies made it 21-0 at 11:47 when Vallett and Klemic hooked
up on a 72-yard play. The defenders just couldn't cope with
Klemic's speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klemic gives us a dimension you have to have to win a big
game,'' said Gallup. ``He's a big-play player.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanova finally scored at 13:03 when Chris Boden tossed a
short over-the-middle pass to impressive Brian Westwood, and he
scooted to a 37-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play from scrimmage following the 'Nova kickoff
Vallett lobbed a 33-yard pass to the streaking Klemic for another
score, and NU was ahead, 28-7. Said Vallett, ``Dave makes you feel
comfortable. Just throw it in his direction and he'll catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Hannon hit a 41-yard field goal at 14:41 for Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats showed poise in the third quarter when they put
together a 13-play, 92-yard drive that ended with a 6-yard pass
from Boden to Murle Sango. Boden connected on 26- and 20-yard
passes on the drive. That cut NU's margin to 28-17, but that's how
it stayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
