<SLUG> BC-FBC-KANSAS-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR RALLIES, HOLDS OFF KANSAS, 31-24
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Baylor continued this year's theme of fantastic
finishes. Only this time, it was the Bears who pulled victory from
the jaws of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Looking sluggish while trailing throughout most of the second
half, Baylor rallied for 17 unanswered points in the fourth quarter
to eke past the Kansas Jayhawks, 31-24, last night before 31,271 at
Floyd Casey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor tailback Darrell Bush snapped a 24-all tie when he
scooted into the end zone from the 1-yard line with 49 seconds
remaining to cap a huge comeback by the Bears (2-3, 1-2 Big 12).
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (2-4, 0-4) had one last shot, and eventually moved to the
Baylor 35. But Nikia Codie intercepted Zac Wegner's pass at the
2-yard line with 21 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came alive right there at the end,'' Baylor coach Dave
Roberts said. ``The effort was incredible, and I'm very proud of
the kids to win this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to the guys and we told them this game was going to
be just like last week and the week before, and to let's just get
it to the last four minutes. We made a play when we had to do it,
and our defense made a play when they had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor dropped a 31-29 decision at Texas Tech last week. Two
weeks ago, the Bears lost an 18-16 heartbreaker at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this win,'' Bears split end Morris Anderson said.
``We can't afford to lose any more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush rushed for 133 yards on 24 carries. Besides his winning
touchdown, Bush set the four-play, 90-yard winning drive in motion
when, on first down from his 10, he ran 70 electrifying yards
before being chased out of bounds at the Kansas 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been running that play throughout the whole game, and
we were being patient about it,'' Bush said. ``Then in the last
minute of the ballgame it opened up for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get up field as fast as I could, and then I looked
around and saw (Kansas defensive back Jahmal Wright.) So, I just
ran out of bounds because I didn't want to waste any more energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Termaine Fulton snagged a 27-yard touchdown from Wegner with
2:19 left in the third quarter as the Jayhawks rolled to a 24-14
lead. But the Bears found some spark in the fourth quarter, and
sent Kansas home pondering that final-quarter collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a tough one,'' Kansas coach Terry Allen said.
``I don't really know what to say, except I think we let Baylor off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit the two big plays in the fourth quarter, and that was
really disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor quarterback Jermaine Alfred, starting his first game of
the season, fired a 19-yard TD to Derek Lagway as the Bears got
within 24-21 with 13:47 remaining in the game. Matt Bryant's
42-yard field goal with 3:50 left tied it at 24.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Bears' last-second theatrics, which Baylor hopes
to repeat next week when they play host to Texas A&AMP;M. Yesterday,
the Aggies upset No. 2 Nebraska, 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys to get used to this feeling, because we're
going to do it against next week,'' said Anderson, who caught five
passes for a career-high 147 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Rubin gave Baylor a 7-0 lead when he picked up a fumble
by Kansas punter Matt Tyler and raced 27 yards to score late in the
first quarter. After Roberts replaced Alfred with Odell James
midway through the second quarter, the momentum went the Jayhawks'
way.
</P>
<P>
   Touchdowns by Wegner and Mitch Bowles pushed Kansas ahead 14-7.
But the Bears knotted it early in the third quarter when Alfred
found Anderson for a 35-yard TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boosts our ego a lot,'' Bush said. ``Tonight, we're going
to go out and have a good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
