<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TOCCHET11-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOCCHET IS COYOTES' MAGIC INGREDIENT  
 WARRIOR STABILIZES TEAM CHEMISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This is what you need to know about the impact Rick
Tocchet has on the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he scribbled a note on the team chalkboard inside the
locker room, inviting anyone who was interested to jot down their
names and join him at his house later that night to watch ``Monday
Night'' ``Football''.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, over the next couple hours, the list began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Q'' _ defenseman Deron Quint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rat'' _ center Cliff Ronning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Izzy'' _ left wing Brad Isbister.
</P>
<P>
   The RSVPs kept rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kong'' _ right wing Jim Cummins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus'' _ left wing Greg Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erkel'' _ defenseman Jyrki Lumme.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, every age group, personality, nationality, bank
account and social status seemed to be represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oley'' _ defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``JR'' _ center Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walt'' _ left wing Keith Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   And a dozen others.
</P>
<P>
   Who said the Coyotes have no chemistry or team unity? Who said
they are a bunch of individuals running around in their own select
cliques? Who said they can't all just get along?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a lot of the Coyotes said it themselves each of the
past two seasons. Privately, it was one of their biggest
complaints. But slowly, those concerns faded like a cheap dashboard
during the Arizona summer.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the credit has to go to Tocchet, the 34-year-old
warrior who is entering his second season in Phoenix. Everyone
agreed a change was needed and that they had to do it together. But
Tocchet, perhaps more than anyone, took the bull by the horns and
ran it headfirst into the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Little things, like inviting the team over to his house to watch
a football game _ and everyone showing up _ have made a world of
difference for the Coyotes as they prepare to open the 1998-99 NHL
season today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that can go a long
</P>
<P>
   way,'' Tocchet said. ``I just remember my first eight years in
Philadelphia, we had a real close team, and we were real
successful. Same thing in Pittsburgh. We were a very close team,
and we won a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think everybody's got to love each other, but
everybody's got to have respect for each other, and when you have
that, it brings good team chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet was one of the first players to openly criticize the
club for not having much of it. After the Coyotes were eliminated
last season in the opening round of the playoffs for the third
straight year and the 11th time in 13 trips to the postseason, he
questioned the leadership in the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including Tkachuk, the team's captain, perceived that as a
direct knock on Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Walt was (mad) about it, but I had a long talk with
him, and I laid it out on the line to him,'' Tocchet said. ``What I
told him I meant was, one guy can't do it alone. Leadership isn't
just one guy. It takes everybody. Everybody's got to help each
other and be there for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   After 14 NHL seasons, which also included stops in Los Angeles,
Boston and Washington, Tocchet has always been there for his
teammates. Whoever they happen to be. Wherever they happen to hail
from. Whenever they happen to need it.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't afraid to pull a player aside and tell them what he
thinks. He's done it with Mario Lemieux. He's done it with Wayne
Gretzky. He's done it with Roenick and Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing with Toc is he just wants to win,'' Coyotes
defenseman Gerald Diduck said. ``But it's not so much just the game
he wants to win, he wants to win every single, one-on-one battle
that he has, no matter what it is. Whether it's having to put your
head down after a two-minute shift and backcheck, you see him and
he's doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet isn't alone, of course. He looked around the locker room
and said others are just as committed and intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dally Drake is the same way. So is JR and Walt and Teppo
Numminen,'' Tocchet said. ``We all talk about it. We all believe in
the same things. Most of the guys in this room do. And as good as
it is now, it's only going to get better. Actually, it got a lot
better last year after Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet credits the coaching staff of Jim Schoenfeld and
assistants John Tortorella and Gordie Roberts for allowing the
players to air their opinions and offer feedback, whether it's on
the ice or off. During a recent practice, for instance, Schoenfeld
stopped the workout and circled the group for some dialogue about
the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet quickly chirped in and had everyone's full attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good relationship with a guy like Oleg
(Tverdovsky),'' Tocchet said, ``and I tell him, `You have to have
input. Don't be afraid to talk. You're a big part of the power
play. You're the quarterback out there. You have to tell people
what to do sometimes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What I try to do with a guy like Oley or guys like Izzy or
Doaner (Shane Doan) is tell them there's nothing that says you have
to be a rookie or a first-year player or a young guy. . . . I'm not
a big believer in telling a guy, `You gotta do it this way because
I've won the Stanley Cup.' That doesn't mean you know everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, although it's worth pointing out that Tocchet is the
only player on the Coyotes' roster to have ever hoisted Lord
Stanley's holy grail over his head. In addition o 909 NHL games,
385 goals, 821 points and 2,626 penalty minutes, the seventh most
in league history, the man has clout.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't stop during the off-season, either. He joined the
likes of Isbister and Roenick in the Los Angeles area this past
summer by participating in the much-publicized off-ice training
program of T.R. Goodman for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of Rick Tocchet,'' teammate Cliff Ronning said,
``I think of the true professional athlete, from his training to
his desire to win to his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet doesn't wear a letter on his chest, designating him as a
captain or an assistant. He doesn't have to. And he doesn't
necessarily want to. Tkachuk is the captain. Roenick and Numminen
are the assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to help,'' said Tocchet, ``I don't know how much
longer I've got left, and the main thing is I want to play at a
high level. Mike Keenan was good at getting guys to a different
level. That's what Shoney's doing right now. That's what this
team's got to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, you have to pound that into yourself and into the
team. If there's a guy who's not willing to do that, and he's just
constantly going against what the team is trying to do, then
something's got to be done about it. I've jumped in a guy's face
before about it. And I'll do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet has a hunch he won't feel the need to do that this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are a lot better around here, trust me,'' he said. ``A
lot better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
