<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-FRESNO-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS WIN, AGAIN, IN FOURTH QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Where the TCU Horned Frogs faltered a year
ago they are excelling this season _ the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs were again wielding their fourth-quarter magic last
night as they rallied behind two final-period touchdowns to upend
Fresno State, 21-10, before 28,013 spectators in Amon Carter
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In a stretch of four consecutive home games, TCU has played
down-to-the-wire football in each outing, winning the first three.
The Frogs, 1-10 last season, are 2-0 in the Western Athletic
Conference and 4-1 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State slipped to 1-4 overall and 1-1 in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shows we really want to win; we're never going to
give up,'' said tailback LaDainian Tomlinson, who finished with a
team-high 113 yards, which included a 33-yard fourth-quarter
touchdown. ``It just comes down to you have to play the fourth
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was fitting after a stifling TCU defensive effort most of
the night that a bone-jarring hit by safety Reggie Hunt on Fresno
State tight end Scott Thompson caused a fumble that cornerback
Kendrick Patterson scooped and bolted 29 yards for what would prove
the game-sealing touchdown with 6:36 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   While Fresno State quarterback Billy Volek was successful in
puncturing the Frogs' blitzing attack with short slant passes
throughout, TCU stuffed the Bulldogs' running game. Jaime Kimbrough
and three other Bulldogs rushers were held to a combined 32 yards
on 35 attempts by a TCU front led by defensive end Aaron Schobel
and middle linebacker Joseph Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' only glaring defensive breakdown came during the
first quarter when a short slant pass from Volek to receiver Atnaf
Harris went for a 47-yard touchdown after cornerback Greg Walls
slipped trying to make the tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one missed tackle that cost us some points, but other
than that, I thought they played well,'' said first-year TCU coach
Dennis Franchione, who has guided TCU to its first three-game
winning streak since 1995. ``We played the run well, like we've
pretty much done all year, and we forced them to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Frogs' offense, though sometimes inconsistent, continued
to show improvement and poise. Tomlinson's 33-yard touchdown run
came on a fourth-and-three option pitch from quarterback Patrick
Batteaux.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson, who played the entire second half in place of an
injured Basil Mitchell, took the perfectly timed pitch from
Batteaux and scooted past the entire Fresno State defense to help
TCU gain a 14-10 lead with 12:09 left.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, which is 4-0 this season when it rushes for 240 yards or
more, finished with 242 yards on the ground and 338 yards of total
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the defense plays as well as it did, it gives you a
chance to be persistent,'' Franchione said. ``In the fourth
quarter, I thought we took it to them physically up front.''
</P>
<P>
   But TCU's offense wasn't entirely smooth as consecutive
turnovers by Batteaux nearly put the Frogs in a hole. But only
Dante Marsh's interception resulted in points when Fresno State
kicker Jeff Hanna converted a 37-yard field to snap a 7-7 tie from
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   One series earlier, Batteaux fumbled the ball on a keeper at the
TCU 40. But a defensive stand pushed the Bulldogs backward 5 yards
on the first two plays and forced them to punt on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad at myself, because it was my mistakes which could
have hurt us,'' said Batteaux, who finished 9-of-17 passing for 96
yards and one interception while rushing for 72 yards and the
second-quarter touchdown. ``I take the blame. It's something I have
to work on and get corrected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
