<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ SENDS YANKEES PAST INDIANS, 4-0, TIES ALCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Perhaps no player in this American League
Championship Series grasps the concept of survival as does
right-hander Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that one quality made ``El Duque'' the New York Yankees'
best candidate to start last night's critical scenario in Game 4 at
Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who along with seven others spent three days floating
aboard a raft during their December 1997 defection from Cuba,
pitched the Yankees to a 4-0 victory against the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who pitched seven scoreless innings, emerged as the
primary reason the Yankees tied the best-of-seven series at two
games apiece. Hernandez, who today celebrates his 29th birthday,
recorded six strikeouts and surrendered only three hits and two
walks during his gutsy 115-pitch appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pressure prior to the game,'' said Hernandez, who
escaped first- and sixth-inning hazards unscathed to earn the
victory. ``It was a big game, and I knew we were in a must-win
situation. I felt pressure, but I had no fear. I've been through
many difficult times on and off the field in my life, and I knew
I'd be able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jim Thome emerged as Hernandez's victim du jour
during the Indians' best scoring threats with two runners aboard in
both at-bats. Hernandez induced an inning-ending fly ball from
Thome that right fielder Paul O'Neill caught on the warning track
during the first inning, and he recorded the final out of the sixth
inning after Thome swung and missed on a 3-2 changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody jumped off the bench on that one,'' Yankees manager
Joe Torre said. ``Striking out Thome was huge. That was probably
the at-bat of the night for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Yankees will enter Game 5 this afternoon with their
ace, left-hander David Wells, scheduled to pitch and 20-game winner
David Cone ready for Game 6 Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest game of the year for us,'' said O'Neill,
whose first-inning home run off right-hander Dwight Gooden gave the
Yankees a 1-0 lead. ``We were playing for our lives out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, who during Game 2 of the Indians' Division Series with
the Boston Red Sox threw only 22 pitches before being ejected,
displayed the effects of inactivity throughout the Yankees' two-run
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden issued consecutive walks to O'Neill and center fielder
Bernie Williams before surrendering a run-scoring, ground-rule
double to designated hitter Chili Davis. First baseman Tino
Martinez later delivered a sacrifice fly that scored Williams from
third and gave the Yankees a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Indians manager Mike Hargrove removed Gooden with two outs in
the fifth inning, and that ensured the right-hander of becoming the
only pitcher in the major leagues to make nine postseason starts
without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez earned his first in his first postseason appearance _
and in a game the Yankees could not afford to lose. The Yankees
would have faced elimination today with a loss last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him at brunch today, and he asked me how I was
feeling,'' Torre said. ``I knew that was the first indication that
he was OK. He was very relaxed, very determined, and he was a
little reluctant to give me the ball when I went out there in the
eighth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Stanton, though, pitched a scoreless eighth
inning, and right-hander Mariano Rivera pitched a perfect ninth for
the save in Hernandez's gem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was very good,'' Hargrove said. ``I don't know
that he missed any spots all night long. He threw the ball well and
made the pitches when he had to make them. He made some tough 3-2
pitches to get some of our big hitters out in some key
situations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
