u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KSU-Colorado-HNS &LR;      10-11 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KSU-Colorado </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas State shows &QL; 
Colorado right stuff
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BOULDER, Colo. _ The purple-clad Kansas State fans who flocked to
Colorado's Folsom Field on Saturday had a reason to rejoice. Their
team successfully made the jump to Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   After feasting on the downtrodden (Northern Illinois, Indiana
State, Northeast Louisiana) and semi-downtrodden (Texas), the
fifth-ranked Wildcats increased their record to 5-0 by beating
Colorado, an alleged heavyweight, 16-9.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State played stout defense and had the benefit of
Colorado's basic ineptitude in gaining the victory on a gorgeous,
60-degree evening in the Rockies. It was the first KSU victory in
Boulder since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the first of the season for Colorado, which had
gained a No. 14 ranking after opening with five consecutive
victories.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 16-0, the Buffaloes came back with nine
points _ a touchdown and a field goal _ in the final 5:42. Kansas
State, trying to hold its seven-point lead, was forced to punt from
its 32-yard line with 37 seconds showing, but the Wildcats got a
gift first down when Colorado was penalized for having too many
players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The game represented a new world for Kansas State, which had
outscored its previous four opponents by a total of 249-21. On a
night when star quarterback Michael Bishop put up mortal numbers
(19 yards rushing, 148 passing), the Wildcats relied on kicker
Martin Gramatica (three field goals) and a defense that sacked
Colorado quarterback Mike Moschetti five times.
</P>
<P>
   Moschetti was dreadful until the fourth quarter, when he
completed 10 of 18 passes for 117 yards and led the Buffaloes on
their two scoring drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is such a thing as an ugly win, you witnessed one
today,'' Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's first series ended with punter Nick Pietsch, in his
own end zone, trying to run, finding no room and then booting the
ball into the stands. As a result, Kansas State took possession at
the Colorado 22. Seven plays later, the Wildcats got a 30-yard
field goal from Gramatica for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado wasn't able to cross midfield until five minutes were
gone in the second quarter. Moschetti hit Andy Peeke, coming out of
the backfield, for a 43-yard gain to the KSU 47. But disaster
struck the Buffaloes two plays later as Moschetti fumbled the snap,
Kansas State's Darren Howard winding up with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Set up at midfield, Bishop threw deep on first down and found
Aaron Lockett for 44 yards. The Wildcats were in the end zone three
plays later, fullback Brian Goolsby going in from two yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 13-0 late in the third quarter, Colorado gained some
life when Ben Kelly intercepted a Bishop pass. The play gave the
Buffaloes the ball at the Kansas State 39.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne Cherrington blasted up the middle for 12 yards on first
down, but the drive stalled, leaving Colorado with a
fourth-and-five at the Kansas State 23. Moschetti threw incomplete
into the end zone on the fourth-down play.
</P>
<P>
   After Gramatica's 41-yard field goal made it 16-0, Colorado got
another break, a fumble by KSU running back Eric Hickson at his own
36, and actually did something with it. With 5:42 left in the game,
Moschetti threw five yards to Marcus Stiggers for the touchdown.
The two-point conversion attempt failed.
</P>
<P>
   On Colorado's next series, Moschetti again moved his team down
the field, this time coming away with Jeremy Aldrich's 20-yard
field goal with 1:46 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an onside kick, Aldrich attempted, in CU coach Rick
Neuheisel's words, to ``kangaroo one down inside,'' and wound up
lofting the ball out of bounds. Kansas State took over at its 35
but did nothing with the opportunity, forcing James Garcia's punt.
</P>
<P>
   When the punt went into the end zone, Colorado apparently was
set up at its 20 with time enough to move down the field. But the
chance quickly went out the window when the Buffaloes were called
for having too many men on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make a play and put Ben Kelly in for the punt
return,'' Neuheisel said, ``and we had 11 guys on the field.
(Special teams coach) Bobby (Hauck) thought, because we put Ben in
and not Roman (Hollowell), we only had 10 guys on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out we had 12 guys on the field at an inopportune
time. Whether it would have made a difference, no one can tell, but
I expect to hear about it. It certainly wasn't the way we want a
game to end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
