<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-JAMESMADISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH SAVES UMASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; AMHERST, Mass. _ The University of Massachusetts, ranked 24th
nationally among Division 1-AA programs, was ahead by 16 points,
28-12, just 12 seconds into the fourth quarter Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   One might have considered that the game was over, but one would
have been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It took a slight tip by Minuteman safety Brian Smith on a pass
over the middle into the end zone to Dukes wide receiver Marc
Bacote with 58 seconds left, causing the ball to fall incomplete,
that gave the Minutemen the Atlantic 10 win before 14,202 at Alumni
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Had James Madison's Greg Maddox completed that 2-point
conversion pass, it would have tied the game. Bacote was his third
option on the play, with wide receiver Ernest Payton, who had a
James Madison record 13 catches (for 155 yards) on the day, the
first option. But UMass wisely had him surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   UMass (4-1, 2-0) didn't play well, but came away with the 28-26
win, its fourth in a row. And James Madison (1-5, 0-3), playing
perhaps its best game of the season, was ahead, 12-7, at halftime,
but gave up 14 points in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   UMass tailback Marcel Shipp dashed for 190 yards on 24 carries,
including a 12-yard touchdown jaunt. ``We knew he was shifty, but
we couldn't wrap him up,'' said James Madison free safety Tony
Booth.
</P>
<P>
   The huge factor, though, was the conversion pass attempt to tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got a break when they were running the play and
we saw their set,'' said UMass first-year coach Mark Whipple. ``And
then Brian Smith, our most solid player on defense, our most
consistent player, had a tip on the pass to give us the win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen had some difficulties _ among them two missed
field goals. One was on the first series, after UMass recovered a
fumble, but the 40-yard attempt by Matt Murphy was wide left. And
then there was a 37-yarder with 2:55 to play, again wide left,
after UMass had a first down on the James Madison 12 earlier in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put pressure on Murphy all week,'' Whipple said. ``Two
missed field goals, that's hard to look at. We need a guy who is
going to come in and make big kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the failed field goal, though, UMass right tackle Mim
Hill had an unsportsmanlike penalty called against him, and the
15-yard infraction brought the ball back to the James Madison 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one reason why you don't get into coaching,'' said
Whipple, who stresses that his team has to become more intense in
practice with first-team offense against first-team defense. ``That
could have cost us the game. That was a foolish penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   James Madison had the game's last two touchdowns, on a 4-yard
pass to tight end Craig Akins with 5:36 left, and then a 9-yard
scamper around the left end by tailback Delvin Joyce with 58
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UMass won, although it lacked spunk, especially in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a way to win and that's the important thing,''
Whipple said. ``I did a poor job of getting the kids prepared and
maybe we'll learn from that. We were up 16 points, but that's just
two possessions, and I think that because we were home, some of our
players might have felt that we could lie down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel a lot better with this win than our loss to
Delaware, but it wasn't as good as our other wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple credited JMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit to them,'' he said, ``but we didn't
have that eye of the tiger feeling. Our offensive line didn't come
out of the huddle like we wanted to play, and on defense we missed
a lot of tackles. But we found a way to win, showing a lot of
character in our kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
