<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERAIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINE SHAFT MAY HOLD CLUE TO AMTRAK DERAILMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teams of lawmen descended 160 feet into a desert mine shaft
Saturday looking for dead bodies, stolen cars and evidence from the
1995 sabotage of an Amtrak passenger train.
</P>
<P>
   After a day's work in foothills north of Buckeye, the haul
included two stolen vehicles and a bunch of junk.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI agents, Department of Public Safety officers and
Maricopa County Sheriff's detectives planned to resume their
subterranean quest _ dubbed Operation Hells Gate _ this morning,
based on unrelated tips from informants.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Special Agent Ray Churay said investigators are trying to
determine if an off-road vehicle that was yanked from the mine by a
crane Saturday is linked to the Amtrak derailment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel one of the vehicles may be associated with the
derailment,'' said Churay, who's in charge of the FBI's Phoenix
office. ``Intelligence developed during the year leads us to
believe that there may be evidence in the mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort took place in scrubby foothills about a mile north of
Interstate 10 at Miller Road. It was made treacherous by conditions
in the mine and the discovery of two dynamite sticks. Investigators
did not know whether the explosives were dropped into the shaft in
an effort to destroy evidence, or left from old mining operations.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment of the Sunset Limited took place three years ago
Friday about 40 miles southwest of Phoenix. One man died and 78
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   After the train jackknifed into Quail Springs Wash,
investigators found several anti-government notes signed by ``Sons
of the Gestapo.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was one of the most intensive law-enforcement
probes on record, with FBI agents and sheriff's deputies
interviewing hundreds of people and tracking thousands of leads.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators today suspect that the Gestapo letter was a ruse
designed to mislead them. Although the motive remains unknown, they
have pursued theories that the sabotage was done by someone with a
grudge against the railroad or emergency workers with a hero
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Several suspects were identified over the past three years. No
arrests have been made, but federal authorities say the Amtrak case
remains a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the FBI announced that reward offers in the case
have been raised to $320,000. Guadalupe Gonzalez, special agent in
charge for Arizona, said he hopes the additional $200,000 will
encourage someone to step forward with information on the
saboteurs.
</P>
<P>
   The off-road vehicle discovered Saturday _ known as a sand rail
_ is a sort of dune buggy with roll bars. Agents would not say how
it might be connected with the case, but it is common for crime
scene investigators to take tire prints.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Amtrak crash, however, dozens of emergency
vehicles entered the area before it was secured.
</P>
<P>
   Churay declined to say what other evidence agents are hoping to
find in the mine shaft.
</P>
<P>
   DPS Officer Andy Vidaure said investigators in an auto-theft
task force learned of the 800-foot-deep pit from a confidential
informant who said that up to six stolen vehicles and two bodies
had been dumped there.
</P>
<P>
   He said that tip came about nine months ago, but retrieving
evidence was not considered worth the cost and danger until
additional tips surfaced involving Amtrak and homicide victims.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Dave Moyer of the Sheriff's Office said investigators
were told one of the corpses would be found in the trunk of a
stolen Mustang. He said investigators apparently do not know the
identities of the deceased, how they ended up in the mine or who
was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's lead apparently came independent of the DPS probe, and
Vidaure said there is no indication that the automobile thieves and
Amtrak terrorists are linked. But those two agencies joined forces
with sheriff's homicide and mountain rescue deputies for Saturday's
search.
</P>
<P>
   The mine, abandoned years ago, is on state land in an area
crisscrossed with vehicle trails. Investigators said trash has been
dumped into the hole along with crime evidence, and it is plain
that hundreds of people are familiar with the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies wearing headlamps lowered themselves into the vertical
shaft with rappelling ropes to a point where eight vehicles were
clogged. A crane was used to haul out evidence. The deputies were
retrieved by about 20 officers who formed a sort of tug-o'-war team
to pull the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Work was suspended Saturday evening after the crane's cable
broke while reeling in the Mustang. Officials said they intend to
remove the rest of the cars today, then descend 640 feet more to
check for evidence at the bottom. &QL; 
 &UR; Dennis Wagner can be reached at 444-8874 or at
Dennis.Wagner &LR; pni.com via the
 &UR; Internet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
