<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-KANSAS-HNS     10-11 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-KANSAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor scores last-minute TD to outlast Kansas 31-24 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ Two also-rans from the North and South divisions of the Big
12 Conference got together Saturday night at Floyd Casey Stadium
for what likely was both teams' last chance for a victory until
sometime in November.
</P>
<P>
   Despite sloppy play for three quarters, Baylor didn't let the
opportunity slip away. Trailing 24-21 with less than four minutes
to play, the Bears scored 10 points in the late going to beat
Kansas 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Darrell Bush, who had been held to 54 yards on 21
carries before the final drive, broke loose for a 70-yard scamper
that moved the ball to the Jayhawks' 20-yard line. Bush carried
four times for 79 yards on the final drive, including a one-yard
run with 49 seconds left that lifted Baylor to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jermaine Alfred, making his first start of the
season in place of Odell James, completed 15 of 29 passes for 288
yards, including 127 in the fourth quarter. Kansas seemed in
control of the game with a 24-14 lead entering the final quarter,
but the Jayhawks couldn't stop Alfred, wide receiver Morris
Anderson or Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, the fun's in winning,'' Baylor coach Dave
Roberts said. ``We seem to play better in the second half for some
reason. The way we hung in there tonight and fought, it's something
to be very proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next month, things will get harder for Baylor (2-3, 1-2
Big 12) and Kansas (2-4, 0-4). Baylor's next four games are against
Texas A&AMP;M, Texas, Notre Dame and Kansas State, meaning its next
sniff of a victory likely will be Nov. 14 against Oklahoma. Kansas
plays Nebraska, Colorado and Kansas State, so its next chance for a
win probably won't be until Nov. 7 against North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Baylor's come-from-behind victory was important.
After upsetting North Carolina State 33-30 on Sept. 19, the Bears
lost by two points to Colorado and two points to Texas Tech.
Another close loss at home to a lesser foe could have spun the
Bears' season downward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some really tough teams coming up, particularly next
week,'' Roberts said. ``That's a team (Texas A&AMP;M) that just beat
Nebraska, so it's not going to get any easier. Tonight, we hung
tough when we had to and made the plays at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson caught five passes for 147 yards, including receptions
of 39 and 49 yards in the final quarter. Those grabs set up Derek
Lagway's 19-yard touchdown run to pull Baylor to within 24-21 early
in the fourth quarter. With 3:50 left in the game, Matt Bryant's
42-yard field goal tied it at 24.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime seemed imminent when Baylor took over at its 10-yard
line with 2:26 left in the game. But Bush hit a big hole up the
middle, veered to his right and raced to the Kansas 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boosts our egos a lot,'' said Bush, who finished with 133
yards on 24 carries. ``To be able to come from behind like we did
feels good after losing like we have lately.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Kansas looked every bit like a team that
was incapable of winning no matter the opponent. The Jayhawks ran
12 plays without a first down. Of those 12 plays, five were
incomplete passes by quarterback Zac Wegner and four were rushing
plays that resulted in negative yards. Kansas had three yards of
total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas even failed at the old one-two-three-kick routine. After
a drive stalled at their 39 late in the first quarter, the Jayhawks
handed Baylor its first touchdown of the game. Punter Matt Tyler
dropped the deep snap, and Clifton Rubin picked up the ball and ran
27 yards into the end zone with 1:08 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second quarter was a different matter for Kansas. Led by
Mitch Bowles, a 5-8, 190-pound reserve running back, the Jayhawks
gained 203 yards in the quarter and scored twice within a
four-minute span to go ahead 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   Wegner, who was 12-of-33 for 254 yards, dumped a pass to Bowles,
who raced 62 yards to the Baylor four. Before that play, Kansas had
run 14 plays that had resulted in an incomplete pass or negative
rushing yards and 10 plays with positive yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't easy for the Jayhawks to score their first
touchdown. A pass-interference call on Rodney Smith on a third-down
play kept Kansas' drive going, and Wegner went in from the one to
tie it with 3:52 left.
</P>
<P>
   On their final first-half drive, the Jayhawks moved the ball 74
yards in less than two minutes, with Bowles carrying 32 yards to
set up his one-yard touchdown run with 11 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor tied the game at 14 with a sharp opening second-half
drive behind Alfred, who threw 35 yards to Anderson on
third-and-nine for the touchdown. The rest of the quarter belonged
to Kansas, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks got a 42-yard field goal from Joe Garcia to go
ahead 17-14 with 8:48 left and increased their lead to 24-14 on a
27-yard scoring pass from Wegner to Termaine Fulton late in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfred and Bush saved the best for last, and the Bears were
able to win a close game to give themselves a boost heading into
the most difficult portion of their schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
