<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-FRAZIER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZIER SUCCESSFULLY JUG GLES ASU, FIESTA, USOC DUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This is the fall of Herman Frazier's content.
</P>
<P>
   And the busiest the 43-year-old has ever been, which is saying
something for a man whose 20-year professional head has never been
covered by a single hat.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier's 20th year in athletic administration at his alma mater
Arizona State begins in March. He is one of two senior associate
athletic directors, a job that would be plenty for most mortals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he concedes that his one-year stint as president of the
Fiesta Bowl in this, the first go-round of the Bowl Championship
Series, is like another full-time job. And his other volunteer
positions _ vice president of the U.S. Olympic Committee and
chairman of the Maricopa County Sports Commission _ are as
consuming and complex as anything that comes his way through ASU
and the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that amazes me most is how he is able to tackle each
problem with a great deal of intensity,'' said John Junker, the
Fiesta Bowl executive director who has known Frazier since their
undergraduate days at ASU in the mid1970s. ``His mental stamina. He
shifts gears quicker than anybody I've ever seen. His ability to
keep up the pace. I think I'd last a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier passes along the credit faster than the 44.95 seconds it
took to win a 400-meter bronze medal _ and a 4x400 gold _ at the
1976 Olympics. What he calls his ASU cabinet _ assistant athletic
directors Cathy Reid, Mike Chismar and Tom Salder and master
scheduler Jill Adams _ gives Frazier the rope to spread himself
thin yet keep the quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grade-point average was higher during the track season than
it was in the fall because I knew I only had a window of time to do
things in the spring,'' Frazier said. ``With juggling 50,000
things, I am probably at my best.''
</P>
<P>
   So Frazier departs after five days in Winnipeg, Manitoba, where
he will be U.S. mission chief for the 1999 Pan American Games, in
time to reach Los Angeles at 2 a.m. for the ASU-Southern California
football game. This week he whirls through a string of
bring-me-up-to-speed campus meetings to clear the deck for
glad-handing with College Football Hall of Famers and meeting with
ABC television officials and sponsors for the Fiesta Bowl,
co-hosting Notre Dame's first football game against ASU and
welcoming the entire U.S. Olympic family to his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff at Sun Devil Stadium on Saturday was a half hour before
the USOC Board of Directors meeting, with Frazier on the agenda to
present a Pan Am Games report, began in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough compared to if I was out of town,'' Frazier
admitted. ``I just pick out what I ``have'' to do, and it's a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier already had 12 years (1980-92) experience on the USOC
Board of Directors when he shifted from the organization to USA
Track &AMP; Field, becoming a vice president. Then came the opportunity
to be U.S. assistant mission chief for the Atlanta Olympics and
encouragement from former USOC President Dr. LeRoy Walker and
former USATF executive director Ollan Cassell to pursue one of
three USOC vice-president slots for 1997-2000.
</P>
<P>
   The timing coincided with ASU's athletic-direction transition
from Charles Harris to Christine Wilkinson (interim) to Kevin
White, all of whom supported Frazier's moonlighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona State has always strongly encouraged career
enhancement and development,'' White said. ``Quite frankly at the
end of the day, the university is the big winner in this regard. It
keeps ASU current and makes us look at issues and trends
proactively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herman is doing a fabulous job to balance all the balls. Most
people could not do what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could Frazier, he thinks, if the time comes that he has a
chance to be USOC president. Or a USOC staff member, which some
feel he is best suited for because of his administrative
background. Or an athletic director, a job that narrowly eluded him
after on-campus interviews at Missouri, San Diego State, California
and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a blessing in disguise,'' Frazier said. ``If I
would have taken one of those positions, I would have not have been
VP of the USOC nor would I be the president of the Fiesta Bowl.
That's why I talk about being lucky and fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a wonderful education to be involved with the
(USOC) Executive Committee. Being on the board is one thing, but
when you're in that room and involved in that decision-making
process, it's incredible. I liken it to a professor taking a
sabbatical to do some research. For me, it's kind of like ongoing
research.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
