<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-USOC-BALDWIN-AZR &LR;      10-11 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-BALDWIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC OFFI CIAL IS A WOMAN ON THE RISE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Her real-estate competitors sometimes suggest to
potential clients that Sandra Baldwin is too busy to handle their
business.
</P>
<P>
   She knows better, and in this day of e-mail, fax and cell
phones, so do her customers. Baldwin's Prudential Arizona Realty
string of most properties sold since 1987 remains intact even as
her commitments to the U.S. Olympic Committee increase as she edges
toward election as the organization's first female president.
</P>
<P>
   If a proposed change in the USOC constitution is passed at the
next Board of Directors meeting in April, current President William
Hybl could run for a second term. Even that would only slow the
seemingly inevitable ascension of Baldwin, a native Arizonan whose
sports career began because her two children were country-club
swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I'd love to be president,'' said Baldwin, 59, who
was USOC treasurer from 1993-96 and has been on the Board of
Directors since '85. ``I've been here a long time and I've worked
hard and I think I understand the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good old boys organization for so long and
regretfully a good old White boys organization for so long that
it's only been in the past 15 years we've had any diversity. Yet,
look at our athletes. We have great African-American athletes, we
have great Paralympians. When you think we've only had two women
officers (Evie Dennis, a former vice president, being the other), I
think having a woman president would say something toward promoting
women in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin and national-level Olympic sports almost perfectly
coincides with Baldwin and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   After she gave up an 11-year career teaching English at Arizona
State _ ``I got burned out. I couldn't think of anything new I
wanted to say and the environment was a little insulated'' _ she
stepped from Arizona swimming to treasurer of U.S. Swimming
(1978-82).
</P>
<P>
   Her first real-estate listing was in 1982, producing a
half-million dollar sale.
</P>
<P>
   Her almost straight-line rise in both fields has broadened
Baldwin's life beyond her post-classroom imaginings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my aspirations, at every stage of wherever I was, was
to try to do a good job at what I was doing at the time,'' she
said. ``I'm just such a believer in people being at the right place
at the right time and that things happen for a reason if we try to
do them right.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin was president of U.S. Swimming (1984-86) and U.S.
Shooting (1994-95), on the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games
board of directors and finance committee and U.S. mission chief for
the 1995 Pan American Games in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   She is U.S. mission chief for the 2000 Olympics and in a recent
10-day period traveled to Salt Lake, Sydney, back here for a day
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin is also on the finance committee that recently delivered
a $1.45 billion budget with a specific price tag on almost every
item.
</P>
<P>
   ``This far out, it's as detailed a budget as any Olympic
organizing committee has had,'' Baldwin said. ``It's going to have
to be done that way. If the Olympics are going to be in this
country, it's very important that we know how much they're going to
cost, what the timing is on that cost and at the end of the day how
you're going to raise the money for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like putting on a county fair yet most people that
sit on these board of trustees until they are really intimately
involved don't understand the scope of the mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin knows all too well about the reality of crunching
numbers that in the case of the USOC quadrennium budget have topped
$450 million. That's why she relishes the mission chief role and
putting athlete faces to the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that you're not always behind a desk and not always looking
at dollars,'' she said. ``Someone has to do that and I manage to do
that pretty well so that's where I have to be part of the time, but
that's not where I have to be all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, said Baldwin who will make two more trips to Australia
in 1999 and another in 2000 before the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 Games, ``is
going to be the most beautiful Summer Olympics certainly that I've
had the opportunity to see.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
