<HEADLINE>
USOC IN CREASES SPENDING, FAILS ON `ATHLETE' DEFINITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The United States Olympic Committee Board of Directors
approved a revised budget Saturday while putting off until today
consideration of the most contentious issue on its Phoenix agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The definition of an athlete, vital to determining who qualifies
to fill the required 20 percent athlete representation in the U.S.
Olympic Committee, was thought to have been hashed out between the
Athletes Advisory Council and National Governing Bodies Council.
</P>
<P>
   But the council pulled its approval Saturday morning, sending
the two groups back into conference with the hope of an agreement
that can be put before the board.
</P>
<P>
   The AAC wants a tighter definition that favors Olympic athlete
selection to the board, committees and task forces. The council
favors a broader definition that makes it easier to fill the 20
percent allotment.
</P>
<P>
   The budget revision includes an additional $28 million in
spending previously approved for Podium 2002 (Salt Lake Winter
Olympics) and Vision 2000/2004 (Sydney/Athens Summer Olympics)
athlete support.
</P>
<P>
   USOC expenses are projected at $462,000 for the quadrennium
through 2000 with revenue pegged at $430 million. The $32 million
deficit is somewhat deceiving because an already-negotiated
increase in domestic Olympic television rights turns that into a
projected $65 million surplus by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer  &UR; Jim Morris said the USOC is $11 million ahead of
schedule in revenue receipt and $19 million under budget so that
the organization will need to borrow against its line of credit
this year. He termed the USOC financial condition as superior.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour Saturday board session included a video tribute to
1988 three-time Olympic track gold medalist  &UR; Florence Griffith
Joyner, who died Sept. 21 of an apparent heart attack at age 38,
and video highlights from the 1998 Nagano Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chris Schenkel of ABC Sports gave the keynote address, touching
on the 10 Olympics he covered beginning with the 1960 Squaw Valley
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Schenkel, 75, told of his meetings with three of America's
greatest Olympians:  &UR; Jim Thorpe,  &UR; Babe Didriksen and  &UR; Jesse Owens.
Owens lived in Phoenix from 1972 until his death at age 66 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   USOC Executive Director  &UR; Dick  &UR; Schultz told the 110-member board
that the revised Amateur Sports Act will be attached to the Omnibus
Spending Bill in hopes of getting what will be renamed the Olympic
Sports Act through the U.S. Congress this session.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark legislation, passed in 1978 and naming the USOC as
the country's coordinating body for Olympic athletics, is being
amended for inclusion and mark/symbol protection purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz reminded his audience that the percentage of total
medals won by the United States at Atlanta in 1996 and Nagano was
down from previous Olympics because more sports are offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program is going in the wrong direction,'' he said, adding
that the earlier the athletes get their training money, the better
the chances of winning a medal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Anita DeFrantz, one of two U.S. International Olympic Committee
members, spoke about the World Conference on Doping, Feb. 2-4 in
Lausanne, Switzerland, out of which a new indepedent agency for
drug testing, education and research could be formed.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Olympic Movement Anti-Drug Agency (OMADA) would be
responsible for testing at major international competitions in all
sports with consistent sanctions and appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation was removed from probation because it
has completed constitutional changes required to maintain its USOC
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Among the USOC state fund-raising officials approved was  &UR; Fred
 &UR; Bauman of Phoenix as Arizona vice-chairman. The Arizona chairman
is  &UR; Dr. Art
 &UR; Mollen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
