<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0571 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-NOTEBOOK-AZR &LR;      10-11 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
  
 Tampa-Florida rivalry turns ugly   
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The natural rivalry between the Florida Panthers and Tampa Bay
Lightning took a turn for the worse after an ugly incident during
the preseason, when not only fists were flying, but apparently, so
were some racial taunts.
</P>
<P>
   Great, just what the NHL needs. More stupid remarks from stupid
players.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it supposedly came from the mouth of Tampa Bay's
 &UR; Darcy
 &UR; Tucker, who, according to eyewitnesses yelled a series of
expletives and a racial slur at Florida's  &UR; Peter Worrell, who is
black.
</P>
<P>
   Later, from the penalty box, both Tucker and teammate  &UR; Sandy
McCarthy reportedly made apelike gestures toward Worrell, who
responded only with laughter. Both Tucker and McCarthy have
emphatically denied the accusations and after an investigation into
the incident, the league absolved each of them because of
insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be the end if it.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Coach  &UR; Terry Murray already has taken offense to
suggestions from the Lightning that the Panthers lied about the
allegations. And he tore into Tampa Bay Coach  &UR; Jacques Demers,
directly blaming him for the actions of  &UR; Andrei Nazarov, who made
an ugly game even uglier by sucker-punching Florida's  &UR; Rob
Niedermayer from behind toward the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way Jacques has operated during his entire coaching
career _ everything from behind,'' Murray said. ``That's a
(expletive) move. The ref came over to me afterwards and said it
was just awful. To send a guy out there who plays just five minutes
a game to jump another guy is (expletive). It's a (expletive) move.
But that's the way Jacques has coached all his life. It's a bunch
of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Demers said Nazarov acted on his own and even called it
``unprofessional.'' Demers also said he thinks Murray is still mad
at him because he got the Tampa Bay job last year after it had been
offered to Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, but don't expect this feud to die down anytime soon.
It's probably only going to get worse. &QL; 
Chicago toughness
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about  &UR; Dirk Graham, the new head coach of the
Chicago Blackhawks, being too green for the job as a 38-year-old,
first-time coach at any level. Graham even understands if some
question his choice as the replacement for the fired  &UR; Craig
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a legitimate concern, and I would think the same
way if I was looking at the situation,'' Graham said. ``But I could
sit here and have 20 years on the job, but if I lose 60 percent of
my games . . . I have no coaching experience, but I'm confident in
what I can do. I've been around the game for 30 years and played it
since I was 5, so I think I know a little about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham saw enough by watching the Blackhawks play last season to
know at least one thing: The club had lost its respect around the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is anytime a team comes into your building and
takes liberties with your captain, they're pretty much saying, `We
don't have any respect for you at all.' And what are we going to do
about it? This is our home, where we practice every day and where
we live every day. When someone comes in and doesn't show you any
respect in the place where you work every day, then it's something
that needs to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Team toughness was never a problem during Graham's days with the
Blackhawks, when he wore the ``C'' from 1988 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a leader as a player, and as a coach, I'm sure
he's going to lay it on the line just as he did when he was
skating,'' Chicago's  &UR; Tony Amonte said. ``Dirk is himself _ he
always tells it straight, and you always know what to expect from
him. What else could a player want?''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bob Murray said he might have gotten a little
more than he expected in hiring Graham over several other
experienced candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is about Dirk. Some guys are just born to
do it,'' Murray said. ``There's a quiet confidence there. He knows
the game, and he has the presence of mind to handle this.'' &QL; 
The Avs and Av-nots
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell the Colorado Avalanche that the regular season
doesn't mean anything. They were terrible in the second half last
year, winning only eight of their final 22 games, and they blew it
in the playoffs by getting stunned by the Edmonton Oilers after
taking a 3-1 series edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playoffs were a huge disappointment, and that can't happen
again,'' center  &UR; Peter Forsberg said. ``It's a long road until the
playoffs, but you build the whole season, . . . you live off what
you did during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the new Northwest Division with Calgary, Edmonton and
Vancouver will only help Colorado, clearly the best of the lot. But
the Avalanche, under new Coach  &UR; Bob Hartley, won't take anything
for granted. They can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody looks like they're more into it this year,''
Forsberg said. ``When you get a new coach, that's something that
happens. It's good for us. I think we needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   They could use All-Star defenseman  &UR; Sandis Ozolinsh, too. He
remains unsigned, and negotiations have reached another impasse
after he turned down a three-year offer worth $10 million, which
seems more than fair. After all, the kid only made $1.5 million
last season. &QL; 
Who's that Predator?
</P>
<P>
   His name is  &UR; Jamie Heward, and in case you missed it, the
forward for the expansion Nashville Predators tied for the
preseason goal-scoring lead with such marquee names as  &UR; Eric
Lindros, Teemu Selanne and  &UR; Luc
 &UR; Robitaille. He finished with six goals, including four on the power
play, also good enough for first in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Heward didn't even play a single game in the NHL last season. He
was in the minors. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
