Stars open with win over Sabres 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars showed a form of banner envy last night that
was enough to make Mike Modano chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars raised three banners _ for the Presidents'
Trophy, the Western Conference regular-season championship and the
Central Division championship _ to the roof before the season
opener, the Stars center quipped: ``I was waiting for them to put
up the Power Play banner and the Norelco Faceoff banner. Heck, we
should have about six up there.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as quickly as he started the laughter in the postgame
press conference, Modano settled it down with one quiet, but firm
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still missing the important one, though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Stanley Cup championship banner, and the Stars
and Modano showed their hunger for it, ripping off a 4-1 victory
against the Buffalo Sabres before a sellout crowd of 16,928 fans at
Reunion Arena. Modano had a goal and two assists and sparked a
power play that went 3-for-8 as the Stars battered two-time
defending NHL MVP Dominik Hasek. The Sabres goalie fell to 3-7
lifetime against the Stars and has now yielded 10 goals in his past
two visits to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek simply wasn't enough to stop a Stars team that sent
offensive rushes in waves, played physical defense and got a solid
27-save performance from Ed Belfour in goal. In short, the Stars'
depth was simply too much for the Sabres, who were good enough to
make it to the Eastern Conference Finals last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a little bit from everyone; that's who we are, and
that's who we've been for the past three years,'' defenseman
Richard Matvichuk said.
</P>
<P>
   While valued veterans Joe Nieuwendyk and Brian Skrudland still
are sidelined with knee injuries, the Stars definitely made use of
their new pieces. Winger Brett Hull had an assist and fired off six
shots. Tough winger Brent Severyn won his fight with Sabres' tough
guy Rob Ray. Rookie winger Jamie Wright had a yeoman performance on
the checking line.
</P>
<P>
   And plenty of the old dependables also showed up. Modano was
spectacular with his three points, an 18-6 night in the faceoff
circle and the speed to draw two key penalties. Linemate Jere
Lehtinen was a pesky performer all night, logging 24:18 minutes of
ice time and adding a goal and an assist. Sergei Zubov had two
assists. Darryl Sydor added a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher played a team-leading 25:48 and added five hits.
Pat Verbeek had a goal and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since we've had a nucleus of such great
players,'' Modano said. ``We have a lot of people to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' first goal was a perfect example. Lehtinen hustled to
keep the puck in the offensive zone on the power play; Modano then
threaded a cross-ice pass to Sydor sneaking in the back door, and
Sydor lifted a perfect shot over Hasek's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great shot,'' Verbeek said. ``It was the only one
we could get by him on the first try.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored on a rebound at even strength to make it 2-0 after
the first period, while Verbeek scored on a charge to the net in
the second period, and Lehtinen finished the scoring at the 19:16
mark of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Geoff Sanderson scored for the Sabres to cut the
deficit to 3-1, but Belfour wouldn't let the Stars get any further
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little bit of a letdown in the second period,''
Matvichuk said. ``But we picked it right back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what the Stars had in mind after watching three
banners raised that all fell short of last season's primary goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great, it meant a lot to accomplish that,'' Matvichuk
said. ``We just want to improve on what we've already accomplished.
We want more this season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
