u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-HNS     10-11 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hernandez, relievers shut down Indians 4-0
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CLEVELAND _ There's something about pitchers with the last name
Hernandez that gives the Cleveland Indians chills in October.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Florida's Livan Hernandez. On Saturday night,
it was his older half-brother, Orlando, who caused the Indians
problems as the New York Yankees evened the American League
Championship Series at two games apiece with a 4-0 victory before a
crowd of 44,981 at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   If you're scoring at home: Hernandez brothers 3, Indians 0.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Orlando Hernandez watched from his native Cuba as
Livan won two games the Indians and was named MVP of the World
Series _ won by Florida in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it was Orlando Hernandez who gave the troubled Yankees
a much-needed shot in the arm, throwing seven scoreless innings and
allowing only three hits. He struck out six and walked two.
</P>
<P>
   The New York offense continued its slumber, but Hernandez _ and
a solo home run by Paul O'Neill in the first inning _ proved to be
enough to guarantee the series will head back to the Big Apple for
at least one more game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing for our lives,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention, a place in history. With the victory, the
Yankees have won a major-league record 119 games during the regular
season and postseason, surpassing the 1906 Chicago Cubs' total 118.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez _ nicknamed ``El Duque'' _ showed no signs of rust
from not having pitched in two weeks, using a breaking ball to keep
the Yankees in check while avenging a 4-1 loss to Cleveland on July
13.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Indians could put nothing together against
Hernandez. Cleveland, which smashed four home runs Friday in a 6-1
win, only could scrape up two singles and a double off Hernandez,
who turns 29 today.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera combined to shut out the Indians
over the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I pretty much had a must-win situation,'' Hernandez
said. ``I had pressure, but I had no fear. I've been through many
difficult times in my life on and off the field. I knew I would be
able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure?
</P>
<P>
   Before his start Saturday, Hernandez was asked to name the
biggest game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, of choosing one of the many highlights during a career
with the Cuban national team that included a 129-47 won-loss
record, he recalled the day last December when, along with seven
others, he boarded a boat and drifted for three days in the
Caribbean before being picked up by the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez cruised most of the way Saturday, and when he did get
in trouble he calmly found a way to keep the Indians off the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Cleveland had runners at first and third
and one out after Omar Vizquel singled and Hernandez hit David
Justice with a pitch. Hernandez reached back to strike out the
Indians' top two power threats _ Manny Ramirez and Jim Thome _ to
end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big lift for us,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
``The biggest lift of the night was him striking out Thome with two
men on base late in the game. Everybody jumped up off the bench on
that one. That was huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the at-bat of the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland also got two runners on in the eighth. Stanton, who
came on in relief with Enrique Wilson on base, struck out Kenny
Lofton before allowing a single to Vizquel. Stanton then got
Justice to ground into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees didn't fare a lot better Dwight Gooden, who allowed
only three hits _ but three runs _ in 4 innings. He is still
looking for his first postseason victory and, with an 0-4 record in
nine playoff starts, has more postseason starts with a win than any
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez became just the seventh rookie starter to win an ALCS
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're two different people,'' Hernandez said of Gooden's past
playoff failures. ``Today, luck shined on me and I had a chance to
win a playoff game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was arguably the biggest game of his career _ and the biggest
this season for the Yankees, rejuvenated now after dropping two
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he knew Hernandez might have a good game after
watching the pitcher serve a few of his teammates during brunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very animated, running out and getting different dishes
for people,'' Torre said. ``I felt good that if we scored some runs
we had a chance, and he proved me right. He was a little reluctant
to give me the ball when I went out there in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he's been through, a playoff game is a playoff
game. Just like a walk in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   New York took a 1-0 in the first inning on O'Neill's 373-foot
homer to right field. Thome just missed his third homer in two days
when his shot to right was caught by O'Neill at the wall to end the
first inning with runners at first and second base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
