<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-OKLAHOMA-HN     10-11 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-OKLAHOMA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas unloads arsenal, whips OU
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ Oklahoma coaches swore all week that Ricky Williams would
not beat the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   They were right.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all of the swearing just north of the Red River is in
reaction to how Major Applewhite, Wane McGarity and the Texas
defense beat the Sooners 34-3 at the Cotton Bowl on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And there is likely to be plenty of swearing in the direction of
Oklahoma head coach John Blake. His team committed 14 penalties for
109 yards as the Sooners suffered their worst loss to Texas since a
41-9 decision in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite threw for 293 yards, and McGarity caught six passes
for 153 yards, including 97 on the longest pass play in UT history.
The Longhorns' defense, meanwhile, enjoyed its best performance in
three years. The much-maligned unit held the Sooners to 197 yards,
its fewest surrendered since SMU totaled 188 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners tried three quarterbacks, but none was effective
against the swarming Longhorns. OU running back De'Mond Parker, who
ripped the Longhorns for 291 yards and three touchdowns last year,
was held to 93 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   And in an oh-by-the-way performance (for him, anyway), Williams
rushed for 139 yards and two touchdowns against the Sooners, who at
times had as many as 10 defenders within a yard of the line of
scrimmage trying to stop the nation's leading ball carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw them walk eight (defensive players) up in the box,
I just kind of thought to myself, `Surprise, surprise,'''
Applewhite said. ``Every defensive coordinator will say, `We're
going to put eight in the box.' It's not a surprise. You have to.
If you're going to put seven in there, then you're gonna have
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite continues to cause trouble for defenses that gear
their entire game plan to stopping Williams. The redshirt freshman,
who started his first game against Kansas State in place of the
injured Richard Walton, has thrown for more than 200 yards in each
of his four starts.
</P>
<P>
   In leading the Longhorns (4-2, 2-1 Big 12) to three consecutive
wins, Applewhite has directed the offense to scores in more than
half of its drives (22 of 43).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a balanced offense,'' McGarity said. ``We do a great
job of doing everything out there. Ricky's gonna get the ball _ we
know that's our game plan coming in. When we call passes, it's our
chance to shine. A lot of teams are going to stack the line like OU
did today, and the big plays are going to happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity has four games of 100-plus receiving yards this season,
and the Longhorns have had a receiver with 100 or more yards in a
school-record six consecutive games. Kwame Cavil was just shy of
that number against the Sooners, catching three balls for 93 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of this as a good game. I only completed 50
percent of my passes (14 of 27),'' Applewhite said. ``But we made
the plays when we had to. That's what we have to do to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma got on the board first with Jeff Ferguson's 47-yard
field goal four minutes into the game. But Texas held a 17-3 lead
at the half thanks to a 20-yard Williams scoring run and
Applewhite's 56-yard touchdown pass to Cavil in the first quarter
and Kris Stockton's 48-yard field goal just before the half.
</P>
<P>
   A quick turn of events early in the third quarter turned the
game into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a spark after a lackluster first half, the Sooners
seemed to get it with Michael Thornton's 79-yard return of the
second-half kickoff to the Texas 15.
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, the Sooners were inches away from pulling
within a touchdown when disaster struck. The snap from center
squirted through the hands of quarterback Brandon Daniels, and
Casey Hampton recovered at the two for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams gained a yard, Applewhite and McGarity broke the
game open. McGarity got behind OU cornerback Corey Ivy on a deep
post pattern, and Applewhite, after a straight drop into the end
zone, hit him in stride near midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy had no chance in a foot race with the speedy McGarity, and
seconds later, the orange-clad UT faithful at the north end of the
stadium _ part of a total crowd of 75,587 _ were rocking when
McGarity scored.
</P>
<P>
   The 97-yard pass play eclipsed the Texas record of 96 yards from
Todd Dodge to Donovan Pitts against Rice in 1985. More importantly,
it put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a nice kickoff that gave us a little momentum, but then
we fumble the ball on the one-yard line. You just cannot do that,''
Blake said. ``I thought that was a key play in the ballgame,
because we had the opportunity to get right back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense made a big stop and jarred the ball loose,'' Brown
said, ``and then (offensive coordinator) Greg Davis made a great
call. That really put some separation between the two teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' call allowed Applewhite to read the OU safeties and
decide whether to run with Williams or go deep to McGarity.
Applewhite made the wise choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They literally played nine men in the box the whole game, and
our receivers took advantage of that,'' Williams said. ``We got up
to the line (before the 97-yard touchdown), and we had a toss play
called, and Major saw that even in (that) situation the safety was
up six yards from the line of scrimmage. So he checked to a pass
play, and it was wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a gradual thing over the past three games.
The defense has been getting better, and the offense has been
getting better, and it all kind of came together this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
