<SLUG> BC-BBM-AZ-FALL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPS JUST PART OF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slow starts of several Diamondbacks playing for the
Scottsdale Scorpions are of little concern to the team's brass. So
far, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Take second baseman  &UR; Junior Spivey, who was hitless in his first
13 at-bats. Don't worry about it, said  &UR; Tommy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's working on some things right now,'' said Jones,
Diamondbacks director of minor league operations. ``This is his
instructional league. I don't think he's at the point where he's
getting disheartened. He's going to use this league to work on a
couple of things and not worry about his numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivey broke out of it Friday with two hits, including a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Spivey is working with Manager  &UR; Chris Speier and
hitting coach  &UR; Dan Gladden on his stance and use of his hands. He
hit .281 in 79 games with Class-A High Desert before being loaned
to Double-A Tulsa, where he hit .311 in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now he's in a different environment,'' Jones said. ``But
he's a great athlete, and great athletes find a way to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop  &UR; Danny Klassen, who spent time with the Diamondbacks
before returning to Tucson and suffering a fractured shoulder, just
got his average past .200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny's issue is that he had six or seven weeks of downtime
without facing live pitching,'' Jones said. ``It's been very
difficult to jump into what's almost a spring training type
situation. But at least in spring training, the pitchers are out
there for the first time. But here, pitchers have been pitching all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   After struggling early, outfielder  &UR; Jason Conti got hot. But
Jones isn't looking at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conti's always going to hit,'' he said. ``His biggest thing is
playing center field for the first time. . . . He's made all the
plays. We believe he can play center field.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers  &UR; Vladimir Nunez, Stephen Randolph and  &UR; Russell Jacob
also won't be judged quickly. Nun ez, who finished the year with
the Diamondbacks, has been hit hard. But he's being used as a
closer for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good experiment for him,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob missed a few days because of a sore shoulder, but it is
nothing serious. And Randolph has been getting better.
</P>
<P>
   The thing to remember, said Jones, is that it's early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assessment of where these guys truly are will be better
served as we roll around to the middle of November,'' he said. ``By
the same token, this is a good test of where all our players are in
their development. But the time to evaluate is at the end.'' &QL; 
Triple play &QL; 
It went 4-6-3-2-5-1 if you happened to be scoring, which is
doubtful unless you were among the 100 or so fans attending the
Maryvale-Phoenix game in which a triple play occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the eighth with runners on first and second,
Phoenix's
 &UR; Torii Hunter grounded to Maryvale second baseman
 &UR; Warren Morris, who flipped to shortstop  &UR; Damian Jackson, who
relayed to first baseman  &UR; Toby Zuleta for what was then a mere
double play.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Jed Hansen, the runner on second, decided to try to make it
home. Bad decision. Zuleta threw to catcher  &UR; Jason LaRue, getting
Hansen in a rundown. LaRue to third baseman  &UR; Chris Truby to pitcher
 &UR; Danny Young nailed Hansen and completed the triple play.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, by the way, is the player whose two-out, two-run homer
in the ninth inning won the College World Series for Louisiana
State in 1996. He's a Pittsburgh prospect. &QL; 
Short hops &QL; 
Going head-to-head with major league postseason play, Fall League
average attendance was reported at 333 a game during the first
week. Grand Canyon and Scottsdale, both based at Scottsdale
Stadium, were drawing 561 and 520 a game, respectively. Maryvale
was last at 105.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs outfield prospect  &UR; Roosevelt Brown hit four home
runs in his first six games, after hitting 15 homers in 111 games
for Class-A Daytona, Double-A West Tenn and Triple-A Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Among current members of the Diamondbacks,  &UR; David
 &UR; Dellucci, Ben Ford, Neil Weber, Aaron Small, Alan Embree, Joel
 &UR; Adamson, Clint Sodowsky, Andy Fox, Travis Lee and  &UR; Hanley Frias
played in the Fall League.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chicago Cubs first baseman  &UR; Leon Durham, whose fielding
gaffe in the 1984 playoffs is used as a reference point every time
a Cub messes up in a key situation, is a coach with Peoria. Durham,
a coach with Triple-A Vancouver the past two years, was a two-time
All-Star and a pretty good hitter, batting .277 over 10 major
league seasons. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
