A0578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PRAIRIEVIEW-ALCOR     10-11 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PRAIRIEVIEW-ALCORNSTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Statistics: Page 8B.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie View falls short against Alcorn St. 45-36
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BRIAN McTAGGART &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PRAIRIE VIEW _ There finally is a good reason to stick around past
halftime at Prairie View A&AMP;M football games, and it has nothing to
do with the band.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, playing their first home game at Blackshear
Stadium since snapping the nation's longest losing streak at 80
games two weeks ago, scratched and clawed Saturady before
eventually dropping a 45-36 decision to Alcorn State.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie View fans have been known to hit the exits after the
``Marching Storm'' band performs at the half, but the new and
improved Panthers football team kept most of the 8,356 sun-drenched
fans in their seats for the better part of three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the football team was the only show on this day.
</P>
<P>
   The band, which got the school embroiled in a controversy with
the Southwestern Athletic Conference after a fight with Southern
University's band, didn't perform after not getting clearance from
the SWAC.
</P>
<P>
   The entire controversy nearly ended Prairie View's football
season when the SWAC indefinitely suspended the Panthers from
league competition because the band missed one game of the two-game
suspension. The SWAC backed off for the time being, and Saturday's
homecoming game went off as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affected us somewhat, I'm not going to lie,'' Panthers
coach Greg Johnson said of the controversy. ``The strength of a
person is how well he perseveres, and we've got to push through the
little things and take care of the big things on the weekend, which
is the football game. That's what we didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers didn't take care of the football, either, turning
it over seven times, including five fumbles. Three of the seven
turnovers came inside Alcorn State's 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just made a lot of mistakes, I don't know how and I don't
know why,'' Johnson said. ``There's some things we've got to get
corrected to get ready for next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Prairie View (1-5, 0-4 SWAC) went up 7-0 midway through the
first quarter on DeMelvi Kelley's four-yard run. The Panthers
forced a punt and drove to the Alcorn State one before disaster
struck. Quarterback Josh Barnes had the ball poked out of his
outstretched hands on fourth down, and Damon Felder picked it up
off the grass and ran 97 yards to tie the score at 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some turnovers in the red zone at key points that I
feel turned the game around,'' Panthers defensive back Quincy
Fuller said. ``Without those turnovers, it is a different ballgame
and we end up on the victorious side.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 17-7 in the second quarter, Prairie View drove inside
Alcorn State's 10 again before Barnes was intercepted by LeeTerry
Moore in the back of the end zone. The Braves (3-3, 1-3) then
sucked the life out of the Panthers with a 17-play, 80-drive that
Cedric Horton capped with a one-yard touchdown run for a 24-7
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach got on us at halftime, and we came out the second half
fired up and ready to play,'' said Prairie View quarterback Jamal
Foster, who played the second half. ``But we really shot ourselves
in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   A blocked punt set up Prairie View's next score _ a one-yard run
by Kelley early in the third quarter that cut the lead to 24-15 _
and the Panthers forced Alcorn State to punt.
</P>
<P>
   But just as momentum began to swing, Prairie View's DeMarcus
Peterson muffed the punt return to give the Braves the ball at the
10. Rodney Thomas scored from there on the next play, and Braves
had a 31-15 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn State built a 45-15 lead heading into the fourth quarter
before the Panthers scored 21 unanswered points. But it was too
little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three opportunities to score offensively and we just
fumbled or did something wrong on the goal line,'' Johnson said.
``Today just wasn't our day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
