<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-GEORGIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEER EFFORT MORE THAN GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ For years, Tennessee's main problem was one of
perception as much as reality. Oh, the Volunteers were good enough
to win the nine and sometimes 10 games necessary to make them a
perennial Top 10 team.
</P>
<P>
   But beat Florida? Forget about it. Win a bowl game against a
quality team like Nebraska? Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Volunteers changed their normal yearly script by
ending a five-year losing streak against Florida with a stirring
20-17 overtime victory Sept. 19, some skeptics remained, arguing it
was as much what the Gators didn't do as what Tennessee did that
contributed to the victory, which caused a wild celebration in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Beat Georgia, which was coming off a stirring 28-27 road win
over LSU? Beat Georgia without leading rusher Jamal Lewis, who
earlier this week was diagnosed with a knee injury that will
sideline him for the season? Beat Georgia at Sanford Stadium, with
a revved up crowd looking for revenge if not redemption for last
year's 38-13 spanking in Knoxville? That wasn't going to happen,
and Tennessee found itself a 1-point underdog despite having a
higher national ranking (fourth) than the Bulldogs (seventh).
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, was just enough of a motivating factor and the
reason the Vols came here Saturday and whipped the Dawgs from hedge
to hedge in rolling to a 22-3 victory that was far more one-sided
then the final score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer, who is now 7-0 in
games against Georgia, ``was a program win. We're not supposed to
be this good.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Vols, who are sure to rise in the polls after
Nebraska's loss to Texas A&AMP;M Saturday, are that good.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, they are different from past Volunteer teams, with
more of a blue-collar, lunch-bucket look to them, a makeover from
the glitz and glamour of the teams that former Vols quarterback
Peyton Manning guided the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's win was defense-oriented. Georgia, guided by
wunderkind freshman QB Quincy Carter, never did get untracked,
being limited to a total of 254 yards and only 59 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which dropped to 4-1, was held to a 48-yard field goal
by Hap Hines in the first quarter, which briefly gave the Dawgs a
3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter, the star of last week's win over LSU, was forced to
move and think on the run from the opening series of the game. ``I
knew they were going to be coming,'' said Carter, who was a
miserable 14 for 37 for 195 yards, with two interceptions. ``But we
didn't handle it. We couldn't figure out what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Tennessee knew exactly what it was doing all
afternoon. There was quarterback Tee Martin, who picked up 45 yards
rushing and threw for a pair of third-quarter touchdowns that
turned a 9-3 Tennessee lead at halftime into a 22-3 romp. There
were the Travises, Henry and Stephens, who filled the role of Lewis
by combining for 160 yards rushing. And there was the defense, led
by linebacker Al Wilson, who shrugged off a shoulder injury
suffered in last week's win over Auburn and was in Carter's face
all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't realize, we're a very aggressive
defensive team,'' Wilson said. ``We chased Carter all day and we
hit him just to let him know we were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter knew, and so did the national television audience and
sellout crowd of 86,117, which had come to Sanford Stadium to see a
game between Top 10 teams for the first time since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan offerd the best explanation for what
took place. ``In the second half, Tennessee assaulted us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With almost half the season gone, Tennessee has done that now to
some quality teams, ranging from Florida at home to Syracuse and
Georgia on the road.
</P>
<P>
   What once seemed a long shot _ Tennessee filling one of the
slots in the national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4 _
now does not seem so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols know the potential for disaster still lurks _ this is a
team that lost a regular-season game to Memphis two years ago. They
know even if they go through the remainder of the regular season
unbeaten, they still have to come to Atlanta Dec. 5 and win the SEC
title game.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a different Tennessee team. Tougher. More
in-your-face. ``We're not the prettiest team,'' Wilson said. ``But
if we stay focused and play hard we'll win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Any game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOUSTON-ARMY-HNS &LR;      10-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-ARMY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Army's ground attack too much for UH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Fancy as a howitzer and just as single-minded, Army's wishbone
offense proved to be everything the Houston Cougars feared.
</P>
<P>
   The Cadets, who scored barely 1{ minutes into Saturday's game at
Robertson Stadium, kept the Cougars off balance on defense much of
the day and then stemmed UH's late rush.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 38-28 Conference USA victory for Army, its
inaugural conference road win and the first time in eight games
dating to 1996 the Cadets have won on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Down 31-7 in the third quarter, Houston (1-5, 1-1 C-USA) made it
a 10-point game in the final minute _ a margin that might have been
smaller if Jerrian James had been able to hold onto a
fourth-quarter pass in the end zone. While James (11 catches, 121
yards, two TDs) and others pulled their weight, the Cougars'
defense, as expected, struggled to solve an offense it had precious
little time to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Joe Gerena replaced starting quarterback Johnny Goff
(reinjured ankle) early in the second quarter, and the Cadets,
cheered on by about 4,000 soldiers from various bases, scarcely
skipped a beat. Ranked fourth nationally in rushing, Army gained
324 yards on 54 carries with an array of eight backs against a
Houston run defense that had been ranked 12th in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half was as big a nightmare as I thought it would
be,'' UH coach Kim Helton said. ``We thought it would take a
quarter to catch up to the speed of their offense because we
couldn't simulate it in practice. Unfortunately, it took a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unhappy with the way the defense played, but I'm
understanding. We took our good defense and made it look bad. We
were timid and afraid to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the Cougars trailed 28-7, due partially to a
lightning-quick start by Army. After Rod Richardson's 47-yard
return of the opening kickoff, Grady Jett sprinted 45 yards on an
end-around to the UH one, from where fullback Ty Amey scored the
first of his three TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and busted it right up the middle,'' said Amey,
whose 79 yards on 15 carries included a 40-yard burst.
</P>
<P>
   Army (2-3, 2-1), which scored on five of its first seven
possessions, led 14-0 after its second possession, a series of 10
running plays. The Cadets didn't throw a pass until their 18th play
and probably could have gone the whole game without attempting one.
They finished the day with one completion in three attempts as the
caissons keep rolling along.
</P>
<P>
   Army coach Bob Sutton said a quick start was imperative after
his team fell behind early while losing to East Carolina and
Rutgers in its previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we decided to take the kick to start and see if we
could get something going early,'' Sutton said. ``I felt our
running backs did a good job going at their D (defense).''
</P>
<P>
   UH quarterback Jason McKinley, sacked four times by an Army
defense that had only four sacks in the first four games, had four
touchdown passes, including two each to James and Orlando Iglesias,
while compiling a career-high 29 completions out of 50 attempts for
302 yards. But McKinley also drew an intentional-grounding penalty
and twice fumbled the center snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd seen all their blitzes on film,'' McKinley said. ``We
just shot ourselves in the foot in the first half. I felt we moved
the ball well in the second half, but we ran out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   James' 13-yard catch in the corner of the end zone narrowed the
Cadets' lead to 14-7 in the first quarter, but halfback Bobby
Williams (11 carries, 62 yards) broke a 36-yard scoring run on
Army's next series. Amey's eight-yard run just before halftime
ended a 46-yard scoring drive that was helped along by a UH
personal-foul penalty, giving the Cadets a 28-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Army ran more than six minutes off the clock on its first
possession of the second half before Eric Olsen kicked a 37-yard
field goal to make it 31-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars, who held an 87-57 margin in plays, didn't get on
the board again until the fourth quarter, when they scored 21
points.
</P>
<P>
   UH made it 31-14 with 11:55 remaining when Iglesias hauled in
McKinley's fourth-down pass for a 17-yard TD after T.J. Light, a
first-time starter at linebacker, made the first of his two fumble
recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   But Amey's 40-yard burst and Gerena's 15-yard TD run enabled the
Cadets to reel off 80 yards in four plays and 84 seconds, making it
38-14.
</P>
<P>
   Light's fumble recovery set up McKinley's 10-yard TD pass to
James with 6:08 remaining. Trailing 38-21, the Cougars recovered
the ensuing onside kick but failed to convert.
</P>
<P>
   UH wrapped up the scoring with 51 seconds remaining on Iglesias'
38-yard catch-and-run from McKinley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
