<HEADER>
A0583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TENNESSEE-GEORGIA     10-11 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TENNESSEE-GEORGIA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee's defense leaves Georgia clueless
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Ga. _ They came from the sides and from up the middle, and
there were times when it seemed there were more than the standard
complement of 11 bursting into the backfield and ruining plays with
each and every snap.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Carter knew it was coming. Doing anything about it was a
very different matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't handle it,'' Georgia's freshman quarterback said.
``We couldn't figure out what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple, really. When Tennessee 22, Georgia 3 was safely in the
books, Al Wilson probably didn't mean to be quite so blunt, but
there was plenty of truth in the Volunteer linebacker's bottom-line
assessment of Carter's long Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about frustrating anybody,'' Wilson said. ``But I
knew if we kept it up and never quit hitting him, he'd fold.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Carter had plenty of company in that regard as the
Bulldogs' hoped-for coming-out party fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   With running back Jamal Lewis lost to knee surgery and Wilson
playing with a bad shoulder, No. 4 Tennessee still strolled into
Sanford Stadium and steamrolled No. 7 Georgia in a game that may
not have been even as close as the one-sided score.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia got just 195 passing yards (59 of those on one play) on
37 attempts from Carter, the hero of the previous week's 28-27
victory at LSU. The minor-league baseball veteran was intercepted
twice, sacked twice and chased all over the turf by a blitzing
Volunteers defense that refused to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's chief ally, the ubiquitous Champ Bailey, was largely
missing in action, too. Bailey had the perfect stage to launch a
serious Heisman Trophy bid, but after a first-quarter interception,
things went downhill in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   As a receiver, Bailey had just three catches for 21 yards. Two
punt returns netted 35 yards, but without effect. In the secondary,
he was beaten by Cedrick Wilson on Tennessee's first touchdown. And
later in the decisive third period, Bailey's audition as passer was
a fourth-down heave that was easily intercepted by safety Deon
Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just outplayed us in every way,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Stephens (20 carries, 107 yards) and Travis Henry (16
carries, 53 yards) did just fine as replacements for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Jamal,'' Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin said, ``we
took it as motivation to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Tennessee would find a way on a picture-perfect
autumn afternoon, making Georgia's stay in the national
championship picture short and not particularly sweet. Supposedly
eager for revenge after the Volunteers allegedly ran up the score
last year in Knoxville, the Bulldogs instead looked like what most
observers pegged them as at the start of the year: young and
talented, but maybe a year or so away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we may have gotten caught up in the hype a little too
much,'' Carter admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but it's just as likely that Georgia got caught up in
an inspired effort on the part of a Tennessee team largely
dismissed as a national contender in the wake of Lewis'
season-ending knee surgery. Martin, asked to replace Peyton
Manning, struggled through a pair of first-half interceptions, but
the Vols used three Jeff Hall field goals (27, 39 and 43 yards) to
more than offset a 48-yarder by Georgia's Hap Hines for 9-3 lead at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Once Martin (seven of nine passing for 64 yards and two
touchdowns in the second half) regained his composure, Tennessee
put this one away with remarkable ease and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols moved 65 yards to the game's first touchdown, a
three-yard pass from Martin to Cedrick Wilson, who beat Bailey on
an out pattern in the right side of the end zone with 12:31 left in
the third quarter. The two-point conversion try failed when Martin
was stopped just short of the goal line, but the points wouldn't be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter's deep throw for Thad Parker was intercepted by
Dwayne Goodrich and returned to the Tennessee 41, the Volunteers
were off again. A 20-yard pass from Martin to Jermaine Copeland on
third-and-four was the centerpiece of a drive that ended on a
three-yard pass from Martin to Peerless Price to make it 22-3 with
6:06 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the only ones among a crowd of 86,117 who seemed to be
enjoying this surprising turn of events were the orange-and-white
clad visitors who filled the west end zone and part of the east
upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   One sideline was pretty happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unbelievably proud of our football team,'' said Tennessee
coach Phil Fulmer, whose feud with Georgia counterpart Jim Donnan
over a late Manning touchdown in last year's game helped spice up
the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not supposed to be this good.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, they are, though. And with a week off to ponder it
all and prepare for a home game against Alabama, the Vols left town
5-0 and feeling pretty pleased with themselves _ though not too
pleased, Wilson hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about this defense,'' Al Wilson said, ``is that
we're never satisfied. That's what you're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   On a surprising day in Georgia, the Vols got what they were
looking for and then some.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
