<HEADLINE>
SHODDY UMPIRING SHOULDN'T HAPPEN THIS TIME OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again the playoffs, a time when baseball's brightest
spotlight should be firmly on the playing field, are being
overshadowed by shoddy umpiring.
</P>
<P>
   As he's done more and more lately, New York Yankees owner
 &UR; George
 &UR; Steinbrenner is making a lot of sense these days when he says the
entire major league umpiring system should be revamped. Many
umpires do a wonderful job, but the ones who do not stand out so
blatantly that they end up bringing the entire group down with
them.
</P>
<P>
   Never was it more evident than in the past two weeks when
American League umpires  &UR; Joe Brinkman and  &UR; Ted Hendry either lost
control of a game or badly blew a call. Again, the call is being
made that the very best umpires are the only ones who should be
working in October.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have a mixture of those who have earned the right to
be there on merit and those who have the most time umpiring in the
majors. The result has been a sad mess that is diminishing the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The best four clubs in the majors are still alive. Why shouldn't
the best umpires be there to officiate the games?
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Baltimore General Manager  &UR; Pat Gillick, as respected a
person as there is in the game, voiced his displeasure with the
current system last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's back to the same old story _ you've got to have a real
stringent review process,'' Gillick said. ``They've got to be
reviewed constantly. If there are problems with umpires, if they
continue to make mistakes, the lower-rated guys have got to be
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope, at least in big-league front offices, is that the new
executive vice president of the game, former Oakland GM/President
 &UR; Sandy Alderson, will make this issue his top priority. Alderson is
very aware of the problem and may very well be the right person to
straighten this mess out. &QL; 
Down and out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a club with a $74 million payroll finishes under .500 and
never really contends, you know it was just a matter of time before
some serious finger-pointing takes place.
</P>
<P>
   Count Baltimore hitting coach  &UR; Rick Down as the Orioles'
scapegoat for the poor 1998 season. Manager  &UR; Ray Miller managed to
get Down out of the Orioles coaching staff and replaced by  &UR; Terry
Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know that Terry is outstanding individually and
personally,'' said Miller, who has known Crowley since the two were
with the Orioles in the mid-1970's. ``He was a great player when he
was in Baltimore, and he had a great rapport with people in
Minnesota from what I understand. He did an outstanding job with
guys like ( &UR; Matt)  &UR; Lawton out there . . . He has a great ability to
make adjustments during a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Down, a finalist for the Orioles manager post when  &UR; Davey
Johnson was fired last winter, had one season remaining on his
contract. The Orioles, who hit a then-major league record 257 home
runs in 1996 under Down, will pay the remainder of the deal off.
</P>
<P>
   The knock on Down, at least the one coming from the Orioles
front office, was that he worked the players too hard, requiring
extra batting practice that owner  &UR; Peter Angelos believed led to
the late-season slump of  &UR; B.J. Surhoff, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray called and told me that Mr. Angelos had not been happy
with our offense this year and for the past two years,'' said Down,
the former hitting coach for the Yankees under  &UR; Buck Showalter.
``That's my area. If it wasn't up to par, then I'll shoulder the
responsibility . . . I didn't know if it would be me, but I figured
something had to happen.'' &QL; 
About a quart low? &QL; 
Houston outfielder  &UR; Carl Everett, who infuriated his teammates and
the opposing San Diego Padres during the division series when he
disparaged  &UR; Kevin Brown, did it again once the Astros were
eliminated by the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be embarrassed,'' Everett said. ``We got beat by a
team that was a lot older and a lot slower. Their bones are
breaking. They basically crawled onto the field and beat us. It's a
shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much talent. We were the feared team, and no one
wanted to play us. The way we played, we deserved to go home. What
you do in the regular season means nothing in the playoffs. It
comes down to whichever team wants it the most. They wanted it
more, and that's why they're going on and we're packing.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Padres dismissed Everett's remarks as those
of an immature 26-year-old who needs some counseling from some of
his teammates. &QL; 
ALCS subplot &QL; 
Opposing outfielders  &UR; Brian Giles of Cleveland and  &UR; Shane Spencer
of the New York Yankees have an interesting past together. The two
grew up in El Cajon, Calif., and played baseball and football at
Granite Hills High together.
</P>
<P>
   They also overcame long odds to reach their current status.
Giles was selected in the 17th round in 1989 while Spencer was a
28th round pick in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the best of friends, but we're pretty good
friends,'' Spencer said. `We've been playing together since we were
10 years old. Seeing Brian make it to the major leagues was good
motivation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles was a center fielder and running back in high school.
Spencer was a left fielder and linebacker on the same teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gratifying that we've been able to do this,'' Giles said,
``because nobody gave him or me a chance to do anything in the
major leagues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; From the Hart: Cleveland General Manager  &UR; John Hart on his club
being an overwhelming underdog against the Yankees: ``People are
missing the boat if they think we are the Washington Generals and
the Yankees are the Harlem Globetrotters. We are not cannon
fodder.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Talk about the rich getting richer: As difficult as it may be
to comprehend, there is a strong belief among baseball executives
that Atlanta may make a shocking move this winter by trading one of
its big three starters _  &UR; Greg Maddux,  &UR; Tom Glavine or
 &UR; John Smoltz _ and then signing free agent and Georgia native &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Rupert Jones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maybe he chatted with Prince: The pitcher formerly known as
 &UR; Dennis Reyes has requested his name be spelled  &UR; Dennys Reyes. One
member of the Cincinnati public relations staff quipped: ``Yeah,
and if he keeps eating we'll have to put the apostrophe in there
(Denny's).''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Still searching for Davey Johnson's replacement: Baltimore
owner  &UR; Peter Angelos telephoned  &UR; Jim Leyland and offered him $3
million per season for three years if he reneged on his three-year
$6 million deal with Colorado. Leyland, who had already agreed to
the Rockies' offer, declined. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The home run allowed by  &UR; Kerry Lightenberg to San Diego's
 &UR; Ken Caminiti in the 10th inning of Game 1 of the National League
Championship Series on Wednesday night was the first run allowed by
a Braves reliever in 20 post-season innings, a span that dated to
 &UR; Jim
 &UR; Leyritz's memorable home run in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Texas first baseman  &UR; Will Clark's post-season drought continued.
Clark was 1 for 11 with no RBIs and no hits with three at-bats with
runners in scoring position during the Rangers' three-game loss to
the Yankees in the division series. He has not had a post-season
RBI since 11 playoff games dating to the 1989 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frank Thomas moved into fourth place on the Chicago White Sox's
all-time list for total bases with 2,570, moving ahead of
 &UR; Eddie Collins. The three ahead are:  &UR; Luke Appling, 3,528;  &UR; Nellie
Fox, 3,118; and  &UR; Harold Baines 2,811.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto GM  &UR; Gord Ash will call in Manager  &UR; Tim Johnson and
pitching coach  &UR; Mel Queen for a three-way meeting to see if the
latter two can iron out their differences. Johnson and Queen did
not speak for most of the final two months of the season. If the
two cannot work out their problem one may be asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   After Pittsburgh's September collapse (the Pirates were 5-22 in
the final month) owner  &UR; Kevin McClatchy voiced his displeasure with
how the club mailed it in down the stretch. Manager
 &UR; Gene Lamont will be on the hot-seat next season. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Diego insists it will be able to move reliever  &UR; Randy
 &UR; Myers and the hefty $12 million remaining on his contract. Expect
the Los Angeles Dodgers, who are fairly resigned to losing closer
 &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Shaw, to be among the most interested.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Felipe Alou is clearly the Dodgers' primary choice to become
just their fifth manager since leaving Brooklyn in 1957. But
Montreal, realizing it needs credibility if the Expos are to make a
real move to fund a downtown baseball stadium, may match any offer
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Should  &UR; Alou bolt for LA, expect  &UR; Kevin Kennedy's name to
surface as next Expos manager. Kennedy, who managed Texas and
Boston, cut his big-league teeth as Alou's bench coach in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Sean Casey expected to be Cincinnati's first baseman for
the next half dozen years, the Reds are looking to move Valley
native  &UR; Paul Konerko. Could Konerko head right back to Los Angeles,
possibly for  &UR; Shaw? It's a good fit for both clubs.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is once again wrestling with the idea of bringing back
ageless outfielder  &UR; Willie McGee. The Cardinals favorite will be 40
before next season starts and remains one of the best clubhouse
influences in an otherwise fractured clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   There's a possibility Philadelphia may be willing to trade
closer  &UR; Ricky Bottalico this winter. The hard-throwing right-hander
only saved six games this year but that was mostly because he had a
bone spur removed from an elbow in April. The Phillies need help
and Bottalico is someone who may bring it in return. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
