<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAIL SMALL, BUT THEY'RE PLENTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TONTO BASIN, Ariz. - Travis Williams of Chandler was walking out
of Butcher Hook Cafe just after noon on Friday, the opening day of
Gambel quail season in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He looked pretty satisfied and stopped for a talk.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists had predicted that this could be the best quail
season since 1993, the year before declining years of precipitation
that led to drought and some of the poorest quail seasons in
memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw more birds today than in the past five years put
together,'' Williams said. ``They were all small birds _ this
year's (hatch of) birds.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a point there. Last year there weren't a lot of quail,
and most of them were adults. They're much harder to hunt than
young, stupid quail. They prefer running far ahead and then
flushing out of gun range. They didn't get to be adults by being
dummies.
</P>
<P>
   But El Nino rains during the winter and spring brought a great
hatch of quail. Biologists say rain at the right times is the
single most important factor in quail reproduction. It provides the
right green plants to spur hens to lay more eggs, brings on the
growth of more cover and seeds to protect and sustain the birds and
causes larger insect hatches that provide needed nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists said the quail reproduced into August, hence some
really small quail for the opening of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a dog,'' Williams said. ``I had five I couldn't
find in all that cover or I would have limited out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was getting hot, in the 90s, and time to take a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hot,'' Williams said. ``Time to go back to the
trailer, drink a beer and take a nap. We'll go back out at 5 when
it's cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his hunting group spent the entire morning hunt in El
Oso Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just chased them around in circles. I've had enough
sweating for one morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Horejsi, a wildlife manager for the Arizona Game and Fish
Department, said he wasn't seeing a lot of birds but heard a lot of
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys without dogs are really having trouble finding their
birds,'' he said. ``There are a lot of birds, but as you heard,
some of them are really small.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Rambo, who lives in the basin, chipped in that ``it takes a
good shot to get those little birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Horejsi said there a lot of hunters but that they were scattered
all over the basin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday will be a big day here,'' he said. ``All the guys who
couldn't get off Friday will show up.''
</P>
<P>
   That made for a big day in the basin on Saturday. Besides all
the hunters, a bass fishing tournament drew another couple hundred
people with boats.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beauchamp of Payson and his son, Jimmy, of Phoenix were
taking advantage of both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bass fishing and quail hunting,'' the elder Beauchamp
said. ``Right now, we're doing much better with the bass.'' He said
the two fished Wednesday evening and Thursday morning and took
about 40, mostly on top-water lures.
</P>
<P>
   Son Jimmy had seen a covey of quail walk up a draw toward the
lake. He got on the shoreline and shot three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dropping off the boat back in Payson, then we'll come
back and just hunt quail,'' the elder Beauchamp said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the lush cover also brought on good reproduction in
rodents, rattlesnake populations increased. But no one was
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Denson of Gilbert and Paul Kaminski and Don Striker, both of
Chandler, said in their hunt together they had heard one
rattlesnake but had seen five tarantulas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw tons of 40-bird coveys,'' Denson said. ``This is the
best it's been in at least seven years.`` They, too, complained of
lost birds in the heavy cover and a majority of small quail. But
they were loving the number of birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little birds aren't too smart,'' Striker said. ``You
have to run at them to flush them, but they just run around in
circles. But the later it got the better they held.''
</P>
<P>
   But the heat turned out to be a major factor for Kaminski and
Striker. Although they carried water, they ranged too far from
their vehicle on this hot day, running out of water and struggling
to get back.
</P>
<P>
   Rambo's hunt wasn't as good. His hunting companion was late
showing up, then could only hunt a short time because he became
ill.
</P>
<P>
   But when the two entered a rugged draw at 3:30 p.m., quail
starting flushing everywhere. Coveys rose one after another, and
not all of them were small birds. And the 40-bird coveys were not
an exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a good quail year. Compared with the past three or
four, it will be paradise. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
