 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tech overcomes Oklahoma State
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ Jones Stadium on Saturday night was the site of the
annual homecoming game at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   It might also have been a laboratory for the Red Raiders and
Oklahoma State Cowboys, a pair of Big 12 South foes that had
something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   With Dorian Pitts stirring things up on defense by blocking a
punt to set up a first-half touchdown and returning a fumble 53
yards for a fourth-period TD, the Raiders frolicked to a 24-17
victory that just may have proved to the pollsters they belong
among the nation's Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Tech, though unranked, improved to 6-0. With a 3-0 mark in Big
12 play, they remain tied with Texas A&AMP;M atop the South Division.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the third time in school history the Raiders have
begun a season 6-0 and the first since 1976, when Steve Sloan, in
his second season as coach, led them to an 8-0 start and 10-2
overall record. They were also 6-0 in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to be 6-0. But there's still room for
improvement,'' Pitts said. ``As long as we keep getting better,
we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oklahoma State (2-3, 1-2) failed in an effort to
prove that last week's 24-17 defeat to No. 2 Nebraska wasn't truly
indicative of its talents. Perhaps the emotional strain of allowing
that one to slip away had a carry-over effect.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Cowboys did show the Raiders, however, was that
Tech's rush defense, fourth-best in the NCAA and No. 1 in the Big
12, might need a little more tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Nathan Simmons (16 carries, 81 yards) and
quarterback Tony Lindsay (17 carries, 59 yards) combined for 140
yards on the ground as OSU rolled up 281 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not enough to overcome a rather balky offense and
11 penalties that yielded a costly 132 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to make critical mistakes,'' OSU coach Bob Simmons
said. ``Until we eliminate those types of things we will continue
to struggle. I thought our offense played well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   During one fourth-period drive by Tech that produced a 32-yard
field goal by Chris Birkholz for a 17-10 lead, the Cowboys were
called for a dead-ball personal foul and a 15-yard facemask
infraction.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts applied the clincher when he picked up a fumble by Lindsay
and raced 53 yards for a touchdown with 2:53 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took one bounce and bounced up in my hands,'' Pitts said.
``I saw nothing but greenery ahead of me, and I had no other choice
but to score.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU got its final tally on an eight-yard pass from Lindsay to
Terrance Richardson with 2:20 left.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the heroics by Pitts, Tech used a pair of
touchdown passes from quarterback Rob Peters to receiver Donnie
Hart to shake out of an early-game slumber and beat OSU for the
third consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice win,'' said Tech coach Spike Dykes. ``It was
probably the best team win we had. The defense gave our offense a
number of chances to get back into our game. And our offense did a
good job of getting back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, making only his second start this season after suffering
an injury in the opener, completed eight of 15 passes for 74 yards
and the two scoring strikes to Hart (four receptions, 53 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Tech tailback Ricky Williams, the nation's second-leading ground
gainer, carried 25 times for 97 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders' usually solid run defense, meanwhile, was
tested from the moment the Cowboys first got their hands on the
football. OSU stormed to an early 7-0 lead, using only one pass in
a 12-play, 51-yard drive that followed a 29-yard punt by Tech's
Brian Roberson. Reserve fullback Brian Aikins got the touchdown on
a one-yard plunge.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first period ended, the Cowboys had already run
for 92 yards, far exceeding the 71.6 yards averaged by Tech
opponents coming in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also had a 10-0 lead, courtesy of a 38-yard field
goal by Tim Sydnes that came with 40 seconds left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of defense wasn't the only phase of the game giving Tech
coach Spike Dykes headaches. Williams bolted for 22 yards on the
Raiders' first possession, but that was about all the offense Dykes
got through the first 15 minutes. Tech came out of the first period
with only two total yards of offense, minus-two yards rushing and a
goose egg on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Quicker than a swish from the tail of their mascot horse, the
Raiders used a fumble recovery and blocked punt near the end of the
second period to right the foundering ship.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had recovered a fumble by Peters and set up shop on
the 43 of Tech. Two plays later, OSU returned the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chaloupka had come on to replace Lindsay, the 1997 Big 12
Freshman of the Year, at quarterback. And after a holding call on
the Cowboys, a pitchout by Chaloupka was fumbled by tailback Jamaal
Fobbs and recovered by Tech middle linebacker Tim Duffie.
</P>
<P>
   With only his second completed pass of the evening, Peters
brought the Raiders within 10-7. Hart got behind defensive back
Evan Howell in the end zone for the 14-yard TD reception.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had to leap and extend to bring in a high spiral from
Peters, Hart executed the move as if in a ballet. Chris Birkholz
tacked on the point-after.
</P>
<P>
   On the very next possession by OSU, Tech was opportunistic
again. The Cowboys in three plays were unable to get a first down
and brought on freshman Scott Elder to punt. His kick was blocked
by Pitts, giving the Raiders the ball at the Cowboys' 26.
</P>
<P>
   Following an offsides call on OSU, Peters for the second time
found Hart, this time with a bullet over the middle. The touchdown
covered 18 yards, and with Birkholz's extra point, gave Tech its
first lead, 14-10, with 3:44 left before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got flat,'' said Nathan Simmons. ``And we shot ourselves in
the foot when we had the momentum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
