<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAGGING DEVILS APPEAR CLUELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - After the leprechaun pranced off the field, they
looked at each other in bewilderment. In the post-mortem, they
sounded clueless.
</P>
<P>
   How can Arizona State be 2-4?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows,'' Chad Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kealy, what's wrong with you? ASU's starting quarterback
shifted in his chair like a witness testifying before a federal
grand jury. Knocked woozy against Southern California and replaced
a week later by Elliott after throwing his third interception,
Kealy either didn't wish to answer the tough, rapid-fire questions
that came at him, or as probably was the case, the sophomore simply
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your guess,'' Ryan replied, ``is as good as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, the Sun Devils were ranked No. 8 in the
nation. Now they're just another ho-hum, so-what middle of the
Pac-10 team.
</P>
<P>
   ASU may finish 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   This season has been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   This season is o-v-e-r.
</P>
<P>
   ASU looks like a team lacking focus and confidence. A team short
on leadership. A talented team that is playing hard but not smart.
A team going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   Like every Bruce Snyder team, this one took a solemn oath before
the season began. The four-point pledge is displayed on a wall in
the room in Sun Devil Stadium where Elliott and Kealy and several
teammates blinked at their inquisitors after Saturday's 28-9
surrender to Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   The oath reads:
</P>
<P>
   1. I will hustle.
</P>
<P>
   2. I will display courage.
</P>
<P>
   3. I will know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   4. I will care about my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils may be living up to 1, 2, and 4. ``We're still a
family,'' safety Mitchell Freedman made a point of saying.
</P>
<P>
   It's pledge No. 3 that has left this team frustrated, perplexed,
at a loss for words. The Devils look like they don't know what to
do. It's a team without answers. This team looks lost.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to cite the problems, some of which are obvious, even the
head coach couldn't be specific _ or he chose not to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's something you can pinpoint,'' Snyder said.
He looked and sounded like a man who welcomed a break in the
schedule. Snyder promised to evaluate every position and every
player between now and the next game Oct. 22. The coaches must look
in the mirror, too.
</P>
<P>
   The next opponent, Stanford, is one team ASU figured it should
beat. Now, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The offense is studded with talent, like a ham with cloves.
Offense was to be ASU's strength. Against Notre Dame, which had
allowed an average of 28 points per game, Kealy and his teammates
were almost as irrelevant as public address announcer Jeff Munn
after the stadium suffered a power outage at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   During the second half, Munn's mike was dead. The scoreboard was
blank. (Thought for the Day: What if this had happened during the
evening Fiesta Bowl national championship game?) So was the ASU
offense until Snyder pulled the plug on Kealy and Elliott directed
the Devils on their only touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   But to blame only Kealy would be like blaming the power failure
on a freshman student's dorm room hot plate. ``I dunno. I just
plugged it in and the campus went dark . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The defense couldn't stop Notre Dame's fullback trap. Backup
fullback Joey Goodspeed ran for 109 yards on four carries. What if
Joey had ``great'' speed?
</P>
<P>
   Penalties were suicidal. With ASU trailing, 14-3, Freedman
intercepted at the ASU 1-yard line. But the Devils defense was
offside, nullifying the theft. Two plays later, the Fighting Irish
scored their third touchdown. Game, set, match.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder obviously overestimated his team. Many of us did. Part of
the problem is leadership. The Devils miss not having players like
Jake Plummer and Pat Tillman, whose contribution to ASU's football
revival extended far beyond their ability to make big plays. Both
have personalities their teammates rallied around. Who are the
leaders on this team?
</P>
<P>
   The game over, ASU players filed silently toward their locker
room, as empty as they felt. Behind them, they could hear the
cheers of happy Notre Dame fans celebrating with the players who
were leaving the other end of the field, their gold helmets
gleaming in the sun. Notre Dame is 4-1. ASU is _ inexcusably _ 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   One school's disappointing slide coupled with the other's third
win in a row calls to mind the old story about the two fellows who
passed each other in midair, traveling in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know anything about parachutes?'' one shouted, tugging
frantically at his rip cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the other called out as he rocketed skyward. ``You know
anything about gas stoves?'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
