<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: SUBS TO CORRECT BYLINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Freshman has hand &QL; 
in maroon-letter day
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
CCOLLEGE STATION _ This was the day the campus of the state's
agricultural and mechanical school became a monkey-free
environment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the day Texas A&AMP;M Aggies have waited for all of this
decade, if not all of their lives. Doing all the things their
critics said they couldn't or wouldn't do, the Aggies ambushed No.
2 Nebraska 28-21 on Saturday, and in the process they uncovered a
new star of field and screen.
</P>
<P>
   The key figure in this historic win was a huge freshman
fullback, who had been, until now, a fringe player. Ja'Mar Toombs
sped 71 yards to the Nebraska one-yard line to set up A&AMP;M's second
touchdown, and he scored their last with a bull rush from the
three. That one put the Aggies up by 21 points on the first play of
the fourth quarter, giving them the cushion they would need so
urgently in the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs is too young and earnest and carefree to understand he
was discovered Saturday, or that his long gallop will burrow its
way into Aggies' memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grew to a man today,'' said Dante Hall, who had previously
employed Ja'Mar as a blocking back.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 60,798 embraced him, dragging out the middle
letters in his last name, as sports crowds relish doing, so that
the chant of ``Toooombs'' droned on through the day.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, at least for a day, the Nebraska dynasty suffered a
tomb-like fate.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Toombs each gained over 100 yards, Ja'Mar getting his
on 10 carries _ one more than he had recorded in the previous five
games.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Hall was asked if he felt ``a little jealous''
of the freshman's reception. Dante didn't understand the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the way the crowd chanted his name,'' added the
reporter, bucking for dumb-question-of the-month honors. ``They
loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall cocked his head and said: ``They loved all of us. Hey, man,
are you drunk?''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies in the crowd refused to leave their seats after the
game. They cheered, they swayed, they sang the war hymn and they
gave each player a standing ovation as he ducked under the stands
and into the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies had scored on the first pass they completed, 81 yards
from a scrambling Randy McCown to Chris Taylor, who said he was
surprised when the play worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had tried it a couple times before,'' he said. ``I turned
around and no one was there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was virtually the only success the Aggies had in the air,
completing only one more out of eight attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Ja'Mar's explosion up the middle of the field that
gave the Aggies partisans their best clue this would be their day.
Facing third-and-two from the Aggies' 28, Toombs burst up the
middle and found a suddenly vacant field in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually,'' he said, ``the strongside linebacker is in the
hole. But he overran the play. There was some daylight, and I just
kept running''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the only person between Toombs and the goal line was
the back judge. While running free, and trying to avoid the
official, Toombs managed to take a peek at the Sony JumboTron
behind the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know there was a (Nebraska) guy behind me,'' he said,
``until I looked at the big screen and saw him. I was about the
20-yard line. The guy behind him wasn't on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them tripped him up at the one, and Hall scored the
touchdown a play later. Toombs ran like he was on a track, hardly
varying from his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running as fast as I can,'' he said, ``because Nebraska
is famous for its speed. The official ran right beside me for a
while. I could see it in his face, he was scared and trying to get
out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a shrewd use of technology by the Kilgore
freshman, who glanced at the screen rather than turn his head.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs has virtually come out of nowhere to help the Aggies
break out to a 5-1 record and a national ranking. He reported for
fall practice at 270 pounds, went on a strict diet and workout
program and in three months managed to slim to 260. He would not be
starting if the two fullbacks ahead of him had not become
indisposed.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs has been compared to George Woodard, an A&AMP;M fullback of
the '70s who weighed 275 and was sometimes mistaken for Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, the Aggies rolled back the years Saturday,
on a day of buttermilk skies. Arguably, this victory ranks among
the greatest in Aggies history, a list that would include the 1939
national champions' win over Tulane in the Sugar Bowl and beating
Texas for the first time in Memorial Stadium in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were hanging on by their fingernails in the fourth
quarter, but hang on they did, ending Nebraska's winning streak at
19, the longest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Few teams in college football lore needed a victory so badly,
and few produced one any bigger. The word gargantuan comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The win was A&AMP;M's first over a Top 10 team since 1989, when they
turned back No. 8 Houston and eventual Heisman Trophy winner Andre
Ware 17-13. R.C. Slocum was in his first season as the school's
head coach, and the Aggies five weeks earlier had opened with a win
over No. 7 LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Since then they had hit nothing but dry holes, losing nine in a
row to ranked teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have heard around here,'' said tight end Dan Campbell,
``was how we couldn't win a big game, that coach Slocum can't coach
a big game. Well, we did it. That's all I've got to say. We did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum called it the biggest win of his career and, in a nice
rounding of the circle, cited Toombs as a symbol of why it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ja'Mar was widely recruited,'' said Slocum, impeccably attired
in maroon sportcoat and silver hair. ``He was told if he ever
wanted to win a big game, beat a big-time team, he had to go off to
Ohio State or Florida State or somewhere else. I don't think they
can say that anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
