<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SITS ATOP BIG SKY WITH WIN OVER MONTANA 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;  NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ After 36 seasons of chuck-and-duck football,
Cal State Northridge finally has a defense. And it's a darn fine
one at that.
<P>
   CSUN quarterback Marcus Brady was again exciting, scrambling to
make big plays, but even he fell into the backdrop Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The defense of the 23rd-ranked Matadors was the show-stopper as
it throttled No.18 Montana 21-7 in front of a season-high 5,237 at
North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The seven points are the fewest the Matadors have allowed in a
Big Sky game and just the second time in 36 games they've allowed
less than 10. It's also the least number of points Montana (3-3,
1-2 Big Sky) has scored in 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this defense I could say that's going to happen quite a
bit this year,'' Brady said. ``We have a great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Couple CSUN's fourth straight win with Weber State's loss to
Montana State and the Matadors CSUN (4-1, 3-0) sit alone atop the
Big Sky standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were nine teams at the Big Sky Conference (media day)
that all thought they could win, and some are finding a way, and
we're one of them,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said. ``Montana
definitely played good enough on defense to win the football
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, part of the reason Montana scored just one
touchdown was the unexpected absence of All-American quarterback
Brian Ah Yat, who had a bruised back. But backup Seth Davis proved
his worth last week when he threw for 297 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors had to deal with a defensive line devastated by
injuries. But even with seven defensive linemen on the sideline in
street clothes, the Matadors were able to put pressure on Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest play was turned in by nose guard Quinton Reed late
in the fourth quarter. On fourth-and-1 from Montana's own 24, Reed,
a converted linebacker playing his first game on the defensive
line, dropped Brian Gales for a 4-yard loss. Four plays later
Melvin Blue scored on a 4-yard run to give CSUN a 21-7 lead with
1:56 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the dude fumbled the ball,'' Reed said. ``I knew I
hit him, but I thought I hit him and we got the recovery. I didn't
know whether he made it or not. I went blank. I just knew I had to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's defense, which played with five defensive backs most of
the way, sacked Davis six times. The Matadors also had a crucial
interception in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On its previous possession Montana answered a 51-yard scoring
pass from Brady to Jimmy Greninger with a 13-yard pass from Davis
to Travis Walker. It tied the game at 7-7 midway through the third
quarter. But with the Grizzlies driving again, Matadors cornerback
Donnell Day intercepted Davis inside the 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to have confused (Montana's offense) because we never
ran four corners in at one time (before this game),'' said CSUN
safety Jeremy Golden, who had 11 tackles. ``They might have
expected it to happen, but they would have thought there would have
been some linebackers covering down somewhere. It just didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when CSUN's offense was able to get into the end zone, the
defense played a big part in setting it up.
</P>
<P>
   After Ethan Beck's 66-yard punt pinned Montana on its own 3-yard
line, CSUN's offense got the ball back on the Grizzlies' 47. Only
then was Brady able to work his magic, though first the Matadors
had to overcome a 57-yard touchdown pass that was negated by a
holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But Brady converted a pair of third downs to push the ball to
the 21, and two plays later he connected with Aaron Arnold for a
21-yard scoring pass over the middle to give CSUN a 13-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the difference in the game was the Brady kid making
big-time plays in the critical situations,'' Montana coach Mick
Dennehy said. ``We were close, and we had him in our grasp a lot,
but you have to finish. Being close on him doesn't make any
difference.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
