r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-NOTRE-DAME-AZ     10-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NOTRE-DAME-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS GO OUT ON ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The message by Arizona State players afterward
was this: We're not a bad team.
</P>
<P>
   They just play one on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Is was as if a hand reached down and pulled the plug on ASU's
season. In front of a sellout Sun Devil Stadium crowd of 73,501, a
regional television audience and much of the Valley's clergy, ASU
was humiliated, 28-9, by Notre Dame Saturday in a game marked by a
second-half power outage on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a cancer inside,'' cornerback Courtney Jackson said.
``We've got to get the tumor out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils fall to 2-4. Yes, ``2-4.'' This from a team that
was a preseason Top 10 pick in many polls. With games against No.
15 Oregon and No. 10 Arizona ahead, ASU is in real danger of
finishing below .500.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils could have a quarterback controversy in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder replaced sophomore Ryan Kealy with
redshirt freshman Chad Elliott late in the third quarter after
Kealy threw his third interception. Afterward, Snyder said he would
use the Sun Devils' bye week to evaluate all positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan is struggling,'' Snyder said. ``There's nothing in him
that lacks effort or courage. I feel for him. Certainly not all our
problems are because of him, but we are struggling at that position
. . . There's a hesitancy to him. He's pressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy was at a loss for an explanation, but said at the time,
``I did force the ball.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 13 of 22 passes for three interceptions and no
touchdowns. He has thrown seven interceptions this season, the same
amount he threw all last year. Elliott was 6 of 8 for 47 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame, meanwhile, improved to 4-1 behind a defense that has
struggled this season. Offensively, quarterback Jarious Jackson
only had to pass for 69 yards thanks to a ground game that got 109
yards from fullback Joey Goodspeed and 84 from tailback Autry
Denson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition either brings out the best or worst in you,''
Fighting Irish Coach Bob Davie said. ``I think it brings out the
best in us.''
</P>
<P>
   And apparently the worst in the Sun Devils, who continue to beat
themselves with mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Against Southern California last week, ASU lost because of a
blocked punt and an interception that were returned for touchdowns
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Notre Dame's first touchdown was set up by a Kealy
interception, and the second was a 25-yard interception return by
A'Jani Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays before the Fighting Irish's third score, a 1-yard run
by Denson in the third quarter, Sun Devils safety Mitchell Freedman
intercepted a Jackson pass at the ASU 1-yard line, but it was
called back by an offside call.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame's final score, another 1-yard run by Denson, in the
fourth quarter, was highlighted by Goodspeed's 60-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the game, ASU's defense was solid, but it did have
problems with the fullback trap.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the Sun Devils to do some serious soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think sometimes people might take a play off here or
there,'' linebacker Joe Cesta said. ``They might not think the
ball's coming at them. Things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder insisted afterward that his team's problems are not
because of lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not do the smartest things,'' he said. ``But this team
really wants to be good. They try really hard, and this comes from
a professional coach who gives my life to coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   They may want to be good, but at this point, they're not.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the coaches will give serious consideration to starting
Elliott against Stanford on Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not up to me, that's up to the coaches,'' Elliott said.
``I'll be ready if they need me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback J.R. Redmond, who rushed for 94 yards and had ASU's
only touchdown, a 1-yard run in the fourth quarter, said, ``Chad
Elliott did a great job. It's tough for a backup quarterback
because you don't get as many snaps during the week.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a surreal game throughout. The power outage, which was
due to the failure of a transformer on the main concourse of Sun
Devil Stadium, came during halftime and knocked out the public
address system and the scoreboard for the entire second half. It
also sent ABC off the air for much of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been the best thing for ASU fans watching the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hurts,'' Jackson said. ``Our only goal going in was
to be 3-3. To have that goal destroyed . . . We've got to take a
few days off and each person has to evaluate himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
