<HEADER>
A0596 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOL-HNS &LR;      10-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Fujii/ChronicleRicky Williams does an impressive Doak
Walker imitation while wearing Walker's old number Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton Bowl brings forth special memories
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
DDALLAS _ For one day, the Longhorns could reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this team in the orange and white on this day, in this
setting, was like going back to a time when men were men, Texas was
Texas and there was no reason to believe things would change.
</P>
<P>
   The smell of funnel cakes and crispy corn dogs wafted through
the air Saturday afternoon at the Texas State Fairgrounds. And the
feel of old-time Texas Longhorns football made its way to the
Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That was saltwater taffy being spun under the shadows of the
giant ferris wheel. Just like old times.
</P>
<P>
   And that was Texas 34, Oklahoma 3 in an old-fashioned shucking
that had everything but James Street, although if you squinted,
Major ``General'' Applewhite bore a striking resemblance.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one bringing back memories.
</P>
<P>
   That was No. 37 dancing across the Cotton Bowl turf, looking so
graceful yet powerful, carrying seemingly defenseless Sooners with
him and later talking about things like perspective, humility and
just wanting to help the team.
</P>
<P>
   Texas tailback Ricky Williams brought back the days of legendary
SMU running back Doak Walker, all right, but this time the Doaker
wore orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doak was a role model for me,'' Williams said. ``It was
special to wear his number.''
</P>
<P>
   Start to merciful finish, much about this game was like taking a
nostalgic trip down a nostalgic trail.
</P>
<P>
   Those were old-fashioned cotton candy vendors, carnival barkers
and merry-go-rounds making the grounds buzz on a beautiful Saturday
afternoon for football that might not have been out of Norman
Rockwell's book, but certainly Cactus Pryor's.
</P>
<P>
   And those were Longhorns fans _ smiling, of all things _ acting
as if the past 18 or so years were just a bad dream. No Fred Akers.
No John Mackovic. No up-and-down emotions or losing seasons. And
definitely, no losing games 66-3.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one day, sure. It was only a time to reminisce and
see things in Texas that have not been seen with any consistency
for years. Power. Balance. Poise. Even defense, for gosh sakes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Saturday's impressive effort only will lead to more tease,
more Longhorns frustrations down the road and more wondering if the
Empire ever will be rebuilt to the level it once was.
</P>
<P>
   After all, for all the parts to this Texas show that seemed so
perfect _ the potential Heisman winner making gallant dashes and
classy gestures, the slippery quarterback heaving bombs, the
crushing defensive effort, the smart coach _ it came against an
Oklahoma team that is bad. Very bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners have little team speed, showed little discipline (14
penalties for 109 yards) on either side of the ball, tried three
quarterbacks with equal futility and was outcoached or overrated on
defense. Maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   As much as this was the kind of day that showed why Mack Brown
wanted to come to Texas to try to rebuild the Empire, it also
showed why Sooners coach John Blake might be shown the way out of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm frustrated with everything,'' Blake said
afterward. ``We didn't do much of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, you could understand why no matter the opponent or the
mediocre 4-2 Texas record even with the win, on this day, in this
setting, there were hints of a turn in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone around here is in danger of thinking that
we've made it back,'' Brown said. ``But after our first three
games, I wasn't sure we could win another game this year. We're
better now. This was good for us today. There were some big
emotions flowing in me when we walked into the stadium. You
understand why Texas-OU is so special when you're in it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, you also could understand why Williams
did what he did, wearing his departed friend's jersey number, then
pointing to the sky and saying to himself, ``This is for you,
Doak,'' both times he scored a touchdown. Afterward, Williams
presented the No. 37 jersey to Walker's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put on the jersey this morning and felt rejuvenated,''
Williams said. ``He was the kind of person that I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day you could understand.
</P>
<P>
   Walker won the Heisman Trophy in 1948, but never had to be
handed a piece of hardware for all the world to know he was
special. Williams, who carried the football 139 yards and his team
the distance in this one, might not win the coveted award 50 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   It's early in the Heisman campaign. And frankly, only a
2,000-yard season by Williams could make some voters forget the
Longhorns' dismal efforts against UCLA and Kansas State. But
Williams made himself at home in the house Doak built, showing why
he is a special Longhorns player no matter what trophies decorate
his home.
</P>
<P>
   Williams changed the complexion of the game by just walking onto
the field. The Sooners tried eight men on the defensive line, then
nine, trying to find a way to stop No. 37.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't. Williams foiled every plan, changed every
strategy, just like it was when Doak roamed the Cotton Bowl or in
the old glorious Texas days of Street's wishbone, Roosevelt Leaks'
dashes and Earl Campbell's pounding runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a special day for me, because of the jersey,''
Williams said. ``And we showed we can play. We can play with
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky was Doak. And Texas was Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
