r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BEARS-SEASON-AZR &LR;      10-11 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BEARS-SEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMBLIN' BEARS NO LONGER CUTE TO FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first month of the season, the Chicago Bears were, well,
kind of cute. No one expected anything from them, and they turned
in some gritty performances while starting 0-4.
</P>
<P>
   They led each game at halftime only to collapse, but they didn't
quit, and they showed just enough skill to be entertaining. And
besides, Chicago was consumed by the Cubs, who were making a run at
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But by last Sunday, the Bears' charm had worn off faster than a
child actor's.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone had caught the act, and with the Cubs having been
eliminated from the playoffs the day before, the eyes of Chicago
were on the Bears, who were playing Detroit at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bears Coach Dave Wannstedt could sense the mood changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said in the locker room, `Hey, we'd better play good this
week and win because we're going to have about 60,000 upset Cubs
fans in the stands and they're going to be taking out all of their
frustrations on us,' '' said Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears didn't play great _ losing five fumbles _ but they
scored 21 points in the fourth quarter to come back and win, 31-27.
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that went 4-12 last year and had lost four
straight to start this season, it was a huge relief.
</P>
<P>
   But Wannstedt is hardly ready to declare that the Bears are
back. After all, they barely beat a bad Detroit team, and even a
victory today over the Cardinals (2-3) at Sun Devil Stadium won't
turn anyone into believers.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt, in his sixth season as head coach, has caught
considerable heat for the Bears descent into the bowels of the NFL.
His tenure started so promisingly with a 7-9 season in 1993
followed by a 9-7 record and a playoff win in 1994. The Bears went
9-7 again in 1995, then slipped to 7-9 and then to 4-12 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the slide are familiar to Cardinals fans, who
have watched that organization make similar mistakes. Bad drafts.
Poor choices in free agency. Freakish injuries. Questionable
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Cardinals, who are on their third coach since
1993, one of the few constants for the Bears has been Wannstedt,
who still has the support of team President Mike McCaskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a mystery to me or anybody around here what has
happened the last few years,'' Wannstedt said. ``We're just trying
to battle our way back a little bit. It's not the norm in the NFL,
where a coach is in his sixth year and going through a rebuilding
stage. But that's where we are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's taken a series of personnel mistakes to get there, and
there are plenty of people to blame.
</P>
<P>
   When Wannstedt was hired, he was given considerable powers over
personnel. Rod Graves, now in the Cardinals front office, was the
director of player personnel from 1994-97 and was blamed for the
poor drafts. And many people point at McCaskey and the structure of
the organization for the Bears' problems.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Tobin left the team after the 1993 season, the Bears
no longer had just one person in charge of all personnel decisions.
Like the Cardinals, a decision was made only after it filtered
through several layers of management. And the decision usually
turned out to be the wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears haven't had a Pro Bowler since 1994. The top draft
pick in 1994, defensive end John Thierry, hasn't done much. The
second pick that year, tackle Marcus Spears, never contributed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Bears' top two picks were running back Rashaan
Salaam and defensive lineman Pat Riley. Neither is with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The club also failed to improve itself through free agency.
Middle linebacker Bryan Cox, signed in 1996, was supposed to
provide a stabilizing force but proved to be more of a divisive
one. He's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt traces part of the downfall to 1996. In the preseason,
Wannstedt proclaimed that all the pieces were in place for the
Bears to return to prominence. And it seemed to be true after the
Bears opened the season with a victory over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   However, the season turned, Wannstedt said, when quarterback
Erik Kramer suffered two herniated cervical discs after starting
the first four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears spent part of the next two seasons trying to find a
replacement. Dave Krieg was a stop-gap measure, and the Bears ended
up trading a first-round pick to Seattle for Rick Mirer and a
fourth-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer started the first five games of last season and was
horrible. The Bears lost all five, and Mirer was replaced by
Kramer. For the season, Mirer completed just 51.5 percent of his
passes, didn't throw a touchdown pass and was intercepted six
times. He was released before training camp this year.
</P>
<P>
   As the club floundered, the front office structure was changed.
Mark Hatley, who had spent nine years in Kansas City's personnel
department, was hired as the vice president of player personnel. He
restructured the scouting department, creating separate departments
for pro and college scouting, something Graves requested but was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts think the Bears' 1998 draft was more productive
than in years past, given the early season play of running back
Curtis Enis, the first-round pick, and safety Tony Parrish, taken
in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskey, meanwhile, gave Wannstedt a vote of confidence. But
Wannstedt knew he not only needed an infusion of talent on his team
but also some character.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some things going on within the club that we're not
going to discuss, but it's a different ballclub this year,'' said
receiver Bobby Engram. ``Guys in this locker room believe we can
win, that we have a chance to win every week, and that's all you
can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals and objectives were different (last year),''
Wannstedt said. ``The team and its approach is different this year.
We're a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been Wannstedt's mantra since training camp, which he
called the most fun in his six seasons in Chicago. There are 11 new
starters, and problems such as defensive end Alonzo Spellman and
Cox have been weeded out. It's questionable whether these Bears are
better than last year's team, but no one denies that there are
fewer problems in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really took a hard stance and said that we might be getting
rid of some talented players,'' Wannstedt said. ``But we felt like
we would be able to take one step back but two steps forward from
an attitude standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being 1-4, the players seem to genuinely believe that
this season is salvageable. The upcoming schedule is favorable,
with the next six games coming against the Cardinals, Dallas,
Tennessee, St. Louis, Detroit and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After last Sunday's game, a reporter asked Kramer if he really
believes it's possible the Bears can reverse their fortunes. ``It
must be if you're asking me that question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is a town that does not indulge warm beer or losers for
long. There aren't many fans who truly believe Wannstedt can pull
the franchise out of the muck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago's a tough town, and I feel like I've got big enough
shoulders to handle it,'' Wannstedt said. ``It's easy to blame
everything on me. And in a lot of cases that would have happened.
But Mike (McCaskey) has not responded that way. He's got confidence
in what we're doing, and we're just plowing ahead.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
