<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUITTER QUARTERBACK INFURIATES PANTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bashing of Carolina quarterback  &UR; Kerry Collins, who quit on
his team last week, is going on inside the Panthers' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can officially say I've seen everything that can
happen in the NFL now,'' Carolina cornerback  &UR; Eric Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unheard of,'' outside linebacker  &UR; Kevin Greene said.
``The only other case I know of that was anything like it ws when
(New Orleans) Coach  &UR; Jim Mora just up and died out (by resigning)
in the middle of a season.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins stunned the team when he walked into Coach  &UR; Dom Capers'
office Wednesday morning and announced that his heart wasn't into
it and that he wanted to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had made that comment, my wife would have shot me,''
linebacker  &UR; Jeff Brady.
</P>
<P>
   With Collins out of the picture, former Cardinals quarterback
 &UR; Steve
 &UR; Beuerlein becomes the starter for today's game at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Beuerlein said he was shocked when Collins told him of his
decision to forfeit the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was joking,'' Beuerlein said. ``I didn't realize
he was serious until he re-emphasized it several times. I don't
know if it was something that was festering in him or if he just
woke up (Wednesday) morning and felt this way. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation so unique, I don't even know what to
compare it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady described Beuerlein as a veteran who has the players'
respect. ``There's an uplifting breath of fresh air with him,''
Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' impending departure doesn't have huge salary-cap
implications because he is in the last year of his contract. In
fact, team officials declined after last season to exercise an
option on his contract, which would have required them to pay
Collins a $6 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But the team can't replace him in the first round of next year's
draft in what is considered a deep quarterback crop, headed by
Kentucky's  &UR; Tim Couch. The Panthers sent their first-round pick to
Washington in the deal for defensive tackle  &UR; Sean Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was the franchise's first draft pick and led the team to
the NFC championship game in his second season. But the past two
years have been disastrous for him.
</P>
<P>
   He offended teammates by using a racial slur after going out
drinking on the final night of training camp a year ago. Three days
later, he suffered a broken jaw in a preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Collins went on to lead the NFL in interceptions with 21 and
ranked last in passing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he wants out because he doesn't like the franchise, the
city of Charlotte, N.C., or the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard thing for me to say, but he has quit on us,'' said
offensive lineman  &UR; Frank Garcia, a Maryvale High School product.
``He has jumped ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be able to come in and play. But will people respect
him as a leader? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the Panthers are better off without Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if you're washing cars,'' Davis said. ``If you
don't want to be out there washing cars, the guy who wants to do it
will do a better job.'' &QL; 
Wet and wild &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Seahawks punter  &UR; Jeff Feagles never has seen rain fall
as hard or long as the 3.6 inches that fell in Kansas City last
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The storm caused the game at Arrowhead Stadium to be delayed for
54 minutes and left the field ``a complete mess,'' according to
Feagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed pretty dry (on the sideline),'' said Feagles, the
former Cardinals punter. ``We had big ponchos on and trash bags
were over shoes. But at one point, I just gave up staying dry. I
was tying my shoes, and as a I drew the laces tighter, water
squeezed out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time when I ran out to punt, I could see my shoes
sloshing.'' &QL; 
Losersville, USA
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos quarterback  &UR; Bubby Brister was asked whom he
likes in today's game between the winless Washington Redskins and
the winless Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cheerleaders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The game between two 0-5 teams has been billed as the ``Paper
Bag Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has been outscored, 137-52. The Redskins have been
outscored, 169-74, and have a minus-11 turnover ratio. &QL; 
No hard feelings
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals Coach  &UR; Joe Bugel, offensive line coach at San
Diego, returns to Oakland today for the first time since being
fired as head coach of the Raiders last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Bugel, a class guy, isn't angry about being dumped after one
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never left a job bitter,'' said Bugel, who was fired
after a 4-12 season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, two weeks after his ouster, Bugel kept a scheduled
visit to an Oakland elementary school and told the kids of his
firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day relieved a lot of pain, to be honest with you,''
Bugel said. ``I told them that sometime, something like that could
happen in their life, and I wanted them to know you could bounce
back with a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Bugel said he is still smiling even though he likely won't get a
chance to be an NFL head coach again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real good lieutenant,'' he said. ``I've served in this
capacity most of my career, and I didn't realize how much I missed
it.'' &QL; 
Unbeatable?
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Packers safety  &UR; LeRoy Butler doesn't expect the
Minnesota Vikings (5-0) to lose a game anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we meet them again,'' said Butler after the Packers were
routed, 37-24, last Monday night at Green Bay's Lambeau Field. ``I
don't see anybody else beating them. We were the only people
capable of beating them. They're going into the sunset now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're playing this good without Brad (starting
quarterback
 &UR; Brad Johnson), when Brad gets back, oh my God.''
</P>
<P>
   The rematch is Nov. 22 in Minneapolis. By that time, Vikings
wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss might already have locked up the
offensive Rookie of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a lot of criticism, and a lot of people want me to
fail, but I think I turned a lot of heads,'' said Moss after he
caught five passes for 190 yards and two scores. ``There's no room
on this bandwagon for all the people who want to climb on.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator  &UR; Brian Billick said he still is getting a
gauge on what Moss can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed, size, jumping ability, ratio . . . and he's
absolutely unflappable,'' Billick said. ``Here it is Monday night
in Lambeau, and this guy is loving every minute of it. There's not
a nervous bone in his body. For a rookie, that's unnatural.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
