<HEADLINE>
BROWN STANDS TALL AT CORNER  
 BACKUP TAKES CHANCE, SHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Sometimes the best decisions in life are those we
don't have to make, and the one he didn't have to make in August
has proven fortunate for cornerback J.B. Brown and the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Brown's sister turned out to be a tissue match to
provide their mother with a new kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get the chance because my sister was a match, but if
she had not been, and I was, I would have done it,'' Brown, 31,
said. ``Even if it meant I'd never play football again.''
</P>
<P>
   Which it would have meant. He's pleased to report both mother
and sister are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired from Pittsburgh for a seventh-round draft pick on
Tuesday, Aug. 25, Brown flew to Arizona the next day, returned to
Washington on Thursday for the transplant surgery, and then joined
the Cardinals in Oakland on Saturday. Without a practice, he played
in more than half the preseason victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the defense or anything,'' Brown recalls. ``I
just wanted to play hard, show my skills and play with good
technique and go on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where he went from there was into a supporting role at right
cornerback to Tommy Knight. It blossomed into a starting role last
Sunday when Knight was sidelined because of a tear in a hamstring
connector. It's likely that Knight's injury will keep Brown in the
starting role again today when the Chicago Bears visit.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in his 10th NFL season, drew raves from Cardinals
defensive coaches after his play against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very valuable for us,'' defensive coordinator Dave
McGinnis said. ``We're fortunate to have a veteran like him to come
in and play as well as did. Oakland tried to go after him twice
late in the game and he was in great position both times. I was
really pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondary coach Larry Marmie and Brown spent more than a week in
hourlong, crash-course sessions on the defense before the other
players came to work daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday's game was the best he's played since he's been here,''
Marmie said. ``I feel very confident with him going into the game
now. He's a quality person who wants to be coached. It isn't like,
`Tell me what you want me to do and I'll do it.' He wants to be
coached and asks, `How do you want me to do it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has 16-career interceptions and four fumble recoveries in
eight seasons in Miami and one in Pittsburgh. He was a starter for
six years in Miami, at one point started 71 consecutive games and
played in 75 straight before a knee injury sidelined him. In 1993,
his five interceptions led the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   He has no problem accepting his role behind a healthy Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage of my career I'm just happy to be playing and
contributing,'' said Brown, a Maryland product. ``When I came here
I told Coach (Vince) Tobin I wanted to help anyway I could,
including special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put my ego to the side. It just doesn't matter to me.
This is a good opportunity for me. I was a nickel back in Miami two
years ago and a backup in Pittsburgh last year, so I really haven't
played much in two years.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
