<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0601 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BEARS-AZR &LR;      10-11 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER WIPES OUT LAST WEEK  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Second-year quarterback Jake Plummer appreciates all the
concerned citizens who have inquired about the state of his psyche
and his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   But he wants Cardinals fans to know that he's not as fragile as
some might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny that they are worried,'' Plummer said.
``Maybe it means they care about me.''
</P>
<P>
   They also care not to see Plummer throw three interceptions, two
that resulted in Oakland Raiders scores in a 23-20 loss last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer will try to bounce back today when the Cardinals play
host to the Chicago Bears at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new week,'' Plummer said. ``I learned that at
(Arizona State). Last year, I threw four picks in a game. The next
game, I didn't think about them. You keep pushing on. Hopefully,
I'm going to have a couple hundred games in my career. One bad game
doesn't push me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie safety Pat Tillman, Plummer's college and pro teammate,
doesn't think there is any reason to spend sleepless nights
worrying about Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake's fine,'' Tillman said. ``You're not going to get him
down. Look at the position he plays. You have to be headstrong to
do it. . . . He'll bounce back from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin is confident Plummer will play well today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jake has had a good week of practice,'' Tobin said.
``He's a battler. He has continued to work. It's not going to get
him down.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Plummer's job even tougher is that the Cardinals have
second-worst third-down percentage in the league, at 17 of 66.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the big question is whether defensive tackle Eric
Swann (knee) will play. He hasn't practiced this week.
</P>
<P>
   If Swann doesn't play, he'll be replaced by second-year pro
Rashod Swinger, who would be making his first NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicago Tribune'' reported this week that Swann guaranteed
a victory in an offhanded remark.
</P>
<P>
   Swann wasn't quoted in the article, and his teammates maintain
he never said it.
</P>
<P>
   Note
</P>
<P>
   Only once in Cardinals history has a player guaranteed a win.
Defensive end Michael Bankston guaranteed a victory over Cleveland
in 1994. The Browns won, 32-0. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
