<HEADLINE>
NAU KEEPS PACE IN BIG SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ It was a day of ``Can you top this?'' for
Northern Arizona linebacker Afa Faraimo.
</P>
<P>
   He recovered a fumble on the first play of the game that led to
a touchdown, blocked a punt that a teammate took 31 yards for
another score and intercepted a pass.
</P>
<P>
   And just for the heck of it, he made 12 tackles and led an
inspired defense that triggered Saturday night's 30-7 victory over
Idaho State. It was a game the Lumerjacks desperately needed to
stay on the fringes of the Big Sky race.
</P>
<P>
   Faraimo, a 5-foot-10, 205-pound junior, dedicated the game to
his 4-month-old son, Daniel, and his performance capped a perfect
campus Family Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the best game I've ever had,'' he said. ``But
we had some players coming back from injuries, and we all wanted to
make some plays. We wanted to play to our standards, and we pretty
much did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jake Crissup marveled at Faraimo's performance: ``He
was just incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   NAU (3-3, 1-2 Big Sky) completely dominated the Bengals (1-4,
1-2) before a crowd of 12,301 at Walkup Skydome. And it may take a
similar effort next week when the Lumberjacks visit Montana, a
perennial Division I-AA powerhouse and where NAU Coach Jerome
Souers coached for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the game's first play for Idaho State, quarterback Seth
Buford was clocked by defensive tackle Derek Allen, and Faraimo was
there to pounce on the loose ball at the Bengals' 28-yard line.
That set up a 1-yard scoring plunge by Tavon Cooper, who also put
the finishing touches on the evening with a 35-yard scoring jaunt
in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In between, two key players, quarterback Travis Brown and
Crissup, put in some time. Brown had been out for more than three
games because of a dislocated left elbow, and Crissup missed last
week's game because of injured ribs.
</P>
<P>
   But it all came back to Faraimo, who said the Lumberjacks'
defensive scheme worked well, especially on his blocked punt and
one of his near-blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who played the second and third quarters, looked solid.
He was 10 of 15 for 95 yards, including a 24-yard touchdown strike
to Justin Yuille. Backup quarterback David Moran, who may have seen
the last of his starting duty, continued his good work as a
fill-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to get back in there,'' Brown said. ``I wanted to
take a hit, but not a bad hit. I felt like I was in a groove right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the likely starter against Montana next week, and his
return comes at the right time for NAU. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
