<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUCK OF THE IRISH OVERWHELMS KEALY  
 SUSPECT SECONDARY RISES TO CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - It was evident from the first play of the game on
Saturday that Arizona State was ready to test a battered and often
beaten Notre Dame defensive secondary.
</P>
<P>
   And from that first play, when Fighting Irish cornerback Brock
Williams tipped away an underthrown Ryan Kealy bomb for Lenzie
Jackson, it was apparent the Notre Dame defense would pass that
test and every other the Sun Devils presented in a 28-9 victory at
Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out on that first play, and threw long on
play-action because they knew we had to respect (ASU running back)
J.R. Redmond,'' said safety A'Jani Sanders. ``We knew that was
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the day was over, the Irish had intercepted Kealy three
times _ including one that Sanders returned 25 yards for a
touchdown _ and forced the Sun Devils into a quarterback change.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame run defense wasn't bad either, limiting Redmond
to 94 yards on 19 carries and the Sun Devils to 315 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Irish came into the game ranked 22nd in the country
by the Associated Press and 24th in the USA Today/ESPN coaches
poll, their defense was suspect. Notre Dame had yielded averages of
28 points and more than 400 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing quarterbacks had racked up an average of 269 yards a
game and the Notre Dame defense, with two starting safeties out
because of injuries, had intercepted only two passes all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our secondary just made plays,'' said cornerback Deveron
Harper. ``We made plays on their running game, too. We just stick
together and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only major mistake the Irish defensive backs made was
Harper's. With Notre Dame leading, 14-0, Kealy was hit while trying
to scramble and lost the ball on a third-down-and-10 play. The ball
landed at Harper's feet, and while his teammate and the Sun Devils
scrambled for the ball, Harper nonchalantly gave it a little shove
with the side of his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the play was over,'' Harper said. ``I thought it was
an incomplete pass, and I was heading back to the sideline. I
thought we had them stopped on third down.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a 15-yard penalty and an ASU first down. To
make matters worse, Kealy fired a 17-yard completion to Jackson,
who beat Harper on the right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   It eventually led to an ASU field goal and a heated tongue
lashing from Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie for Harper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you want to know (what I said),'' Davie said,
laughing. ``We had a little disagreement. He saw things a little
different. Those little things can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Harper, Davie didn't kill him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let off a little steam,'' Harper said. ``I told him,
`Coach, look me in the eyes. I did not kick the ball
intentionally.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Davie called it ``a silly play'' later, but he didn't have many
reasons to complain about his club's defense. He expected ASU to
challenge his secondary and felt fortunate that the Sun Devils
didn't convert on the first play of the game. Jackson had a step on
Williams but had to wait for Kealy's pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew that was coming on that first play of the game,'' he
said. ``We play an eight-man front on first down, and we knew they
would be coming with that (long pass) right there. The ball may
have been a little under thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had something going right there. That could have been a
7-0 lead on the first play. Those are the little things that make
the difference.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0134EDT &QL; 
