<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-OFFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY'S PROG RESS INTER CEPTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. Of all the nasty numbers concerning the mystifying
sophomore slump of Arizona State quarterback Ryan Kealy, here are
two that stand out _ seven and seven.
</P>
<P>
   Seven is how many interceptions Kealy threw all of last season
when he was the model of precision, breaking most of Jake Plummer's
freshman passing records.
</P>
<P>
   And seven is Kealy's interception total in only six games this
year after Notre Dame picked him off three times during its 28-9
victory over ASU on Saturday at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interceptions, on a badly overthrown pass, was
returned 25 yards for a touchdown by free safety A'Jani Sanders to
give the Fighting Irish a 14-0 lead early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, who appeared headed for stardom, might be headed for the
bench. He came out for redshirt freshman quarterback Chad Elliott
in the fourth quarter. The same thing happened last week during
ASU's loss to Southern California, with one difference. A
concussion forced Kealy to leave the USC game. This time, it was
his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a bye week, which will enable the Sun Devils to try to
heal emotionally and physically and take stock of themselves, ASU
Coach Bruce Snyder was asked if he would look at the quarterback
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prudent thing to do would be to look at everything,'' he
said. ``And the quarterback position falls into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, who helped lead ASU to an 8-3 record and a Sun Bowl berth
in 1997, has the identical completion percentage (54.5) and almost
the same efficiency rating. But all those interceptions. And as the
Sun Devils fell to 2-4 to already exceed last year's loss total, he
has not shown the anticipated progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some mistakes and paid for them,'' he said after the
game. ``It's my job to correct them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy said he felt no effects from last week's knock in the head
against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just me not playing well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, a St. Mary's High School graduate reunited with his
former teammate, Notre Dame kicker Jim Sanson, was limited to a
brief question-and-answer session that lasted about five minutes.
But it could have gone an hour without him producing a ready
explanation for his inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little baffling to me, personally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded, ``Probably, at times, I did tend to force the
ball.'' His analysis went no further.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy completed 13 of 22 passes for just 121 yards. There also
were two fumbled exchanges with center Grey Ruegamer, both
recovered by Kealy, one of which was caused by Ruegamer's wet
hands.
</P>
<P>
   If Kealy's confidence is lagging, coaches tried to snap him out
of it by calling a deep pass to wide receiver Lenzie Jackson on the
game's first play. The ball was slightly underthrown and barely
tipped away by cornerback Brock Williams. If Jackson had caught it,
he could have gone all the way, 76 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was scripted,'' quarterbacks coach John Pettas said.
``We should have had that one. That was close. We thought we could
throw on them and then run.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU managed 315 yards against a defense giving up more than 400
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Kealy's confidence has taken a hit, Pettas said, ``A
little bit, possibly, especially late in the game. We've got to
overcome it and end it. We had a lot of faith in him and still do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been pressing a lot more in terms of trying to make plays
and carry the team and live up to expectations. What happens, I
think, is that when he struggles, he gets a little bit down. But we
know he's a talented kid. My job is to get it right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
