<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ALOU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WON'T GET ALOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Felipe Alou, whose strong character and quiet
manner made him the top candidate to become the Los Angeles
Dodgers' next manager, has decided to remain with the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   New Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone learned Saturday night
that Alou will reject the club's offer of a multiyear contract
worth nearly $1 million per season to stay in Montreal, where he is
critical to the survival of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not official, but that is where it is headed,'' Malone
said. ``I still think there is a glimmer of hope, but the situation
really became a quandary. All the qualities we like in Felipe as a
manager were the very reasons he is staying in Montreal. His
loyalty to that organization and the city are the reasons he is
staying.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone added that he already has spoken to Davey Johnson, who
managed a World Series championship team with the New York Mets in
1986 and led Cincinnati and Baltimore to division titles the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, fired by the Orioles over differences with owner Peter
Angelos, was out of baseball this season. He draws almost universal
praise from his players, but is known to be abrasive with
superiors. Malone was an assistant GM in Baltimore last year when
the Orioles won the American League East title.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that is still early,'' said Malone, who hoped to have a
manager in place by the World Series, which begins next Saturday.
``There will be discussions this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone learned of Alou's intentions Saturday evening during a
telephone conversation. Malone returned to Los Angeles on Friday
night after spending three days with Alou near the manager's home
in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   It was there Malone and club president Bob Graziano made their
offer. Early Saturday, Alou flew to the Expos spring training base
in Jupiter, Fla., to meet with Montreal general manager Jim
Beattie.
</P>
<P>
   The two met twice. According to sources, Beattie failed to
convince Alou to stay until an evening dinner. The Expos guaranteed
they would double any contract offer made by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   That would put Alou's new contract at three years for almost $2
million per season, close to the three-year, $6 million deal Jim
Leyland signed last week with Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``But knowing Felipe, this was not about the money,'' Malone
said. ``This was about his family. His wife is from Montreal and he
felt a great commitment to that organization. I had great
confidence during our meetings that we could get a deal done. But I
think the Expos laid a pretty heavy guilt trip on him to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting Expos, who have lost money despite trading much
of their top talent in the past few years, could not afford to lose
Alou, the organization's most popular figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos are hoping to keep the club in Montreal by building a
downtown open-air ballpark to replace the ill-fitting Olympic
Stadium. After after years of trading players like Pedro Martinez,
Larry Walker and John Wetteland, they signed young stars Vladimir
Guerrero and Ugueth Urbina to long-term contract this year in an
attempt to build support.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal also hopes to infuse capital into the organzation by
adding several new members to their 11-man ownership committee. But
first it had to keep its manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
