<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUC PULLS KINGS UP IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta - So far, so good, as the Los Angeles Kings
take their first tentative steps into the land of great
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong defensive effort and Luc Robitaille's goal with
4:35 remaining Saturday night, the Kings opened the new season with
a 2-1 victory over the Edmonton Oilers before a sellout crowd of
17,100 at Skyreach Centre.
</P>
<P>
   And the start of the season couldn't have come a moment sooner
for Kings coach Larry Robinson, whose team concludes its brief
season-opening trip Monday afternoon in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four weeks of training camp can wear on you,'' Robinson said.
``It's kind of nice just to get going and start playing for real.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the Kings began playing for real, there were a few new
sights to be seen. For one, rookie left wing Josh Green made his
NHL debut, playing on a line with Robitaille and Yanic Perreault,
though at times he was replaced on the line during power plays by
Sandy Moger.
</P>
<P>
   The other new sight was that off veteran defenseman Garry Galley
sitting in the stands in favor of Philippe Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   In the early minutes of the new season, the Kings looked
somewhat burdened by their high hopes, even after Rob Blake
inaugurated the new year after 47 seconds with a thunderous
open-ice hit that left Edmonton left wing Andrei Kovalenko prone
for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, with the Kings scrambling in their
own end, Edmonton's Boyd Devereaux took a hit behind the net from
Ian Laperriere, but managed to pass the puck across the end boards
to teammate Kelly Buchberger. Former King Kevin Brown, unchecked to
the left of goalie Stephane Fiset, then swatted in Buchberger's
centering feed for a 1-0 Edmonton lead.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes later it nearly became 2-0, when Kings defenseman
Steve Duchesne lost the puck in center ice, setting up a 2-on-1 for
the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Only a brilliant split save by Fiset on a shot by Pat Falloon
kept the Kings within a goal, a deficit they overcame on a power
play a little more than two minutes later, when Perreault scored on
an eight-foot blast off a centering pass from Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Kings settled down for the rest of the first
period and through the scoreless second period, in which they
outshot the Oilers 11-5. Some of the Kings' finest shifts came from
their third and fastest line of Russ Courtnall, Craig Johnson and
Nathan LaFayette, which did a good job of neutralizing Edmonton's
edge in team speed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings were repeatedly frustrated by former Mighty Ducks
goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov, who entered the game in the second
period after Edmonton starter Bob Essensa departed after 20 minutes
with an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov, 32, has been well-traveled in the past few months.
First, he was left unprotected by the Ducks in the expansion draft
in June and selected by the Nashville Predators. Then on Oct.1, the
Predators dealt him to Edmonton in a five-player trade.
</P>
<P>
   Shtalenkov's play on Saturday made it clear why teams have
wanted him in the past few months, but left unclear why other teams
haven't felt the need to keep him around.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many big saves he made in the second period, two stood
out. Midway through the period, Shtalenkov made an acrobatic glove
save on a 35-foot Robitaille slap shot from the slot. Three minutes
later, he stuck out a pad to stop Johnson on a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset had his moments, too, none better than when he sprawled
from one side of the crease to the other to block a wide-open shot
by Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' best chance to take the lead came early in the third,
when Oilers defenseman Craig Millar received a double minor for
high-sticking Moger. But the Kings failed to generate an attack,
and the advantage disappeared when Duchesne nearly coughed up the
puck and pulled down Todd Marchant to avoid a possible Oilers
breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   It took until overtime loomed for the Kings to get the
game-winner, a bang-bang play on which Perreault beat Josef Beranek
on a faceoff to Shtalenkov's right. The puck went to Robitaille in
the slot, and he blasted it into the Oilers' goal, building off his
strong exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   After Robitaille's goal, the Oilers never seriously threatened
to tie the score, and the Kings won an opener for the first time
since beating the New York Islanders, 1-0, two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
