</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES PUSHED TO BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ For seven years, the Atlanta Braves have had a
formula for winning that has been fun to watch and always seemed to
work. But their magic may be wearing off.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight game, the Braves were stifled by the San
Diego Padres. Saturday, San Diego did more than just beat Atlanta,
4-1, to take a 3-0 lead in the best-of-seven National League
Championship Series. The Padres did it at the expense of Greg
Maddux, the best pitcher in baseball in the '90s. But even a
four-time Cy Young Award winner can't win if his team doesn't score
a few runs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Padres, who can wrap up their first World Series
appearance since 1984 with a win Sunday night, are beating the
Braves at their own game _ starting pitching. San Diego won Games 1
and 2, 3-2 and 3-0, as Alan Ashby and Kevin Brown were better than
John Smoltz and Tom Glavine. Saturday, the Padres only got five
innings out of lefthander Sterling Hitchcock. But by the time he
left, San Diego had a 2-1 lead it would not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run homer has been hard to come by for the Braves.
Former sluggers David Justice and Fred McGriff now wear different
uniforms. The bench is weak and the offense is vulnerable to strong
pitching, which the Padres have shown the last three games. No team
in baseball history has rebounded from a 3-0 deficit to win in a
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shut us down,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``We had
good matchups going into situations and couldn't smell a hit. You
can't get going into bases-loaded situations every inning without
doing some damage.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 1-0 lead in the third inning, the Braves loaded
the bases in the fourth, sixth, and eighth and failed to score.
Meanwhile, San Diego scored twice off Maddux in the fifth with a
rally that was started by Hitchcock of all people. Little did the
62,779 in attendence at Qualcomm Stadium suspect the two-run rally
would be enough to beat Maddux, who was removed in the sixth for a
pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the fifth, Hitchcock singled to left off Maddux,
who flied out with the bases loaded to end the fourth. Hitchcock
advanced to second on a grounder to the mound by Quilvio Veras.
Steve Finley followed with a double up the gap in left-center,
scoring Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves then intentionally walked Tony Gwynn. But the
strategy backfired as Ken Caminiti singled to center, scoring
Finley to give San Diego a 2-1 lead. The Padres scored two
insurance runs in the eighth off Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maddux was really good,'' said Finley, who had 12 hits in 61
at-bats (.197) prior to Saturday against Maddux. ``He was moving
the ball in and out like he usually does. It's hard to pick up. I
just tried to see the ball, back it up, and put a swing on it.
Thank goodness, it got into the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux would make no excuses. He wasn't upset that he was
removed from the game for a pinch hitter after throwing just 77
pitches. The club needed runs and pulled out all the stops in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the sixth inning and we had a chance to score some
runs,'' said Maddux. ``Was I surprised? No. We're not finished. We
have to bounce back. I'm aware no team has ever come back from 3-0.
But then no team has won seven in a row, either,'' referring to
Atlanta's seven straight division titles. ``It doesn't matter.
There's a first time for everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what is happening is natural. Teams are not scoring
runs in playoff games. The reason teams get to the playoff round is
that they have good pitching. Not just us. Other teams, too. That's
why they're up and after us, with their pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres say they understand the series is not over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to win and be ahead by three games,'' said manager
Bruce Bochy. ``I don't think you could ask for a better situation.
But we know this is a best-of-seven and there is still a lot of
baseball left. We have to be levelheaded out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've relied on our pitching and defense all year.
Offensively, we haven't been as strong as we like. But last year,
we set a Padre record for runs scored and finished last. So it
shows you how important pitching has been to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
