</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOOK BOWL-WORTHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ UCLA tailback Jermaine Lewis' suspension was
greeted with indifference by Arizona coach Dick Tomey on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just looking for an excuse to play DeShaun Foster,''
he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know it, but Tomey's comment would symbolize
third-ranked UCLA's most impressive performance of the season, a
52-28 victory over No. 10 Arizona before 58,738 at Arizona Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, not Heisman Trophy candidate Cade McNown or Arizona
flipmeister Ortege Jenkins, was the star.
</P>
<P>
   Subbing for Lewis, the true freshman gained 94 yards in the
first half and singlehandedly grabbed the momentum away from
Arizona's potent offense _ propelling the Bruins to their first win
here in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Foster scored on his first carry, a 37-yard run in which he
broke four tackles, and he had 103 yards in three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, combined with Nebraska's loss, could vault UCLA to
No. 2 nationally. It improved the Bruins to 4-0, 2-0 in the Pac-10,
setting up a critical game against Oregon on Saturday in the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's performance helped offset Jermaine Lewis' suspension
and another subpar game by Bruins quarterback Cade McNown, who
completed 9 of 23 passes in three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   However, McNown made one of the game's biggest plays, connecting
with Danny Farmer on a 64-yard touchdown pass with 11:18 remaining
for the 38-28 lead. It was McNown's 50th career touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to past Tucson visits, UCLA wasn't worried about
matching Arizona's physicality. Instead, coach Bob Toledo was most
concerned with eliminating the mistakes (especially penalties) that
are often the difference in tight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``More games are lost than won, and we can't go in and lose
it,'' he said. ``We can't get sacked. We can't (commit) turnovers.
We can't get penalties or give up big plays or (make mistakes in)
the kicking game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although UCLA made no mistakes in the first half, the Bruins
seemed taken aback by Arizona's aggressiveness. The Wildcats used
several trick plays and odd formations _ including quarterbacks
Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins on the field together _ but it was
their attacking defense that gave UCLA tons of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats blitzed every chance they got and continually
disrupted McNown's rhythm. He completed two of his first 10 passes
and didn't find a groove until Foster forced Arizona to respect the
run: he gained 94 yards on 10 carries in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona jumped to a 7-0 lead with the help of a trick play.
Facing a fourth-and-7 from UCLA's 36, Wildcats punter Ryan
Springston heaved a long pass down the left sideline to A.J. Brown.
The ball was beyond Bruins cornerback Julius Williams and Foster,
the punt returner who raced over when Springston threw. Brown made
a diving catch at the 1, and two plays later Kelvin Eafon scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats made the first mistake, as receiver Dennis
Northcutt fumbled on the ensuing possession.
</P>
<P>
   McNown threw two incompletes, then hit Danny Farmer for 23 yards
to advance to the Arizona 37. One play later, Foster charged over
right end, broke four tackles and raced into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had quelled Arizona's momentum _ but only for a
moment. Two plays later, Jenkins connected with Trung Canidate on a
short crossing pattern into open field, and Canidate ran 74 yards
down the left side to UCLA's 4. Eafon scored again for a 14-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pace slowed as the teams exchanged punts. But on UCLA's
first possession of the second quarter, McNown ran the option for
12 yards, then Foster galloped for 20. A personal foul (late hit)
on Arizona cornerback Chris McAlister pushed UCLA into the red
zone, where it rarely misfires. On third down, McNown found Brian
Poli-Dixon, a Tucson native, on a quick-hitting screen. He broke
one tackle, then glided into the end zone to tie the game 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats responded with a time-consuming, 80-yard drive of
their own. The key play was a fabulous one-handed catch by
Northcutt on a well-thrown pass from Smith. The reception gave
Arizona possession at the Bruins 17. On the next play Smith, with
plenty of time to throw, found Jeremy McDaniel for a 21-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense finding its rhythm, the Bruins countered with
their most impressive drive. It included an 18-yard shovel
(underhand) pass from McNown to tight end Ryan Neufeld. Foster took
care of the final 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins cornerback Ryan Roques intercepted Jenkins early in the
third quarter _ Roques' third pick of the season _ and ran 39 yards
to Arizona's 19. From there, the Bruins went backwards, eventually
needing a 41-yard field goal from Chris Sailer to take a 24-21
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, the Wildcats moved downfield easily, and Jenkins hit
McDaniel on a 31-yard touchdown pass. McDaniel made the catch in
full extension at the goal line _ certainly the play of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
