<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES LEVELHEADED DESPITE LOPSIDED LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ They're saying all the right things, and who
wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, holy moley, the Padres are up three-and-oh. No one ever,
anywhere, at any time or any place, has ever come back from a 3-0
deficit in this sport. But you're not going to get anyone in the
San Diego camp to say anything that would have the slightest chance
of either a) stirring up the Atlanta Braves, or b) fooling around
with the karma.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a funny thing about this never-ever business. For if
there is one sport in which no one should be surprised if a team
were to come back from 0-and-3 to win four straight, it's baseball,
right? All you need is four well-pitched games, a timely hit or
two, a little luck, and, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The Padres know. Trust me. They know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win one more game,'' sighed San Diego general
manager Kevin Towers, ``and that's not going to be easy. You're
looking at (Denny) Neagle, (John) Smoltz, (Tom) Glavine, and (Greg)
Maddux. Those four guys could sweep you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could ask for a better situation,'' agreed
manager Bruce Bochy. ``But there's still baseball left, and we have
to be levelheaded about this. It's a good feeling, but we have to
go out there and get number four.''
</P>
<P>
   They will get it if they continue to do the same things they've
done to win numbers one, two, and three, all of which have included
a formula mix of superb starting pitching, brilliant relief
pitching, good fielding when needed, and just enough hitting to
make sure they're in the lead when Trevor Hoffman jogs in from the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman saved Saturday's 4-1 victory with 1 1/3 innings of
shutout relief. When the Padres lead after eight, it's the donest
deal in sport. They haven't lost a game in that situation since
July 24, 1996, and Trevor Hoffman is the reason.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to get to that situation they need help from other
people, most of whom have no need for bodyguard help as they stroll
the mean streets of America. 'Fess up, now. If you heard that Donne
Wall or Dan Miceli walked into the restaurant while you were
ordering, would you even look up from the menu? They might as well
be in the Baseball Witness Protection Program, which is what
happens when you play your games out here, in the Land That TV
Forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Wall and Miceli, both righthanders, are two of Hoffman's set-up
guys, and the team wouldn't be here without them. The latter was
10-5 this season. The former was 5-4, with a 2.46 ERA, and in this
series he has been immense. He saved Game 1 for Hoffman and
Saturday he extricated the ballclub from a bases-loaded, none-out
jam in the sixth by striking out pinch hitters Michael Tucker and
Greg Colbrunn on breathtaking changeups.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Mr. Towers can take a bow, because he got both of them
in the same deal. Now that's some savvy GMing.
</P>
<P>
   Who outside of fine-print fanatics was paying attention last
Nov. 19 when Towers sent Tim Worrell and Trey Beamon to Detroit for
Messrs. Wall and Miceli? I sure wasn't. And yet it is moves like
this which so often turn out to be key in the construction of
pennant-winning teams. It isn't always a matter of throwing $75
million at a superstar. This is a 25-man game. Never forget that
Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez may very well be the two best
players in baseball, and look where the Mariners are today.
</P>
<P>
   Towers had his eye on the 31-year-old Wall for a long time. ``I
liked him when he was the pitcher of the year in the Pacific Coast
League,'' he said. ``We put a waiver claim in on him last year when
he went from Houston to Cincinnati, but we couldn't get him. They
sent him right over to Detroit, and then we were able to make the
deal. He's a guy with ice water in his veins.''
</P>
<P>
   Miceli, according to Towers, is a ``bulldog.'' Towers needed no
briefing on him, since the GM was in Pittsburgh three years ago
when Miceli was busy saving 21 games for a bad team. ``He's got a
closer's mentality,'' Towers said.
</P>
<P>
   If any casual fan knows anyone on the Padres, it is Tony Gwynn,
and maybe _ maybe _ Greg Vaughn, who hit the most anonymous and
instantly forgotten 50 home runs in baseball history. Ken Caminiti?
Maybe. He did, after all, win the 1996 MVP award.
</P>
<P>
   The shortstop? It's Chris Gomez, and, no, he's not from San
Pedro de Marcoris or Maracaibo. He was born and raised in
California. Oh, and the catcher? You have any idea who Carlos
Hernandez is?
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hernandez is another Towers coup. Towers signed him as a
minor league free agent in 1996 after he had spent parts of seven
seasons backing up the likes of Mike Piazza. In AL eyes, he's just
a box score line. ``He's done a great job for us,'' Towers said.
``He calls a good game. He stops the running game. And he's had
many big hits for us this year.'' Hernandez was 2 for 4 with a run
scored in Game 1 and he had a damaging eighth-inning double
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are in their current position _ one win from the
World Series _ because they have simply been better than Atlanta in
every phase of the game. There has been nothing wrong with the
vaunted Atlanta starting pitching (5 earned runs in 18 innings),
except that San Diego's has been better (2 earned runs in 21
innings). The Padres aren't smacking the ball around, but they've
done enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers have really been clutching it up,'' said center
fielder Steve Finley. ``They've just been dominating. And the
hitters have done just enough to stay ahead until Trevor comes
in.''
</P>
<P>
   And the San Diego unknowns have done more than the Atlanta
unknowns. Let's not forget that.
</P>
<P>
   So it's 3-0. That's very nice, but now's the time to heed Yogi's
Law, the one which holds that the struggle is not terminated until
it's, well, terminated. ``These guys have been around,'' said
Bochy. ``They know how good Atlanta is.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as close to inflamed rhetoric as you're going to get from
this bunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
