<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES PULL EVEN WITH INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Orlando Hernandez, taught as a child in Cuba to fear
and loathe the Yanquis, did his part to save the New York Yankees
Saturday night in a 4-0 win over the Cleveland Indians that tied
the American League Championship Series at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his younger brother Livan did a year ago for the Florida
Marlins against these same Indians, El Duque turned the national
pastime into a showcase for Cuban defectors, demonstrating the same
mix of composure, cunning, and command that made his brother the
World Series MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should just go ahead and trade for them all,'' said
Indians general manager John Hart. ``Intercept the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez gave up just three hits in seven innings and allowed
just one runner as far as third base, putting the Yankees back in
position to seize control of this series with ace David Wells
scheduled to pitch Game 5 this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a must-win situation, no doubt about it,'' said shortstop
Omar Vizquel, who had three of the Indians' four hits. ``Live or
die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow is the most important game. David Wells is on the
mound at 4 o'clock. It will be tough to see the ball anyway.
Against that guy, every little mistake will count.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with what outfielder Paul O'Neill described as a
``dangerous situation,'' the Yankees rallied behind a pitcher
forced to survive much graver perils just to get here, a man who
left family and friends behind the day after Christmas last year
when he set off on a raft from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him this morning,'' said his agent, Joe Cubas, who
had engineered the defection of Livan Hernandez from the Cuban
national team while it was in Mexico, ``and I said, `You know that
God puts people in difficult situations, but always situations they
can handle. He's done that to you many different times. You guys
are down, everybody is down, but you're going to pull them through
this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool? That's this guy's demeanor. This guy had to risk his
life in the Florida Straits. Pitching for him is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hernandez held the Indians in check, striking out Jim
Thome and Manny Ramirez in succession in both the fourth and sixth
innings, the latter occasion with two runners on base, the Yankees
generated just enough offense to take a 3-0 lead against Doc
Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill hit a first-inning home run to give the Yankees a 1-0
lead, then opened the fourth with the first of two consecutive
walks issued by Gooden. Designated hitter Chili Davis then dropped
an opposite-field, ground-rule double just inside the left-field
foul line to score O'Neill to make it 2-0, and Tino Martinez, the
Yankees' slump-ridden first baseman, followed with a sacrifice fly
that scored Bernie Williams, making it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's fly ball generated another controversial call when
second-base umpire Jim McKean ruled that Indians center fielder
Kenny Lofton dropped the ball, even though replays showed Lofton's
drop came as he was transferring the ball from his glove to his
throwing hand after the catch had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez reached first on the error, but Gooden avoided further
damage when Jorge Posada flied out and Chad Curtis tapped into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added a final run in the ninth when Martinez hit an
opposite-field double off reliever Dave Burba, a hit that ended his
0-for-19 streak in ALCS play, and pinch runner Homer Bush advanced
on a wild pitch and scored on Scott Brosius's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Doc better,'' Indians manager Mike Hargrove said,
``but Doc certainly threw well enough to win tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was part of the Yankees' run to a World Series title in
1996, throwing a no-hitter after Yankees owner George Steinbrenner
gave him a chance to salvage his career when it appeared
drug-related suspensions had brought it to an end. But Saturday
night, he was unable to end his legacy of never having won a
postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden has two Cy Young Awards and is a four-time All-Star, but
in 10 postseason starts for the Mets (seven times), Yankees (once),
and Indians (twice), he has never come away with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of frustrating,'' said Gooden, who was ejected four
batters into his last start, against the Red Sox in the Division
Series, and was lifted with two out in the fifth Saturday night
after throwing 92 pitches. ``A lot of different things have
happened. Pitch good, and get outpitched, a lot of no-decisions. I
just have to look forward to the next opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez dodged an early bullet in the first inning, when with
two on and two out Thome's bid for a home run died on the warning
track in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez set down nine Indians in a row until Vizquel lined a
single over shortstop Derek Jeter's head in the sixth and David
Justice was hit by a pitch. That brought up the iron of the
Indians' order _ Ramirez and Thome _ and Vizquel did his best to
distract Hernandez by stealing third while Hernandez held the ball
on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get him out of focus when I stole third and he lost
his head a little bit,'' Vizquel said, ``but then the coach (Mel)
Stottlemyre came out and said, `Don't worry about that guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez answered with his finest moment, setting Ramirez and
Thome down on strikes, Thome with a 3-and-2 changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, he really surprised me,'' Vizquel said. ``He's never
been in this situation before, but he made great pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, it was suggested, the Indians should think about
getting their own Cuban-made pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel smiled. ``There aren't many with that talent. Livan has
a little more velocity, more of a power pitcher, but El Duque, he
knows how to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a cool one, right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
