<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ COMES THROUGH WITH FLYING COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Pressure? Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Pitching to keep your team in a game, in a championship series,
in front of an international television audience and 45,000
unfriendly spectators is not pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez knows real pressure. Pressure is
making $8.75 a month, living in a one-room, cinderblock apartment
in Havana while your country denies you the right to do what you do
best. Pressure is the constant threat of arrest because the leaders
of your country think you might defect, just as your half-brother
did. Pressure is hopping aboard a 20-foot makeshift wooden sailboat
last December with seven friends and relatives, bound for freedom.
Pressure is running aground 10 hours later, somewhere in the
Bahamas, and living on seaweed and conch for three days awaiting
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque has been through all of the above. So how was he going
to get rattled by the Cleveland Indians and/or the expectations of
the Yankee fandom and its maniacal owner?
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban righty with the high kick beat the Indians, 4-0, with
seven-plus innings of three-hit pitching Saturday night at Jacobs
Field. The win evened the American League Championship Series at
2-2 and the 114-win Yankees hope to regain the lead with David
Wells on the mound this afternoon. Saturday night's game was even
more dramatic than Livan Hernandez's heroics for the world champion
Florida Marlins last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pressure but I had no fear,'' Hernandez said through an
interpreter. ``I have been through many difficult times in my life
on and off the field and I knew I would be able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very relaxed, very determined,'' said Yankees manager
Joe Torre. ``A playoff game is a playoff game, just like a walk in
the park for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were tense before Saturday night's Game 4. All the
pressure had shifted to the Pinstripers and there were questions
about New York's ability to deal with adversity, which it was
facing for the first time all year.
</P>
<P>
   And then along came El Duque, the Tiant-esque, high-sock,
low-cap righthander who pitched his last playoff game at Estadio
Latinoamericano in Havana. Under the flag of Cuba, he hurled 10
seasons for Havana's Industriales, but was kicked off the team in
October of '96 for allegedly plotting to defect (Livan Hernandez
defected in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   After crashlanding on Anguilla Cay (an island off Bermuda),
Hernandez and his companions were spotted by a helicopter, and a US
Coast Guard cutter was radioed. The group was initially detained by
local authorities, but Hernandez and his common-law wife acquired
humanitarian visas and took up residence in Costa Rica. Once there,
he was free to sign a $6.6 million contract with the Yankees, the
favorite team of his childhood. He went 6-0 at Triple A, then went
12-4 with a 3.13 ERA in 21 starts with the musclebound Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees needed him desperately in Game 4. It was 57 degrees
at game time and there were fears that El Duque might have trouble
with the cold. Nonsense. It was probably pretty cold on that boat
last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill staked Hernandez to a 1-0 lead with a homer in the
first. El Duque gave up a single to Omar Vizquel in the first and a
double to Kenny Lofton in the third, but was not truly threatened
until the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Leading, 3-0, Hernandez surrendered a one-out single to Vizquel,
then hit David Justice. The crowd howled, but El Duque never lost
his cool, not even when Vizquel stole third while he wasn't looking
and danced down the line while he pitched to the heart of
Cleveland's order. No problem. El Duque fanned Manny Ramirez and
Jim Thome to get out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   He needed only 10 pitches in a rocking-chair seventh, then was
pulled when he walked No. 9 batter Enrique Wilson to start the
eighth. New York's bullpen (Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera) did
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he (Hernandez) was very good,'' said Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove. ``I don't know that he missed any spots all
night long. He threw tough pitches when he had to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some records, Sunday is Hernandez's 29th birthday,
but many of his countrymen believe he is closer to 33. He certainly
pitched like a veteran against Cleveland. Too bad the Communist
Party newspaper will pretend the game never happened. El Duque's
two daughters, still in Cuba, may not hear of their dad's
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, who was rocked for four homers in Game 3 Friday,
would be in turn to pitch a potential seventh game in this series,
but Torre would almost certainly come back with El Duque if there's
a deciding game in New York Wednesday night. And then we might have
a Hernandez brother winning a postseason MVP award for the second
straight season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
