u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BLUES-BOS &LR;      10-11 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BLUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GO FOR KNOT IN OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a night of glitter, stars, and history as the
Bruins opened their 75th National Hockey League season Saturday
night at the FleetCenter. Before the game, Bobby Orr, Derek
Sanderson, former voice of the Bruins Bob Wilson, and ex-coach Don
Cherry participated in the festivities that featured pyrotechnics
and a laser show.
</P>
<P>
   Past meets present. Last year's coach of the year Pat Burns and
rookie of the year Sergei Samsonov were honored for last season's
achievements that they hope will translate into this season's
success.
</P>
<P>
   As warm and fuzzy as the ceremonies were, the contest itself was
a ragtag coaches' nightmare that ended in a 3-3 tie as Boston
battled back from a two-goal deficit twice to earn the point.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe kept the Bruins in the game throughout,
stopping 21 shots while Grant Fuhr made 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the opening jitters got to everybody,'' said Burns,
whose team was defensively challenged the entire night. ``We came
along better after. They're a big team. I didn't realize they were
that big. They were beating us on the boards a little bit. Their
size definitely came into play there at one point but our speed
started picking up and we found a way to get a point and tie the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dafoe was one of the heroes another was enforcer Ken
Baumgartner, who scored his first goal (No. 13 in his career in 628
games) since Jan. 17, 1996, that turned out to be the tying goal at
3:17 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins got off to a rocky start. Just 2:30 into the game,
former Boston College star Marty Reasoner charged in on a
two-on-one with Pascal Rheaume. Reasoner snapped a shot from the
inside edge of the right circle that Dafoe knocked down with his
glove. It was a harbinger of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe had no chance on the Blues' first goal at 8:59. Al
MacInnis, who has one of the hard-est slappers in the league, teed
up a shot from just inside the blue line at the right point and
blistered it at the net. It went off Blues' enforcer Tony Twist and
deflected past Dafoe for the 1-0 lead. Baumgartner later noted that
not only was it the first time he and Twist, who had just his ninth
career goal in 383 games, scored on the same night but it happened
in a game in which neither had a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was equally blameless on the second St. Louis goal, scored
on the power play when left wing Pavol Demitra banged in a
back-door shot from the left post at 16:07. The Bruins got one back
two minutes later on the power play. Samsonov took a pass from
center Jason Allison down low. From behind the net, he backhanded a
pass to Steve Heinze, who beat Fuhr from in front at 18:19.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had a goal nullified at 2:02 of the second. Pronger
committed a kneeing penalty and play continued with defenseman Don
Sweeney shooting from the left circle. Antti Laaksonen beat Fuhr on
the rebound from the crease but it appeared the whistle had blown
prior to the goal, despite the fact that Boston had puck possession
the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He blew the whistle,'' said Burns of referee Blaine Angus,
when asked what he was told about the non-goal. ``Why, I don't
know. Only (baseball) umpires I see give press conferences, our
guys don't. Maybe it's time. He said he blew the whistle because I
guess he thought (the Bruins) lost the puck. He didn't come over
and tell me. He'd be over at the bench all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues regained the two-goal edge at 13:31 when they took
advantage of a Bruins' turnover at the offensive blue line. Demitra
went in on a breakaway and beat Dafoe with a backhander to make it
3-1. Boston started the climb back at 17:08 on the power play.
Samsonov took the puck from Heinze behind the net, skated it right
to left, and curled into the left circle around a pick from
Allison. He let his shot fly and when Fuhr stopped it, he went into
the crease after it and whacked at it again. It went in off
MacInnis and the Bruins were within one, 3-2, setting the stage for
Baumgartner's heroics when he took advantage of a Fuhr miscue. He
scored unassisted on a backhand shot. Even Burns couldn't suppress
a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns won't be laughing if his club has to rely on Dafoe
every game to save it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron Dafoe kept us in the game the whole time,'' said Burns.
``We were making some awful mistakes. I think the puck weighed
about 10 pounds there for awhile. We were getting a lot of passes
intercepted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
