</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING NIGHT WAS REVIVAL FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ The Bruins moved ahead with a new season Saturday
night _ an interesting 3-3 tie with the St. Louis Blues _ but not
without first looking back fondly at their past.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's hockey team turns 75 years old this season and Opening
Night on Causeway Street began with some laser lights and fireworks
and also included a parade of former Black 'n Gold heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Now beginning their fourth season in the Vault, the city's
biggest and richest ATM, the Bruins trotted out Bobby Orr, their
ageless icon, to help in handing Sergei Samsonov the rookie of the
year award. No. 4 picked up assists from Derek Sanderson and Ray
Bourque, with the Causeway crowd shaking the roof over Orr's
appearance as Samsonov clutched the chrome.
</P>
<P>
   One faithful baby boomer in the crowd held high an old
black-and-gold sweater with ``ORR 4 EVER'' on its back. Samsonov,
who received the Calder in the league's June award ceremonies at
Toronto, posed for pictures with his distinguished Boston brethren.
</P>
<P>
   But all eyes, as usual, were on Orr. He was his trademark humble
self, chin tucked, looking embarrassed by the attention. He scooted
in on the heels of Sanderson, with emcee Bob Wilson wasting little
time during introductions _ no doubt at Orr's prompting. Nearly a
quarter-century has passed since Orr laced 'em up for the Bruins,
but he remains the eternal object of the Hub's affection.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional championship won by the Celtics _ the
local entry in the currently-defunct-but-does-anyone-notice NBA _
we live in a relentless hail of pro sports disappointments in Our
Town. The latest chapter in the book of torture, of course, played
out last weekend at Fenway Park when the Red Sox went charging into
the postseason war, only to find their wild card was a joker. Hey,
how were they to know they'd have to send nine guys to the plate
and not four?
</P>
<P>
   Orr is symbolic of a time when we thought it was OK to win, when
we expected good things happened to those who wait ... and wait ...
and wait some more. Now when we sense victory we instantly are
overwhelmed by the fetid stench of doom. Bill Buckner. Bucky Dent.
Too many men on the ice. One too many Parcells in New Orleans. Petr
Klima. Outchamagoucha.
</P>
<P>
   In Orr's day, the Bruins should have won, and they did win, and
he remains that everlasting link to getting it done when it's there
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Until someone serves up a fresh batch of feel-good memories
(inhale deeply here, folks, and hold it until your fingers and toes
turn blue), Orr will own the Boston patent on pure joy.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruins coach Don Cherry also received a warm hand from
the Vault faithful. Grapes presented Pat Burns with the Jack Adams
coach of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry was dressed to the nines, as usual, with starched white
collar matching his mustache and goatee. He looks like a character
peeled from a pouch of fine pipe tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The video screen flashed images of Cherry in his days behind the
Boston bench. Twenty years ago, as it turned out, Cherry was
entering his last season with the Bruins, it all ending in a clash
of egos with general manager Harry Sinden. No coach in Boston since
has been Cherry's equal for showmanship, theatrics, engaging the
media. Parcells was close. Mike Milbury was a smart guy who
cleverly worked at acting crude (witness: the tirade he launched
Bob Johnson's way in the '91 playoffs), but true crazies don't come
in Armani suits. Cherry was a character _ sometimes with a little
too much salt, mind you, especially in how he viewed the early wave
of European players. You might have loved him. You might have hated
him. In all likelihood it was one or the other, nothing in between.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is a character, too, but not in Cherry's league. Times are
different. Money is huge. Burns makes about $750,000 a year, about
seven times what Cherry made. Burns gets heated up now and then and
lashes out with an emotional thunderclap. Then it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry was forever stirring it up, pushing buttons, kicking over
rocks, making himself a cult hero here _ an act he later refined
and turned into a fortune on Canadian television. Nutcases like
Grapes can't land big jobs today. The business is self-important
and believes it is too refined. It is, in fact, too refined for its
own good. A couple of nutcases would go a long way in putting a
little character back in the product.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new hockey season has dawned in the old West End.
The Hub's hockey hopes spring eternal. The Bruins haven't won the
Cup since John Bucyk rhumbaed around Madison Square Garden in '72,
but that drought didn't prevent a sellout 17,565 from pledging
their allegiance once more to the Great Bear Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   How good will they be? Is this the year? Will Bourque one day
rock on his front porch the way a great old hockey man should,
clutching a picture of himself holding that Cup, his cheekbones
chiseled and chafed?
</P>
<P>
   For those answers and more, read these pages in the days, weeks,
and months to come. The first night is now history, will all the
rest be?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
