<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BAUMGARTNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET RESULT FOR BAUMGARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It took 89 games and a little digging under Grant
Fuhr's blocker, but Bruins wing Ken Baumgartner finally showed his
scoring punch, rather than his knockout punch, Saturday night at
the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   And his first goal in a Boston uniform couldn't have come at a
better time, 3:17 into the final period that lifted the Bruins into
a 3-3 standoff with St. Louis on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Baumgartner's first goal since the 1995-96 season, ``at
least 200 games ago,'' by his own count and just his 13th
regular-season goal in 628 National Hockey League games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the happiest moment of his career here and probably the
happiest moment of mine,'' said Bruins coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   It had been all uphill for the Bruins until the Bomber's
hustling forechecking effort and it's fair to say the 32-year-old
veteran, who played for Burns in Toronto, had never been so crowded
in along the boards as he was by the media at his locker Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this was an occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell it's been awhile since I've had this much
attention over one goal,'' he said. ``It was a big one. We'll take
the point. It wasn't our best effort, we have some things to work
on, so when it can be timely, it's helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing fancy about the key play, or even a hint, at
first, that the Bruins would even threaten in the Blues zone. But
when St. Louis defenseman Marc Bergevin slid the puck toward Fuhr,
Baumgartner did his best to create a little confusion by rushing
straight at the goalie in hopes that the puck had not been tied up.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, and, said Baumgartner, ``I don't know if Fuhr was
about to clear it, but I stayed there and it was loose and I was
able to put it in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes if you put pressure on people, they'll do things
that they wouldn't if you just waited for them at the blue line.''
</P>
<P>
   Baumgartner's offensive fireworks put the finishing touch on an
evening of fireworks at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of energy in the building,'' he said, ``but
one of these days, they'll realize you can't set off fireworks
indoors. It was about the second period before you could see across
the ice. There were some legends in the building. It was a great
night for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   And a memorable one for Baumgartner, because his poke and shot
marked the second goal he's scored against Fuhr, ``the only goalie
in the NHL I've scored two on. He's not a bad guy to have that
record against.''
</P>
<P>
   His other goal against Fuhr, Baumgartner said, came on a slap
shot. His most recent goal, he recalled, ``was a game-winner,''
against Winnipeg Jan. 17, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably the active leader (for consecutive games
without a goal),'' he said with a grin, ``but I am no longer.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night when neither of the team's tough guys, Tony Twist of
the Blues and the Bruins' Baumgartner, dropped their gloves, both
players scored goals. Twist opened the scoring and Baumgartner
closed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew good things were about to happen when I saw Twist get
one,'' he said. ``I couldn't have him run away with the scoring
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Baumgartner said he never saw his shot go in because it was off
his backhand and when he got back to the bench, Ted Donato told him
not to rush back to take the faceoff at center ice, but to enjoy
the rare moment with his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a hard worker and such a good guy in the dressing
room that I don't think that anybody would ever tease him about
(his long scoreless streak) or offend the guy,'' said Rob Tallas.
``He works so hard in practice, he's a great leader in the dressing
room. Tonight we were happy that a great guy like that got a goal.
And it was a big one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
