<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-PRONGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRONGER HAS LIVED UP TO BILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five months to the day, back on May 10, Blues captain
Chris Pronger lay on the ice at Joe Louis Arena in Detroit fighting
for what many thought was his survival.
</P>
<P>
   He had just taken a Dmitri Mironov slap shot to the chest and
went into cardiac arrhythmia. Medical personnel rushed to the ice
ready to administer CPR.
</P>
<P>
   But their services weren't needed. As quickly as Pronger's heart
had gone weak and irregular it began to pump strong and steady. He
was taken to the hospital for tests, all of which showed no
abnormalities, and two days later he was taking a regular shift in
the playoff series against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night at the FleetCenter, in a 3-3 tie against the
Bruins, Pronger was doing what the Hartford Whalers, in general,
and general manager Brian Burke, in particular, envisioned when
they made him their top pick, second overall, in the 1993 draft.
</P>
<P>
   And showing no ill effects from what he, his coach, and his
teammates call a ``freak thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He logged 33 minutes 48 seconds of ice time, more than any other
player except the goalies, had a pair of quality shots on net, and
played with his usual reckless abandon, racking up six penalty
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical Chris Pronger game,'' said Blues coach Joel
Quenneville. ``He's a tough kid. What happened was a freak thing.
At the time, you had some scary thoughts going across your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger downplays the incident, saying, ``It was isolated, just
out of the blue. Stuff like that happens. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Twist, who had the Blues' first goal Saturday night,
recalls the incident, and Pronger's reaction, vividly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't figure out what all the fuss was about,'' Twist
said. ``He was kicking and moaning on the stretcher on his way to
the ambulance and wanted to get back into the game. That's how bad
he wanted to get back into the game. He's a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   What the 24-year-old Pronger has accomplished thus far in his
short career hasn't surprised Burke, now president and GM of the
Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he'd be a guy who could play 30 minutes or so a
game, be a Norris candidate, play nasty, and be a respectable, but
not damaging scorer,'' Burke said. ``He hasn't won the Norris yet,
but he will within the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford thought so much of Pronger that they swapped picks with
San Jose to assure they'd get their man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a deal that helped both teams,'' said Burke. ``Sam Jose
wanted Viktor Kozlov and we wanted Pronger. I just couldn't believe
that a guy that big (6 feet 6 inches, 220 pounds) had such quick
feet. We had to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger spent two years struggling with Hartford before being
dealt to St. Louis in the summer of 1995 for Brendan Shanahan. And
since joining the Blues, he's done all that Burke projected.
</P>
<P>
   e's been playing his 30 or minutes a game, has done some
scoring (27 goals, 71 assists), and picked up more than 400 penalty
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still young and maturing every day,'' said Quenneville.
``I wouldn't trade him for anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 0229EDT &QL; 
