<HEADLINE>
OOPS, BRUINS BOTCH THE PLAY _ AND SCORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ The most important play of the game was a
mistake. With UCLA clinging to a 31-28 lead, quarterback Cade
McNown called the wrong formation on a pass play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it scripted, but it was supposed to go to Brian
(Poli-Dixon),'' UCLA receiver Danny Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, McNown faked an option run, then dropped into the
pocket and fired downfield to Farmer, who raced 64 yards for a
touchdown that gave UCLA a 38-28 lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they bit on the run fake, so it was wide open,''
Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Character switch: UCLA, the team that loves fast starts and
trick plays, got a dose of its own imagination Saturday night. Long
known as a bastion of blandness, Arizona dipped into the creative
chapter of its playbook in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats used a fake punt to set up their first touchdown,
with punter Ryan Springston passing 35 yards to A.J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   They used cornerback Chris McAlister as a tailback and receiver.
In the second quarter, the Wildcats shifted to a no-huddle offense,
which propelled them to another touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they ran several plays with quarterbacks Keith Smith
and Jenkins on the field together.
</P>
<P>
   __ Don't ask: All-American offensive tackle Kris Farris, a
junior, has been bombarded by questions about his future.
Specifically: Will he turn pro after the season?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, he doesn't know. Farris will seek advice after
the season _ both from NFL general managers and the NFL Draft
Advisory Board _ and then decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farris is one of 10 finalists for the Lombardi Award, given to
the nation's top lineman. Other finalists include Ohio State
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer and Texas A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen.
Based on the Lombardi Award's initial press release, Farris has
little chance. His name was spelled ``Ferris.''
</P>
<P>
   __ It's good: Chris Sailer made his first field goal of the
season when he connected from 41 yards to give UCLA a 24-21 lead in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   __ Saw it coming: Bruins coach Bob Toledo wasn't surprised by
the importance of Saturday's game. He had it pegged in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look on the schedule and put pinpoints on certain games,''
he said. ``I felt this would be our first one. I thought it would
be Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Say what?: Lanky receiver Poli-Dixon excels at making
difficult sideline catches; he thrusts one leg into the air while
dragging the other inbounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call that, `Pee on the hydrant,' '' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fatherly advice: Toledo spoke with suspended tailback
Jermaine Lewis several times last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to make the decision because I feel bad for the
kid,'' he said. ``I told him he's like a son _ `I'm going to
discipline you, but I still love you.' I tell the (players), `Don't
make me have to discipline you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis could be reinstated as early as Monday if Toledo
determines Lewis was acting in self defense when he fought Elonza
Malone III in the early hours of Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   __ Still waiting: UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis said he did
not speak to Miami AD Paul Dee last week about rescheduling the
canceled game for Dec. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
