<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0633 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-UCLA-AZR &LR;      10-11 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-UCLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA EXPLODES IN 4TH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It was flip to flop.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's dreams of an unbeaten season went flat suddenly and in
stunning succession Saturday night in a 52-28 loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats high-wire ride after Ortege Jenkins' acrobatic flip
into the end zone at Washington nine days took a tumble within 2:08
of the fourth quarter at Arizona Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Third-ranked UCLA scored three touchdowns within that stretch, a
Bruin blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Brown, a junior running back from Mountain Pointe High
School, scored two of them. One was on a 54 yard run. The other
covered 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The initial strike in the Bruins' TD triple was a 64-yard pass
to Danny Farmer from Cade McNown, UCLA's Heisman Trophy contender.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, the thunderstruck crowd of 58,738 fans
had seen the probable end of No. 10 Arizona's chances at a Pac-10
title.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd also witnessed Arizona's first loss since last season.
The Wildcats' nine-game win streak was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, were any national title pretensions. UCLA (4-0, 2-0
Pac-10) was the only contender at the sudden, strange end.
</P>
<P>
   It was strange, because an apparent first-half shootout
continued through the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins grabbed the second-half advantage on a 41-yard field
goal by Chris Sailor. The scoring opportunity was created by a
37-yard interception return of an Ortege Jenkins pass attempt. The
chance at a UCLA touchdown was killed by a Marcus Bell sack.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 5:20 later, the Wildcats retaliated with the brilliance
and boldness that have become their trademarks. The key play was
some beautiful footwork by Jeremy McDaniel on a 30-yard reception
of a Jenkins pass. The payoff came with a TD reception by McDaniel,
who stretched across the goal line to catch a 28-yard pass from
Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins were as resilient as Arizona was bold. The Bruins
put together a carefully-called, unerring drive that covered 53
yards in 13 plays. McNown, UCLA's Heisman Trophy contender, applied
the capper with a 3-yard TD run.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about the first half was ordinary. More like
extraordinary. There were big plays, small plays. And unusual
plays. Within two quarters, there was enough of the unpredictable
for one season.
</P>
<P>
   Call it wild, wacky and uniquely Arizona in a season that has
been full of Wildcat surprises from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's first touchdown was set up by a punter's pass to a
reserve cornerback. Among the Arizona Stadium's crowd of 58,738 _
the fourth largest in school history _ only the punter and
cornerback were not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it happened:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona punter Ryan Springston, an All-State high school
quarterback in Kansas, waited at midfield in what appeared to be a
kicking situation. After all, it was fourth down and about eight
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Springston caught the long snap. A split-second later,
cornerback A.J. Brown, a redshirt freshman from Washington High
School, was open near the one-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Springston lofted a pass. Brown caught it. Springston and Brown
made it look as though they had been a combination for years. They
haven't been, of course. A dramatic guessing game full of bluffs
and power had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats held the early advantage after Kelvin Eafon dove
into the end zone two plays after the punter-to-cornerback strike
late in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's turn was next. Freshman running back DeShaun Foster
introduced himself four plays after Wildcats receiver Dennis
Northcutt fumbled and UCLA recovered at the Bruins 40. First, there
was a 33-yard pass from McNown to Danny Farmer. Then, Foster broke
an attempted tackle by Marcus, spun and raced 37 yards for the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   It was all even. On the scoreboard. And on the sensational
scale. But it was far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first quarter ended, the Wildcats struck again. This
time, the opportunity was created by tailback Trung Canidate, the
powerful junior from Central High. He caught about a 10-yard pass
from Ortege Jenkins and raced about 64 on a path that took him from
one sideline to the center of the field to the Bruin four. The
powerful Eafon bulled his way in the end zone one the next play.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crowd caught its collective breath, it was UCLA's
turn. First, Foster broke a Scooter Sprotte tackle on a 20-yard
dash. A couple of plays later, an eight-yard Foster run and a
15-yard personal foul penalty against Chris McAlister put the
Bruins on the Arizona 15. Three plays later, McNown hit Brian
Poli-Dixon, a sophomore from Tucson, with a 14-yard TD strike early
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Within five minutes, the Wildcats drove 80-yards, and this time
Keith Smith was at quarterback. The key play was a 27-yard pass to
Northcutt, who looked over his shoulder and pulled the ball down
with one hand. The TD was scored on a 15-yard strike from Smith
Jeremy McDaniel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
