<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-SIDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BROWN SHOWS FRIENDS, FAMILY &AMP; UA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ With 45 friends and relatives in the stands, UCLA
tailback Keith Brown knew the pressure was on to put on a show.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile, but Brown, a junior from Phoenix's Mountain
Pointe High School, came through Saturday night against Arizona.
Brown scored twice within a 25-second span in the fourth quarter to
help the Bruins break open a tight game and beat the Wildcats,
52-28.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was in the starting lineup in place of Jermaine Lewis, who
was suspended from the game because of his involvement in a fight
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of pressure on me,'' Brown said. ``And a lot of
the media were hitting me up for interviews over the last week. But
I was coming home. I was supposed to put on a show. And I think I
did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown hadn't done much Saturday until the fourth quarter, and in
fact, he had been overshadowed by freshman DeShaun Foster, who
rushed 20 times for 118 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA led by three going into the fourth quarter, when
quarterback Cade McNown hit flanker Danny Farmer with a 64-yard
pass to extend the lead to 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins then shut down the Wildcats' offense. On the first
play of the next possession, Brown took the ball off right tackle,
slipped a couple of defenders and cut back left and sprinted to a
54-yard touchdown to give the Bruins a 17-point lead with 9:35
left. ``I just had one man to beat and it was a foot race then,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA intercepted Arizona quarterback Keith Smith on the next
possession. On the next play, Brown went 20 yards for another
touchdown. Until Saturday, Brown had carried just 14 times for 37
yards this season, although he had scored two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Brown finished the night with 91 yards on nine carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great game,'' Brown said. ``It was like a
15-round boxing match.''
</P>
<P>
   Both opponents used nearly all of their tricks.
</P>
<P>
   To see the different offenses used in college football, you
usually have to have a remote control in your palm, a satellite
dish on your roof and a free Saturday on your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you could have just watched Saturday night's game at Arizona
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Like end-of-the-week stew, there was a little something for
everyone in the pot. A little bit of Canadian League flavor, a dash
of Arena League, a bit of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   There were long passes, triple options and power running. There
were quarterbacks and defensive backs catching passes, and punters
and receivers throwing them. Receivers were running the option. Two
quarterbacks were lining up in the same backfield.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just in the first half. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
