A0635 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BICKLEY-A     10-11 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLIPPER FALLS OFF ARIZONA'S FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - Destiny disappeared. The karma expired. The
somersaults turned to smelling salts.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of 128 seconds, the great fantasy went poof.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona will not weasel its way into the Fiesta Bowl. The
Wildcats will not play for a national championship on Frank Kush
Field while the normal tenants are off in some remote outpost. The
biggest football game in school history went from riveting to
ridiculous, and the hosts will need much detergent to get the tire
tracks off their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the game got serious, just when the final 15 minutes
began to tick and the great upset seemed within reach, UCLA hung a
28-point barrage on Arizona, coasting to a 52-28 victory that said
more about the winners than it did the losers.
</P>
<P>
   They have a Heisman Trophy candidate in Cade McNown, a rising
star in tailback DeShaun Foster, an offense that almost scores at
will. Since opening last season with losses to Ryan Leaf and Peyton
Manning, the Bruins have won 14 straight. And they made a
convincing case to what many have expected since last December.
</P>
<P>
   They could be the best team in the nation and should have a
chance to prove it come January. After all, coupled with Nebraska's
loss Saturday, the Bruins occupy one lane on the fast track to the
Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In Tucson, the pain will linger, the bruises exacerbated by the
missed opportunity. &QL; 
No Cinderella &QL; 
Every season has its Cinderella, its enchanted program, its
underdog that charms the nation. Doug Flutie and the Hail Mary.
Jake Plummer and the Sun Devils. Northwestern and its journey to
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the slipper seemed to fit Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was Ortege Jenkins and his highlight-reel tumble into
the end zone. On Saturday, it was a punter throwing a successful
bomb. An acrobatic, one-handed catch by Dennis Northcutt. A pair of
quarterbacks that not only shared playing time, but lined up in
something called the ``Muddle Huddle'' and threw the ball to each
other. A full-fledged diving catch in the end zone by Jeremy
McDaniel that staked the Wildcats to a 28-24 lead midway through
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   If they could hold on to the lead, if they could prevail, the
Wildcats could dare to dream. The schedule softens up considerably.
The two biggest games left on the docket _ skirmishes against
Oregon and Arizona State _ are both at home. They could think about
playing in their first Rose Bowl. And with a couple of breaks, they
might even make the big dance.
</P>
<P>
   It all ended so suddenly. Collapsed so convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   But they will find solace. If UCLA runs the table, Arizona still
has a chance for the Rose Bowl. And no matter what happens, they
have succeeded where their rivals in Tempe have failed, and that's
saying something. &QL; 
ABC made fans losers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the real loser was a nation of college football
fans, and the lesson was a painful reminder of priorities and
money. Because no matter how much you smell like destiny _ and the
Wildcats carried the scent all week _ you can never get past the
800-pound gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on ABC. Shame on the suits who opted for the knee-jerk
allure of Notre Dame. Shame on the people who, according to one
source, wanted to use Saturday's game at Sun Devil Stadium as a dry
run for the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   So what did they get? A boring game. A power outage that had the
Bidwill family smiling and officials from the Bowl Championship
Series slightly alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Everything you know about the East Coast bias originates from
this, from marquee games televised at night when they should be
showcased in the afternoon. It is how Troy Aikman finished third in
the Heisman balloting in 1988. How Stanford's John Elway finished
second in 1982. How Plummer finished third to Danny Wuerffel in
1996. How a fraud named Gino Torretta took home a trophy that
rightfully belonged to Marshall Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   And what did they miss? Nothing but two wonderful teams and an
explosive game of pinball. One powerhouse threatened for three
quarters before showing its mettle. And in the end, one
overachiever that simply ran out of magic. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
