<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BLAHS IN EVIDENCE EVEN THOUGH IT'S PREPLAYOFF SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Presidents' Trophy banner? Nice.
</P>
<P>
   The season-opening audience at Reunion Arena? Just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The new guy from St. Louis? He'll do.
</P>
<P>
   So, when do the playoffs start?
</P>
<P>
   It irks Stars coach Ken Hitchcock that a team can play earnest,
Cup-caliber hockey for six months, and people _ people like you and
me _ can yawn and jingle pocket change during the banner-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But that's hockey. Some people had important cell-phone calls to
make.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season, we have come to learn, is six months of
sound, fury and a few fistfights, signifying ... a nice banner? The
meaningful stuff is not supposed to start until around Memorial
Day.
</P>
<P>
   But anybody who truly thinks that doesn't know Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   On a banner night at Reunion, the Stars again displayed
Cup-caliber form in throttling the Buffalo Sabres, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any feelings of been-there, done-that among the
Presidents' Trophy-winning Stars, they vanished swiftly under the
emotion of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first 12 minutes,'' Hitchcock said, ``with the way we
moved the puck; I haven't seen our team play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the acknowledged best goaltender on the planet, Dominik
Hasek, the Stars dominated play for those first 12 minutes and then
settled back to play with shoulder-jarring efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 line of new guy Brett Hull, Mike Modano and Jere
Lehtinen created an immediate presence. The Stars' deep cadre of
defensemen was superb. Hasek, for his part, was outplayed by the
Stars' Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Stars fans had to pinch their Calvins to remind themselves that
Hasek and the Sabres reached the Eastern Conference finals last
season. Yet, the home team won almost handily last night.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stopped 27 of 28 shots, reminding the local crowd that
his alleged meltdown in the Western Conference finals was not the
Eddie they've come to love and know. Granted, Belfour had plenty of
help in front of him against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know where he was really strong?'' Hitchcock suggested.
``With the puck, in the area around the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules are different this season. The ice is foreign, in a
way. With the goal lines moved out an additional two feet, goalies
have to resist the wanderlust that once beckoned some of them.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has always been eager to stray. But last night he was as
trusty as a guard dog.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Hitchcock said, ``He helped us on breakouts
probably 15 times by getting the puck out quickly to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars made Hasek pay. Interestingly, against the Czech
Republic-born Hasek, who beat the world at the 1998 Winter
Olympics, the Stars are 7-3. This is the same goaltender who has
won the NHL's most valuable player award, the Hart Trophy, two
years in a row. This is the same Hasek who has won the Vezina
Trophy as the league's top goalie for four of the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars peppered him with opening-night welcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scored two great goals against him tonight,'' Hitchcock
said. ``But we had two two-on-ones and one three-on-one, and he
stoned us in all three. He never allows you to stretch your lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But a 4-1 victory sounds like an ample stretching.
</P>
<P>
   It was midseason hockey in the NHL's yawning days of autumn. How
many days until the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   While the crowd sauntered in, the Stars held a quasi-impressive
ceremony to hoist three banners signifying their last season
accomplishments. There were cheers and nods of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really bothers me when people write that stuff off,''
Hitchcock said later. ``People write that it was a waste of energy
to get there, and that bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning things like that set such a strong foundation for your
team _ a work ethic foundation, a consistent-play foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll take a President's Trophy over an Also-Participated Plaque
any day, Hitchcock was trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   In six months, we'll see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
