<HEADLINE>
TWO-WAY PERFORMER KEYS NORTH TEXAS' WIN AT BOISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ North Texas defensive tackle Brian Waters asked
coach Darrell Dickey last week if he had a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop by, Brian,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Waters did, pleading with Dickey to give him a chance to play
both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey remembered, calling Waters' number in a critical
third-down, fourth-quarter, UNT-trailing situation last night
against Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   Waters responded by hauling in a 27-yard touchdown pass that
provided the go-ahead score in UNT's 21-13 victory against Boise
State last night at Bronco Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he listened,'' said Waters, who played tight end his
first three seasons before moving to defense in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   It was Waters' first reception of the season. It was UNT's first
Big West Conference game of the season. And it was also UNT's first
victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And when that victory looked in doubt _ Boise State (3-3, 0-1
Big West Conference) had responded by driving to UNT's 24-yard line
_ Waters responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   He caused a fumble that linebacker Fred Pertile recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the victory remained in doubt until tailback Tubby
Coleman's 10-yard touchdown with 1:44 remaining. Coleman finished
with a career-high 96 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a little redemption for Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   He had a costly fumble a play after the Eagles (1-4, 1-0 Big
West Conference) got into Boise State territory with a spectacular,
over-the-shoulder, 40-yard catch by Jay Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sick feeling,'' Coleman said of his fumble. ``So, yes,
it did feel a little redeemed.''
</P>
<P>
   The nail-biting finale, with Boise State failing to convert a
fourth down deep in UNT territory with nine seconds remaining, was
in sharp contrast to most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were plagued by penalties and sloppy play.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams opened with yawn-inspiring displays.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a lazy first quarter ended, UNT and Boise State had
combined for 95 yards, a handful of first downs and hardly a threat
of a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, better than 20 minutes in, a 21-yard Todd Belcastro
field goal ended that drought, well, at least for BSU.
</P>
<P>
   A suddenly revitalized Broncos bunch followed with a five-play,
63-yard drive. The touchdown came on a 15-yard pass from backup
quarterback Nate Sparks to backup tailback Shaunard Harts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I was most pleased about?'' Dickey said. ``We're
0-4 and we fell behind and we were making some mistakes, and not
one time did I feel like the players were saying `Here, we go
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead UNT went 82 yards in 56 seconds, ending with Coleman
scampering in for a 4-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back passes by Jason Attaway _ a 23-yarder to Young and
a 33-yarder to Carlos Yearwood _ keyed that drive. Attaway finished
7-of-17 for a career-high 155 yards. Extra points When Garrett
Courtney's 48-yard field goal attempt sailed wide right with 37
seconds remaining in the first quarter, it broke his streak of nine
consecutive field goals made from 40 yards or better. ... The
Eagles are 0-5 in coin tosses this season. ... UNT's 82-yard,
touchdown-producing drive marked its longest of the season. ...
When UNT took a 14-13 lead with 12:23 remaining, it was their first
lead since the second quarter against Oklahoma in Week 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
