<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0669 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     10-11 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Oct. 18.)  
(lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boys: The Untold Story of 732 Young Concentration Camp
Survivors
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Gilbert. Owl/Holt, $16.95. A seasoned custodian of the
memory of the Holocaust puts a human face on the catastrophe by
letting a remarkable group of mostly Polish Jews recall their
childhood ordeals. Last year our reviewer, Michael R. Marrus,
called this a `` remarkable volume ... about survival and painful,
vivid, individual memories of surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Believers: A Novella and Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Baxter. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. These
psychologically dense tales track the unpredictable destinies of
ordinary Midwesterners, often focusing on the internal struggle
between the forces of love and violence. ``It's the eloquence of
the language _ the quirky intelligence, the humor, the lively
rhythmic assurance of sentences and paragraphs _ along with the
surprising plots, that makes these stories such a pleasure to
read,'' Francine Prose said here last year. The same publisher has
reissued an earlier collection by the author,  &UR; Through the Safety
Net: Stories &LR;  ($13), which features many middle-class characters
estranged from life _ a couple paralyzed by the death of their
child, for example, or a perpetual graduate student dazed by the
real world. In 1985 in the Book Review, Ron Hansen called these 11
stories ''original, gracefully written, always moving, frequently
funny and _ that rarest of compliments _ wise.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nearer, My God: An Autobiography of Faith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By William F. Buckley Jr. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $14. The
author may be an imposing public intellectual but he's also a
devout Christian, and this unusually personal essay is both a
celebration of his lifelong Roman Catholicism and a doctrinal
apologia for the church. ``It is certain to provide many insights
into the mind of a polished writer ... and it will do much to
explain how the hopefully changeless faith of a Catholic jibes with
the politics of a late-20th-century American political
conservative,'' William R. Everdell wrote here in 1997.  &UR; In Living
Faith &LR; , by Jimmy Carter (Times Books/Random House, $13), the former
president laces his spiritual self-portrait with poems, Scripture
and frank revelations about his personal and political lives. The
book, which includes a new preface by Carter, is ''an appealing,
straightforward account of a life marked, as many are, by
unexpected successes and crushing failures,'' Michael Wright said
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lucky You &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carl Hiaasen. Warner Vision, $7.50. JoLayne Lucks doesn't
have much good fortune in the romance department, but things look
up when she wins half of a $28 million prize in the Florida
lottery: the trouble is, the other winners are two dirtball white
supremacists who aim to rip her off. ``Hiaasen writes witty
dialogue that crackles, and his characters are eccentrically
colorful,'' Charles Salzberg said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Goldwyn: A Biography &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Berg. Riverhead, $16. The legendary mogul who set
Hollywood in motion was an inspired ruffian whose outsize ambitions
and appetites make for terrific reading. ``This story of a grabby
but imaginative man would make a more telling movie about America
... than Goldwyn ever produced himself,'' Mordecai Richler wrote
here in 1989. On a smaller stage,  &UR; How I Made a Hundred Movies in
Hollywood and Never Lost a Dime &LR; , by Roger Corman with Jim Jerome
(Da Capo, $14.95), explains how the schlockmeister responsible for
fare like ``Bloody Mama'' was able to become a major independent
force in filmmaking while running an absurdly tight ship. ``Corman
comes across as likable, admirable and, in his ability to survive
in Hollywood with his integrity intact, even awe-inspiring,'' Barry
Gewen wrote here in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Byrne &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Burgess. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $10.95. The author's final
novel is an audacious hybrid even for a lifelong experimentalist:
the story of a minor modern composer whose real skills are in the
bedroom unfolds in novelistic fashion but entirely in rhymed verse.
Last year our reviewer, Dana Gioia, called this ``genuinely
astonishing _ a complex dark comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Platypus and the Mermaid: And Other Figments of the
Classifying Imagination &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Harriet Ritvo. Harvard University, $15.95. A history
professor chronicles the Victorian obsession with classifying and
categorizing God's creatures, particularly as they relate to man
and the dinner table. Last year in the Book Review, Stefan Collini
called this an ''entertaining and informative tour of both the
highroads and the hedgerows of natural history.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Teen Angel: And Other Stories of Wayward Love &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Marianne Gingher. Zuckerman Cannon, $14. The adolescent
characters who populate these inventive tales somehow manage to be
both quirky and down to earth despite the broken adult
relationships around them. ''Gingher possesses a stylistic deftness
and a flair for comic detail,'' W.L. Taitte said here in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Magician's Assistant &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Patchett. Harvest, $13. When a gay Los Angeles magician
named Parsifal dies suddenly, he leaves behind his heartbroken
assistant, Sabine, and a secret past that leads her to Nebraska and
a family she never knew he had. Last year our reviewer, Suzanne
Berne, called the author ``an adroit, graceful writer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
