<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-YOUNG12-COX     10-11 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-YOUNG12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andrew Young tells Christians in China to keep faith
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Marcia Kunstel and Joseph Albright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANJING, China _ Like the preacher he started out to be, Andrew
Young came here Sunday and delivered solace and hope to an overflow
congregation of nodding, rapt Chinese parishioners _ believers
under a communist regime that keeps religion on a short leash.
</P>
<P>
   Like the diplomat he became, the former United Nations
ambassador, mayor of Atlanta and U.S. congressman plans to meet
later this week with Chinese leaders in Beijing to explain how that
short leash might chafe U.S.- China relations. Young is expected to
tell the Chinese that America is about to pursue a policy of
punishing countries that persecute religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the nondenominational Mochou Road Church, one of the
country's largest Protestant churches, Young invoked the memory of
the Rev. Martin Luther King in a speech reminiscent of those Young
used to inspire embattled civil rights workers in the American
South.
</P>
<P>
   ``He challenged our government about many of its policies,''
Young recalled of the friend and mentor he said gave his life for a
cause stemming from his Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we refused to do any violence against people, even those
who did violence against us. We followed Jesus's commands to love
your enemy and to bless those who persecute you,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show them your love of God, and God works through you to
transform them. So God will work through you in this church to show
the love of God to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,600 Chinese parishioners listening to the sermon
in translation may have detected an underlying message addressing
their own daily lives. Here in China, the openly religious are
relatively few, religious education and proselytizing are
restricted, and those who refuse to toe the Chinese government's
mark by worshipping in unregistered ``underground churches'' may
find themselves imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation of common, everyday Chinese, men and women,
elderly and children, dressed in everything from old wool Mao coats
to pretty silk jackets, listened closely in the sanctuary, then
gave Young solid applause. Others listened in a next-door meeting
hall where the service was piped in for the overflow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very touching. Very inspiring,'' said Yu Zhi Xiang, a tiny
68-year-old happy to stop and chat after the service.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese are not accustomed to suggestions they directly
challenge their government a la Martin Luther King. And Young
certainly did not exhort them to storm out, confront the state and
convert their 1.2 billion countrymen not already believers.
</P>
<P>
   The government conservatively estimates there are 10 million
Protestants and 4 million Catholics in China, and even double that
would still comprise only 2 percent of the population. But the
numbers of churchgoers are said to be rising _ the Rev. Jiang Juin
Yu said he receives ``several hundred'' new members every year at
Mochou Road _ and the country's communist government has been
careful to prevent the movement from getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Besides imposing limitations on religious education and
promotion, the government requires that church meeting places be
registered and may censor cleric's sermons. Officials can prohibit
a sect or group from meeting on vague grounds of being a
``pseudo-religion'' or endangering security. Christian churches are
supposed to be nondenominational _ either Protestant or Catholic,
the latter stripped of ties to the Rome church.
</P>
<P>
   These constraints are part of the reason Young and a delegation
of the National Council of Churches of Christ in the USA, of which
he is president-elect, are making this visit to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trip is different, because we'll meet with government
officials to talk about the implications of the new (American)
policy,'' said the Rev. Joan B. Campbell, National Council of
Churches general secretary. The new policy is the Religious
Persecution Act, passed by Congress but not yet signed by President
Clinton, which provides for possible U.S. diplomatic or economic
sanctions against countries found to persecute citizens for their
religious practices.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day visit has been arranged by the China Christian
Council, the state-sanctioned body that promotes Protestant
religious activity and serves as the formal channel to the
communist government. The National Council of Churches has
maintained relations with the China Christian Council since its
formation in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, Young said China's religious situation
``is very complex'' and has been portrayed in a negative and
one-dimensional way by American political figures intent on
China-bashing for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of nuts in Atlanta that we've put in jail for
preaching on street corners and disrupting traffic,'' Young said.
``How can I assume that I can make judgments about a nation this
large, with more than a billion people?''
</P>
<P>
   Young's last visit to China grew out of the Nike controversy. In
1997, he visited Nike factories in China, Vietnam and Indonesia as
a paid Nike consultant to investigate charges by American labor and
human rights advocates that Nike mistreated its workers, and
similarly found a complex situation not so simple for him to
declare right or wrong. He was later criticized by some Western
human rights groups for ignoring their complaint that Nike workers
were paid ``below-subsistence'' wages and subjected to corporal
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Young is not the only one to find China's religious situation
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western religious leaders have expressed concern that
attempts to punish the prickly Chinese government for its domestic
policies may backfire, causing the government to crack down on the
freedoms that do exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to support these churches every way we can,'' said
Campbell of the NCC. ``Just to be a Christian in an atheist society
is a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
