 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, Oct.
12.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (Moving in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-SPENDING (Undated) _ The global financial crisis and
the plunging stock market are beginning to unnerve the nation's
more affluent families and make them more cautious in their
spending. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-GATES (Undated) _ The U.S. government and Microsoft
Corp. may be nearing an historic antitrust showdown. But Bill
Gates, the man who co-founded Microsoft, has largely disengaged
himself from the company's legal defense to concentrate on new ways
to extend the world's largest independent software company's
influence into the next century. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LAWSUITS (Undated) _ Microsoft's legal department
could keep a travel agent fully occupied these days. In addition to
dispatching lawyers from Redmond, Wash., to federal court in
Washington, D.C., the company is currently defending itself against
lawsuits filed by software companies in San Jose, Calif., Salt Lake
City and Bridgeport, Conn. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-LEGISLATION (Washington) _ A long-sought compromise
to let high-technology companies hire more foreign workers has been
derailed in the Senate, and infighting in the final hours of the
105th Congress is threatening final passage of two other
cornerstones of the information technology industry's legislative
agenda. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWS-MEDIA (New York) _ CBS, ABC and NBC cannot compete with
CNN, MSNBC and the Fox News Channel in the 24-news business. That
does not mean they are getting out of the news-gathering business.
But it does mean they are dramatically changing the way they
conduct it. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FELICITY-HYPE-MEDIA (Undated) _ Two weeks into the run of the
new WB series ``Felicity,'' it stands as a textbook example of the
impact of a perfectly orchestrated symphony of buzz _ and perhaps
of its limitations. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-TRANSITION-MEDIA (New York) _ The changing of the guard
at Forbes magazine _ with veteran editor James W. Michaels, 77,
being replaced by William Baldwin, 47 _ is not just one of
generations, but of taste and consumer sensibility. By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-TIMES-MEDIA (Undated) _ The audacious effort to push
outward from the Financial Times' longtime beachheads in Washington
and New York was started a year ago. Now, measured against itself,
The Financial Times _ known familiarly as the FT _ is doing quite
well, thank you. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NAUMANN-POLITICS-MEDIA (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Michael Naumann
swims with the sharks, instead of the carps, since he abandoned the
rarefied world of New York publishing for a political career and a
tenure as German culture minister. Still, though he's now a nouveau
politician, he came to mingle with publishers at the 50th annual
Frankfurt Book Fair, a sprawling yearly rite of the book industry
that this week drew some 6,700 national publishers promoting more
than 360,000 titles. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-VIDEO-HYBID (Undated) _ Despite test marketing in two
cities that did not appear to be a runaway success, the national
rollout is underway for Divx, a disk-based recorded movie format
intended to compete with rental videocassettes and the emerging DVD
digital disk format. At the same time, industry rivals have gone on
the counterattack with newspaper ads in several major cities that
extol DVD while obliquely panning Divx _ a DVD hybrid that allows
viewing of a recorded film only for a limited time, unless buyers
pay additional fees. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE (Moving in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BACON-DISCOVERY (New York) _ For several weeks, the basement of
Tony Shafrazi's SoHo gallery has been transformed into a makeshift
photography studio where scores of high-voltage lights and
large-format cameras mingle with paintings of mostly distorted,
screaming figures. The paintings are unmistakably by the hand of
Francis Bacon, the Irish-born artist best known for his macabre,
twisted images, according to two leading Bacon experts. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   PFAIR-CONCERT-REVIEW (New York) _ Liz Phair has been accused of
many things since releasing her debut album, ``Exile in Guyville''
(Matador/Capitol), in 1993. Vanity is certainly one of them.
Evidence of it abounded at Roseland, starting with a preperformance
slide show that captured Ms. Phair in myriad poses: baring her
breasts, smooching some guy, guzzling a beer. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   OEDIPUS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ The unfortunate habits that
characterized Sophocles' mother-loving monarch are to some degree
shared by the title character of Dare Clubb's ``Oedipus,'' a
serio-comic meditation on destiny and its discontents. By Ben
Brantley
</P>
<P>
   JANE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Review of ``The Evolution of
Jane,'' by Cathleen Schine. By Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HARRIMAN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Reviews of Lifetime's ``Life of
the Party: Pamela Harriman Story'' and ``Intimate Portrait: Pamela
Harriman.'' By Anita Gates.
</P>
