<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-FOLLOWUP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets at Wolfpack: Make or break time
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary keeps telling his
team to approach this season as if it was playing 11 one-game
seasons. The Yellow Jackets' next game _ Saturday at N.C. State _
might be the one to make or break the season.
</P>
<P>
   Beat N.C. State and the Jackets (3-1, 2-0 ACC) are in a position
to fight Florida State and Virginia for the conference title. Lose,
and Tech will have its work cut out to get to a better bowl than
the Carquest.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack (3-1, 2-0) has been the surprise of the season,
upsetting Florida State 24-7 and following with a 38-17 win over
Syracuse Thursday night. Torry Holt (29 catches, 594 yards, four
touchdowns) is making a case for being the top receiver in the
country, and quarterback Jamie Barnette is having a strong year.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in N.C. State's loss to Baylor and near-loss to Ohio
University, and the Wolfpack vulnerabilities come to the surface,
but N.C. State is clearly Tech's toughest opponent yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing with great, great effort and enthusiasm,''
O'Leary said. ``They've got their crowd behind them big-time.
They're making big plays on offense and defense. Holt could be tops
in the country. What doesn't he have? He's strong. He's quick. He
can catch. He's got big hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what Tech has planned for Holt defensively, it is yet to
be seen. Cornerback Jamara Clark is Tech's best cover man, but he
won't be asked to take Holt on by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody in the country who can cover him
1-on-1,'' O'Leary said. ``(But) If you overload on him, they've got
two other receivers who can beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tech, here are some observations by O'Leary following
Saturday's 41-13 victory over Duke:
</P>
<P>
   _ Good: Joe Hamilton. Big plays on offense, such as Hamilton and
Dez White hooking up for a 53-yard touchdown. Creating turnovers on
defense: The Jackets scored 10 points off two forced turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad: Dropped balls. Tech had six of them against Duke.
``They're running before they have the ball,'' O'Leary said. ``You
can't do that in a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Worrisome: The health of backup quarterback George Godsey, who
pulled his hamstring at the end of practice Thursday. Without him
against Duke, Tech had to risk playing Hamilton for the entire
game.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the plan was if Hamilton had to come out and the
game wasn't close to use walk-on Alex Thompson. If the game was
close and Hamilton had to come out, he'd use true freshman Jermaine
Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he'll use the same plan this week if Godsey is
unable to go. The difference is Thompson will have more than one
light practice day to get prepared for something besides running
the scout team in practice. O'Leary doesn't want to use Crenshaw if
at all possible, thus saving him a year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   UP NEXT FOR GEORGIA TECH
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: N.C. State
</P>
<P>
   When: Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Carter-Finley Stadium, Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: WSB; WGST (640 AM, 105.7 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
