<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIDE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By any name, Saturday slate will be critical
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You can call it ``Showdown Saturday'' or you can call
it ``Shakedown Saturday.'' No matter what you call it, if you're a
college football fan, you better watch at least one of these games
during the coming weekend. After this Saturday, the national
championship race will begin to take shape:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tennessee (4-0) at Georgia (4-0): The winner has the inside
track to the SEC East championship and will be the league's best
hope of placing a team in the Fiesta Bowl. The last time the
Bulldogs beat the Vols (1988), Vince Dooley was beginning his last
season as coach. ESPN's Game Day is coming to the biggest home game
in Athens since Tennessee-Georgia in '92.
</P>
<P>
   -- LSU (3-1) at Florida (4-1): LSU is still licking its wounds
after Saturday night's 28-27 loss to Georgia and can't be looking
forward to going to The Swamp, where the Tigers were pummeled 56-10
two seasons ago. ``We can mope the rest of the season or we can try
to come back,'' said coach Gerry DiNardo. Florida was lucky to
escape with a 16-10 win at Alabama and coach Steve Spurrier knows
it. This will not be a fun week around Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   -- UCLA (3-0) at Arizona (5-0): Arizona has become the darkhorse
team in the Pac-10 after Saturday night's dramatic 31-28 win over
Washington. UCLA has better talent, but could struggle at Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nebraska (5-0) at Texas A&AMP;M (4-1): After struggling to beat
Oklahoma State 24-17 Saturday night, the No. 2 Cornhuskers should
bounce back and spank the Aggies, who also looked lackluster in
beating Kansas 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning quarterback
</P>
<P>
   -- Expect Spurrier to decide on a quarterback and stick with him
before Saturday's game with LSU. After scoring only one touchdown
at Alabama Saturday, Spurrier is finally convinced that alternating
Doug Johnson and Jesse Palmer is killing offensive consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of this zig-zagging around,'' said Spurrier. Our
money is on Johnson, who completed 10 of 20 passes for 187 yards.
</P>
<P>
   -- The mood was not much better at Florida State after the
Seminoles needed a school-record five field goals from Sebastian
Janikowski to beat Maryland 24-10. ``It felt worse than a loss,''
said defensive end Tony Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   -- Auburn now has a quarterback controversy. Regardless of how
fast sophomore Ben Leard comes back from an elbow injury suffered
against Tennessee, there will be pressure to play true freshman
Gabe Gross, who came off the bench and did some good things in the
17-9 loss to the Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like Ben has a battle on his hands,'' conceded coach
Terry Bowden. Gross was 7-of-15 for 112 yards. The injury to Leard
was so unexpected that Gross was out on the field not knowing a lot
of the Auburn offense. ``I didn't think he knew what any play
was,'' said Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   -- Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin almost got hit in the head
with a full soft drink bottle after Saturday's game at Auburn.
Someone from the upper deck of Jordan-Hare Stadium dropped the
bottle near Tennessee's postgame interview area behind the stadium.
Later, Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis left the locker room with
a police escort and did not give interviews. He had an ice bag
taped to his right knee but his injury is not believed to be
serious.
</P>
<P>
   -- With 350 yards and five touchdowns in Saturday's 54-33 win
over Iowa State, Ricky Williams of Texas is now fourth on the NCAA
career rushing list with 5,241 yards. He's 841 yards shy of Tony
Dorsett's career record of 6,082. He needs to average 140 yards in
his final six games to reach that mark.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep an eye on Tulane, 4-0 after Saturday's big 21-7 win over
Southern Mississippi. The Green Wave forced six turnovers and won
even though quarterback Shaun King played with a cast on his left
wrist. Also keep an eye on coach Tommy Bowden, who is being
mentioned as a possible candidate at Clemson or South Carolina if
either makes a change.
</P>
<P>
   -- While you were sleeping, Arizona QB Ortege Jenkins made one
of the plays of the year. Jenkins scored on a 9-yard run with four
seconds remaining when he somersaulted over three Washington
defenders into the end zone. The acrobatic play gave the Wildcats a
24-20 win and kept them undefeated going into Saturday's game with
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
