<HEADER>
A0703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-FOLLOWUP12-CO     10-11 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-FOLLOWUP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs' center may be out for Tennessee
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia could be without starting center Miles
Luckie for Saturday's SEC showdown against No. 4 Tennessee in
Sanford Stadium. The Volunteers are waiting to see if All-SEC
tailback Jamal Lewis' right knee is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Luckie, a 6-foot-1, 285-pound junior from Clarkston, left
Saturday night's 28-27 win over LSU with a bruised right knee.
Luckie left the game in the third quarter and was replaced by
sophomore Jonas Jennings, the starting right guard. Sophomore
Reggie Stargill of LaGrange replaced Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Luckie) had an MRI (Sunday) and it came back good for us,''
Bulldogs coach Jim Donnan said. ``He has a badly bruised knee.
We're hoping he can play, but we'll have to see. I'd say he's
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the former Douglass High star who ripped the Bulldogs for
232 rushing yards on 22 attempts last year, bruised his right knee
in the Vols' 17-9 win at Auburn. Lewis will undergo an MRI today.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee strong safety Fred White of Griffin injured his left
knee and will undergo an MRI, and reserve defensive end Will
Overstreet is questionable with a thumb injury. The good news for
the Vols: All-SEC linebacker Al Wilson, who missed the Auburn game,
will return to practice today and will play against Georgia.
Offensive tackle Jarvis Reado is doubtful with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings is one of seventh-ranked Georgia's most versatile
players. The offensive line played well against the Tigers, who
sacked quarterback Quincy Carter three times.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's ability to avoid would-be tacklers was a big factor. He
rushed for 72 yards on 14 carries, but finished with 41 yards after
the sacks. Carter was more impressive throwing the ball, completing
27 of 34 attempts for 318 yards and two touchdowns in only his
fourth career start.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the greatest games by a quarterback in any
game, in my opinion,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   UP NEXT FOR GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Opponent: Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   When: Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Sanford Stadium, Athens.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: CBS; WSB (98.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
