 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, Oct. 12. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ News Analysis: Examining the
Clinton administration's foreign policy, and reflecting on the
failure to push the Caspian initiative or forge ahead on the Middle
East peace talks. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENICIAN-SHIPS (Undated) _ The Phoenicians were the master
seafarers of antiquity, but modern scholarship knows little of the
vanished people and almost nothing of their empire's basis, its
merchant ships. Now, however, the cold depths of the Mediterranean
have yielded a bonanza that might change all that _ if
archeologists and treasure hunters can learn to work together. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Three weeks before the election,
Democrats have decided that the best place to campaign is from the
Capitol. Adopting their own version of the ``Rose Garden
Strategy,'' they are romping around marble hallways demanding that
their Republican counterparts do something _ other than talk about
impeachment, that is. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-DATA-BASE (Undated) _ A national DNA data base will be
opened on Tuesday by the FBI. It is the hope of advocates of an
increasing array of DNA techniques that they will significantly
reduce rape and other crimes by catching repeat offenders earlier.
This new generation of forensic DNA techniques promises to be so
efficient that some civil libertarians fear the data bases will be
expanded to include almost everyone, giving the state inordinate
powers over its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-AIDS (Lowry City, Mo.) _ Rural America is becoming a new
frontier for AIDS, as the experience of patients and people trying
to help them is aggravated by social taboos, remote locations,
poverty and lack of education. And, as the HIV virus becomes more
common in women nationally, health experts are especially worried
about rural women because they are often more isolated, less
independent and less assertive. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SCHOOLS (Houston) _ A coalition of Christian
conservatives, favoring home-schooling, vouchers, the mandated
teaching of creationism, heavy editing of textbooks and a breaking
down of the wall between church and state, at least as far as
public schools are involved, now control five seats on the Texas
state school board. Because of a fluke, they are guaranteed a sixth
after the election in November. This means that they only need to
win one more to have control of the state board, and they have two
or three opportunities to get it. Many political professionals
believe this, not the Bush race for governor, which is a foregone
conclusion, is the most significant election in Texas this fall. By
Rick Lyman.
</P>
