<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MARY CASSATT ART EXHIBIT; A THEATRICAL PUB; JUDY
GARLAND ON CDS; NEW SADLER'S WELLS THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Some 100 paintings, pastels, drawings and prints from
public and private collections worldwide go on display Tuesday at
the Art Institute of Chicago in an exhibition billed as the first
retrospective in 30 years devoted to Mary Cassatt (1845-1926). The
only American and one of three women to exhibit with the
impressionists in Paris, she is perhaps best known for her
paintings of mothers and children.
</P>
<P>
   Organized with the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, where it will
appear from Feb. 14 to May 9, and the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, where it will be seen from June 6 to Sept. 6, ``Mary
Cassatt: Modern Woman'' runs through Jan. 10 in Chicago.
Information: (800) 929-5800.
</P>
<P>
   Lush Life
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Meet Joe's Pub. Joe as in Joseph Papp. Pub as in
Public Theater, where Joe's Pub is situated. This 160-seat space
opens Monday night with a performance by the three-time Tony
award-winner Audra McDonald. The pub serves food and drink from 5
p.m. daily. This month and next, various talents are scheduled at
8:30 on Monday, Friday and Saturday nights. Dinner and drinks will
be available later. Information: (212) 539-8777.
</P>
<P>
   Judy, Judy
</P>
<P>
   She's back. She, of course, is Judy Garland, and the medium of
her return is ``Judy,'' a boxed set of four CDs, a book and a video
trumpeted as the most comprehensive career overview of the
entertainment icon.
</P>
<P>
   With the 30th anniversary of Garland's death looming next year,
when ``The Wizard of Oz'' is scheduled for its 60th-anniversary
rerelease, this anthology follows the star from age 7 as one of the
Gumm Sisters to her end 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Besides evergreens like ``Over the Rainbow,'' the set includes
rare and unreleased recordings, concert performances and duets,
plus a 100-page book and a half-hour video of highlights from ``The
Judy Garland Show,'' on CBS in 1963 and 1964. ``Judy'' will be
released Tuesday by 32 Records.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chapter
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ On the site where Richard Sadler opened his Musick
House in 1683 and the waters of his wells were soon prescribed by
London doctors as a cure for dropsy, jaundice, greensickness,
ulcers and distemper, a new theater opens Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth to rise on the Islington property that was the
birthplace of the former Sadler's Wells Ballet, the Royal Ballet
and the English National Opera, the new Sadler's Wells Theater is
an $81 million state-of-the-art complex intended primarily for
dance. Besides the 1,600-seat main theater, a smaller house is to
open next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night the Rambert Dance Company offers the world
premiere of ``Four Scenes,'' commissioned by Sadler's Wells and
choreographed by Christopher Bruce, the Rambert's artistic
director. Information: 011-44-171-863-8000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
