<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGLY-NEW-$20-BILL-2TA     10-11 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGLY-NEW-$20-BILL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW $20 BILL SAYS MORE THAN ITS WEIGHT IN GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't really have anything against new money. I haven't been
around enough old money to get snotty about its patina of
tradition, its noble character and its good breeding.
</P>
<P>
   But now things have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not talking about the nouveau riche. I'm talking about
the new $20 bill beginning to creep into our pockets. The recently
redesigned $50 and $100 notes haven't mattered much; for me, they
have remained pretty much out of familiar reach. But soon these
crude, brash and ill-proportioned $20s will be everywhere. And
their ruder, cheaper cousins are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Why am I making so much fuss? Look at the elegant endowments
possessed by old money. At the back of the old $20 is the
graciously curved South Portico of the White House, with the
building set back, allowing space for the lawn, surrounding trees
and hints of textured sky.
</P>
<P>
   The image is not sharply bounded but fades gracefully away. And
surrounding it is a frame that resembles an elaborate proscenium
from a century-old theater, ornamented with banners, rosettes and
elements derived from classical columns. Even the identifying
numbers are elegant: two enclosed in octagons, two in ovals.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at the new bill. The South Portico's curves are
exchanged for a head-on, close-up of the Grecian north entrance. No
lawn is visible, only shrubs. The leaves are detailed, but the sky
is artificial, without texture. The image does not wash into the
bill's background; instead, it is briskly cropped and bounded by a
draftsman's oval. And around that oval are disorienting expanses of
vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the once ornate frame has shrunk into a thin molding.
Two of the identifying 20s hang down as if by accident. A third
pushes up from below, while in the right corner another 20,
grotesquely large with a typeface new to American money, bursts
through the frame and bubbles into the bill's empty space.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if the new design were pieced together from spare
parts, and there weren't quite enough to go around. The almost
belle epoque reverence of the old, with its sense of looking
through some nobly decorated portal at a building of charm and
authority, is replaced by the cavalier recklessness and rudeness of
the nouveau riche.
</P>
<P>
   And I haven't even mentioned the face of the bill, where the
formal grace of the top and bottom borders is undercut by the
blown-up medallion of Andrew Jackson with its matinee-idol
slickness.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait is off-center, even breaking apart the once subtle
identifying label: The word ``Federal'' is pushed to one side,
leaving ``Reserve Note'' to fend for itself. This bill looks like
money that doesn't care too much about looking like money. It looks
like play money.
</P>
<P>
   All right, maybe I'm making too much of this. After all, until
we use it, paper money is play money. This is its genius: Instead
of actually using valuables to exchange for other valuables _
nuggets of silver or gold, bags of barley or precious-metal coins
stamped with their weight _ something absolutely worthless is used,
worthless and by its very nature transitory, subject to rips, wear
and decay.
</P>
<P>
   But a delicate drama takes place within these slips of paper.
Their fragility is almost part of the point. The authority that
distributes them is so powerful that it can confer the greatest
value on what is most valueless. The bill also relies on a social
contract between its users, who agree to accept that governing
authority and trust that others will as well.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, as economists have long noted, paper money is so
vulnerable; it relies on intangibles like trust, faith and power.
Alexander Hamilton objected to the stuff. ``In times of
tranquillity it might have no ill consequence,'' he wrote about
paper money. ``But in great and trying emergencies, there is almost
moral certainty of its being mischievous.''
</P>
<P>
   The mischief, of course, is that more can be printed at will,
offering a fraudulent promise of value. And if the authority behind
the paper weakens, or has no influence with a neighboring
authority, the bills become useless scrip.
</P>
<P>
   In 1860, for example, there were more than 1,600 private
American banks offering their own paper money in 10,000 basic note
types. One estimate is that 5,000 counterfeit types were also
circulating. The evolution of the Federal Reserve System and the
centralized American monetary system was not merely an economic
reform but a social transformation.
</P>
<P>
   So the design of bills is not a casual matter. Large forces are
being invoked. The inscriptions are almost magical: When they
appear in precisely the right way, they accomplish an alchemist's
dream, as if turning lead into gold. And called into play are all
the weighty icons of the social covenant and its governing
authority, which are _ to alleviate Hamilton's anxieties _
portrayed as eternal, immutable, even divine.
</P>
<P>
   Mythic or ancient images proliferate on almost every nation's
currency (look at the Latin inscriptions and the hovering eye over
the pyramid on our $1 bill). So do the iconic portraits and
buildings of a country's earthly presence.
</P>
<P>
   But the new $20 bill seems indifferent to all this. The guiding
strategy, according to the Treasury Department, was to further foil
counterfeiters with watermark images, color-shifting ink and a
labeled security thread. But that seems to have been the only
concern; elsewhere all density of detail and intricacy of
connection are tossed aside.
</P>
<P>
   As in so many new American stamps, almost every design element
has been dumbed down, turned almost cartoonish, even condescending.
The Treasury even boasts of the ``easy to read'' numeral slapped on
the back. Why not just print the number over the entire surface of
the bill if that's the point? The 20s on the back of the old bill
were actually easier to read, because the eye was drawn to them:
They formed the stable corners of the note's architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while it may seem as if the national icons are given
more importance _ in Jackson's enlarged portrait or the zoomed-in
view of the White House _ this assertiveness could be a sign of
inflation. The bill's stilted decorations, blank spaces and mixed
typefaces actually weaken the icons, which seem to have no secure
place in the overall fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The White House in particular seems like part of an out-of-place
curio hanging on a blank wall. And isn't all this an unsettling
allusion to the nature of contemporary public life?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the new design, with its almost casual disregard for the
dense meanings of paper money, may also be unwittingly revealing
another imminent transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the currency now being designed across the ocean: the
euro. That currency won't rely on the authority of individual
countries, because its guarantor will not be a country at all, but
an economic association. Its bills will be adorned not with
national capitols but with nonexistent buildings meant to broadly
symbolize the evolution of architecture in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The euro will start being used for electronic transfer of funds
on Jan. 1, three years before bills are even available.
</P>
<P>
   What a peculiar situation: The euro will begin as abstract money
and then take form in bills decorated with the abstract
architecture of a newly imagined realm. And instead of being
created by a government, the euro is creating a government. It is
as if money had been freed of all material constraints, attaining
untested powers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the new American bills also bear hints of this. We can
barely associate money with national boundaries anymore (60 percent
of American currency is probably circulating in foreign countries),
so why worry about national icons and their meanings?
</P>
<P>
   As for design, why be concerned when currency is becoming
increasingly abstract, dissolving into a digital stream of ones and
zeroes, making encryption more important than inscription? Paper
money, with all its mythic invocations and heroic portraits, may
become superfluous. The real new money may be personalized versions
of the EZ-Pass used by drivers in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   There goes the neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
