<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      10-11 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING LIGHT ON TUMORS 
MEMORABILIA BY THE PIECE 
BACKPACK ON WHEELS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Pa.)   (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    During Victorian times, physicians tried to detect breast tumors
by illuminating the breast with candlelight. The candlelight
technique turned out to be less than successful. But now, more than
a century later, researchers are turning to light once again _ this
time in the form of sophisticated lasers _ as they search for more
precise, less potentially hazardous alternatives to X-ray
mammography.
 &HT;    Robert Alfano, a laser physicist at City University of New York
and a pioneer in this area, recently received a patent for optical
imaging of breast tissue.
 &HT;    Normally, trying to find a tumor by shining a light into breast
tissue is as futile as trying to find a largemouth bass by aiming a
flashlight into murky water. This is because the light immediately
scatters when it hits such a dense medium.
 &HT;    Alfano and his colleagues have discovered a way to use laser
light to get sharp images of, for example, a tumor lodged in a
breast: by capturing the light particles after they pass through a
given object during the first 100 picoseconds, or 100-trillionths
of a second, of a laser pulse.
 &HT;    These early light particles _ unlike the far more abundant
``diffuse'' photons that arrive 100 picoseconds later _ are known
as ``ballistic'' photons and ``snake'' photons. The ballistic
photons fire straight through the object; the snake photons swish
through, taking a more snake-like path. Both yield important
information about what might lie inside an object.
 &HT;    ``The idea of this is to replace X-ray mammography, which
doesn't tell you the state of the tumor _ whether the tumor is
cancerous or not _ and it also often doesn't pick up small
tumors,'' Alfano said.
 &HT;    Ultimately, Alfano hopes that optical breast imaging will enable
physicians to determine whether a tumor is malignant as the image
is made, without having to perform a biopsy, simply by separating
out different colors of light.
 &HT;    For now, however, he cautions that his research is quite
preliminary. ``We have not done this on a real breast at this
point,'' he said.
 &HT;    Alfano and colleagues Ping-Pei Ho, Leming Wang, Xiangchun Liang
and Pierre Galland received patent 5,799,656.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Budget-busting price tags put most Mark McGwire memorabilia
beyond the reach of the average fan: $5,000 for an old uniform,
$1,000 for a pair of used shoes and an untold fortune for one of
this season's record-breaking homer balls.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Gluck, of Irvine, Calif., has patented what he says is a
way to make such memorabilia more democratically available: by
chopping it up into little bits and attaching it to trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball card companies already have begun doing this.
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck Co. of Carlsbad, Calif., recently chopped up into 200
pieces an old bat belonging to Babe Ruth, which the company had
purchased for $23,000. The cards featuring slivers of Babe Ruth's
bat have been randomly inserted into the company's 1998 UD Retro
Baseball series, which is being distributed this month.
</P>
<P>
   Gluck, who is one of the founders of Upper Deck but no longer
affiliated with the company, said he was currently in licensing
negotiations for his patent.
</P>
<P>
   Gluck dismisses critics who have charged that his idea
encourages the desecration of rare sports artifacts. ``This gives
the average kid an opportunity to have a piece of history,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Can we expect to find miniature Mark McGwire bats in trading
cards any time soon? Gluck said he hoped so, given that he and
McGwire share the same agent, Robert Cohen, of Los Angeles. ``I
haven't approached Mark McGwire,'' he said. ``But I was tickled
pink Bob Cohen took me on.''
</P>
<P>
   He received patent 5,803,501.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Every morning from the porch of her house in Ardmore, Pa.,
Virginia McDermott watches the neighborhood children struggle with
their heavy backpacks as they rush to catch the school bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking, some day they are going have back troubles,''
she said. And Ms. McDermott knows back troubles. ``Bad backs run in
my family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. McDermott has patented a backpack with wheels. It looks
pretty much like a normal backpack, except for a handle and wheels,
which allow it to be dragged along the ground, much like those
rolling suitcases so common in airports these days.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDermott, who received patent 5,743,447, hopes to license
it.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
