<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WITH TIME RUNNING OUT
</P>
<P>
   A long-sought compromise to let high-technology companies hire
more foreign workers has been derailed in the Senate, and
infighting in the final hours of the 105th Congress is threatening
final passage of two other cornerstones of the
information-technology industry's legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Still in limbo as Congress approaches adjournment at midnight
Monday is a ban on Internet taxes and landmark legislation to
protect copyrights in the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   ODD CO-DEFENDANTS IN CNN CASE
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from CNN's discredited Tailwind broadcast continues
to accumulate. One defamation suit has been settled, three are
pending and at least one more has been threatened. One of the suits
names April Oliver, the lead producer on the report, as an
individual defendant. Trouble is, Ms. Oliver and Time Warner, CNN's
corporate parent, are co-defendants without much of a common cause.
Ms. Oliver, who was dismissed by CNN, is looking for vindication
and has hired her own lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL ROLLOUT OF DIVX UNDER WAY
</P>
<P>
   Despite test-marketing in two cities that did not appear to be a
runaway success, the national rollout is under way for Divx, a
disk-based recorded movie format intended to compete with rental
videocassettes and the emerging DVD digital disk format.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BRITISH INVASION TAKES HOLD
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times, the British financial paper, is thus far
pleased with its year-old effort to expand its circulation beyond
New York and Washington in North America. But measured against The
Wall Street Journal's circulation, The Financial Times is still an
upstart.
</P>
<P>
   NEW HEAD OF CREDIT SUISSE UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston, the investment banking arm of Credit
Suisse Group, said it had hired John Nelson, vice chairman of
Lazard Brothers, to become chairman of Credit Swiss First Boston
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   FROM CARPING TO SHARKING
</P>
<P>
   Michael Naumann, the former chief executive of the publishing
house Henry Holt &AMP; Co. and the new culture minister of Germany, has
brought his penchant for outspokenness from the rarefied world of
New York publishing to the rough and tumble world of politics. ``I
always thought that publishing, in a way, is full of sharks,'' he
said at the Frankfurt Book Fair. ``I now know we are all carps _
carps compared to the sharks of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMBERSHIP SURPRISE AT CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the annual conference of the Association of
National Advertisers were startled by the unexpected announcement
that the group will open its membership to regional and national
agencies that create all types of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-BENZ REJECTS BID FOR UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Daimler-Benz, Germany's largest company, has rejected a $1.22
billion takeover bid for its telecommunications service provider,
Debitel, from the much smaller Mobilcom, saying the unit is not for
sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
