<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THOSE WITH TOO MUCH ON THEIR PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose a waiter walked up to your table, delivered a curt nod,
removed the plates and saucers, then proceeded to dump a pan of hot
porridge on your tablecloth.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is you would probably send your compliments to the
chef and leave the waiter a big tip. After all, you ordered the
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe you didn't, because culinary trends move slowly from
New York to Newhalem.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports received in the Intermediate Eater's
dispatch center (known as Indigestion Central), they are serving
the aforementioned mess at Le Cirque 2000 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not porridge,but the Italian mush known as
polenta.
</P>
<P>
   At Le Cirque, they haul the pot out and splash about two quarts
onto the tablecloth. The waiter then scatters a few beans and hunks
of sausage over the steaming polenta and equips everybody at the
table with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the olden days, kings and barons demanded new gustatory
thrills each night from their castle kitchens. It got to the point
where harried chefs would stuff a canary inside a dove and stuff
the dove inside a duck and stuff the duck inside a giant goose,
then bake the whole thing for three hours only to discover that the
king had to fight a war and was grabbing a burrito at Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago Manhattan chefs exhausted their recipes for
stuff-stuffs and in desperation began to move in the other
direction on the culinary ladder. Apparently, at Le Cirque they
have reached the level of ``authentic'' Italian peasant food. In
another year they'll be charging $35.95 for an order of chicken
feet and collard greens. And they'll probably dump it in your lap.
</P>
<P>
   For a child growing up in Montana, ``peasant food'' translated
into tuna casseroles or macaroni and cheese. Will these items soon
appear on the menu at Le Cirque 2000?
</P>
<P>
   If so, I might get in line, because I really like tuna
casseroles and macaroni with cheese. Particularly if they are
prepared like this:
</P>
<P>
   Tuna Tres Chic
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces noodles
</P>
<P>
   2 9-ounce cans solid-pack tuna
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound sliced fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 red or green pepper, seeded and cubed
</P>
<P>
   2 10-ounce packages French-style frozen green beans
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sliced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken bouillon cube
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dill weed
</P>
<P>
   2 cups skim milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons Wondra flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup reduced-fat Velveeta
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup light mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Thaw the green beans, then plunk them into a large casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the noodles in a large kettle of salted water. You might
add a bit of oil to the pot so the noodles won't stick together.
Drain, then dump them into the casserole with the beans. (If the
noodles stuck together, go back two spaces. Do not pass Go. Do not
collect $200.)
</P>
<P>
   While the noodles are cooking, heat the oil in a large skillet
and add the onion, mushrooms, celery and sweet pepper. When the
onion is soft, dump all the veggies into the casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the milk into the same skillet, drop in the bouillon cube
and stir in the Wondra flour. Heat, stirring, until the milk
thickens, then stir in the Velveeta, cubed. When it has melted,
pour this sludge into the casserole, too. Add the dill weed and
mayonnaise, then moosh everything around. Gently stir in the tuna.
</P>
<P>
   If you want, you can sprinkle the top of the casserole with some
dry bread crumbs. If you have some leftover olives in the fridge,
plunk them into the top. If you use the olives to create a happy
face on top of the casserole, don't tell your guests you got this
recipe from me.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the casserole into a 350-degree oven for 30 minutes and
this should serve six.
</P>
<P>
   Macaroni for Millionaires
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces dried macaroni
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup green pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups medium cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Cajun seasoning
</P>
<P>
   5 Ritz crackers
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cubed ham (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is called Macaroni for Millionaires because I
specified that the crackers must be Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   These days I use low-fat mayonnaise and cheese but _ as with the
tuna casserole _ the end result is about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the macaroni in boiling, salted water until done. Drain,
pour warm water over the top, drain again then dump into a
casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Add the undiluted soup, the mayo, green pepper, onion and
cheese. Sprinkle heavily with Cajun seasoning or lightly with
cayenne pepper. Moosh everything around.
</P>
<P>
   Crumble the crackers in your fist and scatter over the top of
the casserole. Dot with butter or whatever, then shove into a
375-degree oven for 30 minutes. This will serve four.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am technically no longer a peasant, I usually sneak some
cubes of ham into this casserole before mooshing and heating.
</P>
<P>
   I also serve it on a plate.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
