<HEADLINE>
A MOVING SATURDAY IN COLLEGE FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving day in pro golf is Saturday, the day after the cut when
the players try to make their move on the leader board. Saturday
was moving day in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Moving up: UCLA, Tennessee, Kansas State. Moving down: Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers, after their shocking 28-21 loss at Texas A&AMP;M,
fell from No. 2 to No. 8 in both the Associated Press (media) poll
and the ESPN/''USA Today'' (coaches) polls.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska's loss means that Kansas State, which moved from No. 5
to No. 4, is the Big 12 Conference's best hope for a national
championship. The Wildcats won their first game against a ranked
team this season, struggling to win at Colorado, 16-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our team is very pleased with the way we won
this ballgame,'' Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said. ``If there
really is such a thing as an ugly win, then you've witnessed one.
You're not going to hear a joyous locker room, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State's next major test comes in a month when the
Wildcats play host to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and Tennessee won difficult conference road games even
though both teams were without their starting tailbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who moved up to No. 2 behind top-ranked Ohio State,
used a 28-point second blitz to beat Arizona, 52-28. UCLA was
playing without tailback Jermaine Lewis, who was suspended last
week.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA quarterback Cade McNown said the Bruins are more concerned
about Saturday's game against No. 11 Oregon than it is about its
No. 2 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season is said and done and we're there at the top,
that's good. But right now we've only played four games,'' McNown
said. ``We've still got a lot of work to do, and we're not
convinced of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers moved up to No. 3 off their 22-3 victory at
Georgia. Tennessee won without sophomore tailback Jamal Lewis, who
is out for the season with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Al Wilson returned to the lineup to boost a Tennessee
defense that has been stingy this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an emotional lift getting Al Wilson back, but we also
knew a lot of guys had to step up with Jamal Lewis out,'' Tennessee
coach Phillip Fulmer said.
Looking ahead
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Worth Star-Telegram'' college football writer Wendell
Barnhouse takes a look at this week's top games:
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Oregon at No. 2 UCLA: The Ducks are averaging 50.5 points
per game; the Bruins are averaging 48 points. First team to 50
wins.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Virginia at No. 25 Georgia Tech: A showdown in the
Atlantic Coast Conference. The Cavalivers' defense must slow a
Georgia Tech offense that has scored 40 points in four consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   No. 22 Texas Tech at No. 19 Colorado: The Red Raiders get
another chance to prove they're for real. The Buffaloes must show
that their 5-0 start wasn't a fluke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
