r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     10-11 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEEP YOUR CHILDREN SAFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a preface to the anti-drug pamphlet ``How Parents Can Help
Children Live Marijuana Free,'' Senator  &UR; Orrin Hatch &LR; , R-Utah,
writes that our ``morally deprived society ... has chosen to
embrace, rather than attack, this plague'' of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The pamphlet -- written by University of Utah criminologist
 &UR; Gerald Smith &LR; , cited in the Washington Post and harvested for
Personals by  &UR; Carol Mitchell &LR;  -- goes on to list warning signs for
parents of children who may be using marijuana: A teenager who
``avoids the family while at home'' may be a kid at risk; watch
out, too, for ``interest in Ras Tafari religion''; most insidious
of all is ``excessive preoccupation with social causes, race
relations, environmental issues, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING AND SPENDING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Observer says that playwright  &UR; David Mamet &LR;  is
producing a line of outerwear that will be sold at Banana Republic
under the label ``Joseph Morse Company'' but couldn't quite get him
to confirm. Mamet's only comment: ``All the proceeds go to  &UR; Paul
Newman &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Angela Weber &LR;  forwards an item from Vroom, the Official
Catalog of Rock and Roll: ``Some people make toilet seats and some
make guitars.  &UR; Marvin Maxwell &LR;  and a few of his friends are the
only ones I know who do both.''
</P>
<P>
   The product is a $149 toilet seat with a lid shaped like a
guitar, and it's owned by the likes of  &UR; Willie Nelson &LR; ,  &UR; Merle &LR; 
 &UR; Haggard  &LR; and  &UR; Howard Stern &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Personals launches the 1998 Holiday Catalog
Quest. Volunteers are asked to send clippings of the most
surprising catalog treasures they find this season. Vote early.
</P>
<P>
   (Meanwhile, the C.F. Martin Co. is selling a limited edition
``Nelson Trigger,'' a copy of a guitar Willie Nelson bought in 1969
and named after  &UR; Roy Rogers &LR; ' horse.)
</P>
<P>
   - Don's Pampered Pet in Millbrae, Ca., is selling D-Dog
Aerobics, a $75 swing-away apparatus attached to a treadmill that
turns it into an automatic walker for an unsuspecting harnessed
dog. ``The dog can walk for miles while its owners relax, make
dinner, watch TV,'' according to promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   - The ``Dog Tag Silencer'' is a gummy rectangle the size of a
dog tag, intended for affixing to the back of the tag to
``eliminate clanking'' against another. No price is available on
this useful item, because the only evidence that it exists is one
found by a reader on a BART platform.
</P>
<P>
   - Wild Eyes, contact lenses newly available at a number of local
opticians, turn one's eyeballs into works of art. The options:
Cateye, Redeye, Hypnotica, Wildfire, White-out, Pool Shark,
Starry-eyed and Zoomin'.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH  &LR;   &UR; - Heidi Lang &LR;  was saddened by a poignant obituary in
last week's San Rafael/Terra Linda News Pointer: The deceased, a
much-admired, civic-minded woman, met her husband ``at a Pt. Reyes
Nature Seminar,'' said the newspaper, ``and they shared a love of
pornography and the outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Johnny Carson &LR; ,  &UR; James Caan &LR; ,  &UR; Gary Coleman &LR; ,  &UR; James Belushi &LR; 
and  &UR; Steven Bochco &LR;  have licenses to carry loaded handguns, says
the latest issue of People magazine. Many celebrity gun-toters
receive their licenses in Culver City, where the Police Department
issued 320 permits in 1997. Los Angeles, which has a population 89
times that of Culver City, issued 158 permits over four years.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Those Navy men sure are cruising Polk Street,'' a man who
emerged from a bar to see the Blue Angels whiz by twice told
 &UR; Robert Cromey &LR; . Meanwhile, when a diamond-shaped formation flew
directly westward over Haight Street toward Golden Gate Park on
Saturday, one jet, out of formation and way off to the left, looked
downright symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;   &UR; ``Charlotte, 32 and a 36B, lives in New &LR; 
 &UR; York City, but sometimes &LR; 
 &UR; works in Los Angeles in film and television, and is always &LR; 
 &UR; struck by the difference between L.A. and New York breasts.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR;  From the new book, ``Breasts'' by  &UR; Meema Spadola &LR;  (Wildcat
Canyon; $13.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
