<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      10-11 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ For the first time this season, the Dallas Cowboys have
clamped two wins together. But they almost let the second one slip
away Sunday afternoon at Texas Stadium. The Carolina Panthers were
in death throes, and the Cowboys had trouble finishing them off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They did it in the nick of time. Prime Time, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas offense was almost flawless. Jason Garrett continued
to improve as understudy to injured quarterback Troy Aikman. And
the rejuvenated offensive line gave Garrett eons to throw and
gouged out canyons for Emmitt Smith to explore.
</P>
<P>
   But then there was the Dallas defense. The Cowboys held Carolina
to 29 yards rushing, but except for Deion Sanders, they couldn't
defend the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's Steve Beuerlein made his first start of the season
and couldn't have done better throwing in his back yard. He
completed 18 of his first 19 attempts. Not until Sanders
intercepted him with two minutes left in the game were the Cowboys
assured of their 27-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion knows the distance he can be from a player and still
make a play,'' Carolina coach Dom Capers observed, noting how the
Neon One lured Beuerlein into a fatal trap.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, pro football's most versatile performer, also was a key
to his team's go-ahead touchdown in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the Panthers' six-yard line, the Cowboys deployed Sanders as
a flanker. They sent him in motion, drawing defenders with him and
creating a gap in the middle. Garrett then shuffled a pass to
running back Chris Warren, who had an easy path to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense was supposed to key on me,'' Sanders said, ``and
it worked out great.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been times this season when Sanders was about the
only weapon the Cowboys had. But Sunday, there were others. Garrett
completed 14 of 22 passes for 287 yards and two touchdowns. Michael
Irvin caught six passes for 146 yards, and Ernie Mills five for
110.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Smith had his second consecutive 100-yard rushing
day, with 21 carries for 112 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Emmitt ran the ball as well as we've ever seen him
run,'' said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Cowboys were happy to jump off the roller coaster
and raise their record to 4-2, there was little glory in struggling
against an 0-5 team.
</P>
<P>
   Beuerlein played only because Kerry Collins asked to be benched,
and Dallas coach Chan Gailey said, ``You would hope he's rusty and
antsy and doesn't see things quickly. But a situation like that can
be a rallying point.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it was. Beuerlein completed his first 12 passes
before he missed under pressure from blitzing linebacker Fred
Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina forged a 14-3 lead with touchdown passes of 35 and 16
yards from Beuerlein to Rocket Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys came back with an acrobatic catch by Mills in the
end zone. He leaned backward to pull down an 18-yard fade from
Garrett, who makes up with touch what he lacks in arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   With two minutes remaining in the first half, the Panthers faked
a punt. Ken Walter made the first down across midfield, but the
play was nullified by an illegal-formation penalty. The Panthers
were said to have only six players on the line of scrimmage, though
a television replay indicated otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   After exiting the field to booing over their 14-10 halftime
deficit, the Cowboys showed more intensity in the third quarter.
Two minutes into it, Kevin Mathis recovered a fumble by Carolina
running back Anthony Johnson on the Panthers' 19-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the shuffle pass _ and the last shuffling of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran that look last week to Deion,'' Gailey said. ``We
thought if we ran the same look, they may run over to that side of
the field, and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-yard TD run by Smith gave Dallas a 24-14 lead, and a
38-yard field goal by Richie Cunningham stretched it to 27-14 in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of lapses let Carolina back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   First, a Garrett fumble on a quarterback sneak was returned 35
yards by cornerback Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to bleed the clock out and not give the ball
away,'' Garrett said. ``But I dived into the crease, and the ball
just kind of disappeared on me. I don't know if somebody knocked it
away or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Cowboys snafu followed as safety Darren Woodson, beaten
deep, committed a 40-yard interference penalty. That set up a
three-yard touchdown pass from Beuerlein to fullback William Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers would have closed to within six points, but Chad
Hennings blocked John Kasay's conversion try.
</P>
<P>
   ``From watching films, I knew they had a PAT blocked from that
side,'' Hennings said. ``So I thought I had a chance to get
penetration and get my hands up and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys were not out of trouble until the Sanders
interception on the left sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been beating us all day with four receivers going
vertical,'' Sanders said. ``This time, my man broke it off and ran
an out. I was cheating inside, so I could run back to the ball and
make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   With a recent commitment to Christianity and humility, Sanders
has eschewed his Prime Time moniker. But he has lost none of his
flair for the dramatic. Certainly there could not have been a more
opportune moment for Prime Time to reappear for the Cowboys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
