<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENALTIES WILL CATCH UP TO NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Right now the penalties are just hurting
Cal State Northridge. But if those penalties continue, eventually
it will kill the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   So far talent and tenacity has overcome the holds and illegal
formations and late hits and delay of games. But at some point that
will stop and CSUN will be lamenting about a wasted opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth straight week the Matadors won, a 21-7 decision
against No.18 Montana. But for the third straight week No.23 CSUN
reached double digits in penalties. The Matadors were flagged 11
times for 100 yards Saturday, which is also the third time they've
had more penalties than their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like we were trying to lose the dang game for a
while,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said. ``The number of penalties
was so heavy on our side it was just absolutely ridiculous. I don't
understand, and I still cannot accept that foolishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rare is the time when a penalty is a good thing (to prevent a
blindside sack or an easy touchdown reception fit the bill). And
right now the Matadors (4-1) are playing well enough to overcome
the penalties. However, that won't last the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   On each of their scoring drives against Montana, the Matadors
had to go extra yards to make up for miscues.
</P>
<P>
   Before Marcus Brady and Jimmy Greninger got together on a
51-yard touchdown pass on the first possession of the third
quarter, CSUN had a substitution infraction that moved the ball
back 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of a prelude to the doozy that turned into the game-winning
drive.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was an illegal use of the hands called against
CSUN. So on second-and-20 from its own 43, Brady scrambled and then
connected with Aaron Arnold for a 57-yard touchdown strike.
</P>
<P>
   For naught. Holding was called.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Matadors went from second-and-33 to getting the first
down, and eventually the touchdown. But not before the penalties
wiped out huge plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like a dagger. I was heartbroken when that one got
called back,'' Brady said. ``I didn't see it. After I threw it I
was sitting there cheering, jumping up and down, ready to
celebrate. And I saw a yellow flag on the ground, and it just kind
of hurt inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we threw three touchdown passes just to score
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the game-clinching drive, a modest 20-yarder after
Montana was stopped on fourth down, there was a penalty, this time
for delay of game.
</P>
<P>
   And the penalties aren't relegated to the offense. Twice in the
first half the Matadors defense was penalized on key third-down
plays that extended Montana drives. Two other times CSUN defensive
penalties resulted in first downs for the Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for us to continue to improve we have got to stop
doing those stupid penalties,'' Ponciano said. ``I mean, it's on
both sides of the ball, and that is 100 percent unacceptable. But I
tend to forget that we won a football game that was very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano knows a week is coming where CSUN will lose a football
game thanks to penalties. The last three weeks the North Campus
Stadium field was littered with yellow hankies. An average of 10.7
flags for 91.7 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the yellow flags catch up to a team. Eventually,
those flags will shatter a team's hopes for a Big Sky championship
or playoff bid.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, CSUN will lose if the penalties continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
