<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANITY FAIR WON'T RUN STORY ON REPRESENTATIVE  
 WHEN AN EDITOR TAKES A POLITICAL STANCE  
 THREE PRODUCERS SEE POTENTIAL IN HOLLYWOOD TALE  
 DEFENDANT IN CNN SUIT HIRES HER OWN LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana, the Republican chairman of the
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, found out that Vanity
Fair magazine was planning to run a story revealing that he was the
father of an illegitimate child, he decided to beat the magazine to
the punch. On Aug. 31, he announced at news conferences in Indiana
that Vanity Fair would soon be producing a ``scandal story'' about
his sexual life.
</P>
<P>
   But Vanity Fair, having arguably generated more buzz than any
other magazine in history for an article that had not yet been
published, is no longer planning to publish the article, which was
to be written by the freelance writer Russ Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Baker will be paid his entire fee for the article, which is
Vanity Fair's general practice when stories do not run. Staffers at
Vanity Fair, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said that the
Vanity Fair editor Graydon Carter wanted Baker to change the
emphasis and spend less space exploring the personal history of
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The senior articles editor Doug Stumpf, who assigned the piece
to Baker, did say, ``We hadn't yet scheduled the piece and since
Russ felt strongly that it be published before the election in
November, we told him he was free to take it elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker asked Charles Lane, the editor of The New Republic, to
look at his 6,000-word manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shopped it to us,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   But before Baker sent him the manuscript, Baker took it to Mike
Wallace's producing team at ``60 Minutes.'' Baker and Jonathan
Wells, a member of Wallace's team, confirmed that they were indeed
working together.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   When an Editor Takes a Political Stance
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Thursday, The New York Post pointed out with no
small measure of delight that Harold Evans _ editorial director and
vice chairman of The Daily News of New York, U.S. News &AMP; World
Report, The Atlantic Monthly and Fast Co., a business magazine _
had added his name to a full-page advertisement in The New York
Times, calling for censure, not impeachment, of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which was paid for by a group called the Committee for
Censure, Not Impeachment, included Evans' name on a list of 84
luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Should an editor with responsibility over news pages be taking a
public position? Joan Konner, publisher of the Columbia Journalism
Review and dean emerita of the Columbia University School of
Journalism, said, ``Ordinarily, a journalist should not be on that
document.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Traditional journalistic ethics say that you are an
outsider on every journalistic controversy. If you are reporting on
the story, you must be an outsider.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans responded by saying that he was ``massively unperturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we supposed to do?'' he asked. ``Skulk in our tents?
An ethical problem would have been for an editor or editorial
director to persuade a journalist working for him to write
something he didn't believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he did not think that any reporter or columnist
reporting to him would be troubled by Evans' belief that the
president should not be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the journalists at the Daily News and U.S News are
made of sterner stuff than the hand-wringers outside who have not
had a professional job in 100 years,'' he said. ``Ask anybody in
the Daily News if they are intimidated by my signature, and you
will find they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Three Producers See Potential in a Hollywood Tale
</P>
<P>
   ``Indecent Exposure,'' David McClintick's 1982 best-selling saga
of greed and glory in Hollywood, may finally make it onto the
screen. The tale, which started with a check forged by David
Begelman, then president of Columbia Pictures, and ended with
Begelman's ouster, was perhaps the first book in which the daily
history of a business crisis was recreated by an author.
</P>
<P>
   Noted books of this genre that followed included ``Barbarians at
the Gate,'' which recounted the takeover battle for R.J. Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   During the Columbia battle, Begelman was defended by Ray Stark,
the powerful producer, and Herbert Allen, the head of Allen &AMP; Co.,
an investment banking firm with a stake in Columbia. His critics
included Columbia's chief executive, Alan Hirschfield, and the
actor Cliff Robertson, whose name Begelman had forged on the check.
</P>
<P>
   Now Edward Pressman and Ken Lipper have bought an interest in
the rights to the book from the producer Elliott Kastner as well as
the rights to McClintick's 1996 article in Vanity Fair in which he
described Begelman's difficult final years and eventual suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The three men are negotiating with Film Four, the film division
of Channel Four of Britain, to finance the production. That company
has financed about 18 films a year, including ``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kastner said this might be a good time to produce ``Indecent
Exposure'' as a movie, because audiences are more sophisticated
about boardroom issues. Pressman describes the project as ```The
Godfather' of the movie business'' because it involves so many
highly placed film executives in such a visible fight.
</P>
<P>
   _ GERALDINE FABRIKANT
</P>
<P>
   Defendant in CNN Suit Hires Her Own Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Talk about strange bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from CNN's discredited Tailwind broadcast continues
to accumulate. One defamation suit has been settled, three are
pending and at least one more has been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting suit was filed in Washington by Maj.
Gen. John Singlaub of the Army, who commanded the Studies and
Observations Group special forces units in Vietnam. It is the only
suit that names April Oliver, the lead producer on the report, as
an individual defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Ms. Oliver and Time Warner, CNN's corporate parent,
are co-defendants without much of a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliver is looking for vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's goal is less clear, though it would be logical to
assume it has a strategic retreat in mind, since during the summer
it decided to settle a defamation suit brought by Adm. Thomas
Moorer for a sum that one CNN executive, who declined to be
identified, estimated to be ``around $200,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for support, Ms. Oliver has retained Martin Garbus, an
aggressive lawyer who has worked both for and against Time Warner
in earlier legal battles.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, under its libel insurance policy, must insure Ms.
Oliver, both sides agree. It is less clear whether the policy would
cover a separate lawyer for Ms. Oliver _ even though her claim of
truthfulness is directly at odds with Time Warner's repudiation of
her work.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's spokesman, Steve Haworth, had no comment. But Ms. Oliver
said that Time Warner's lawyers had made it clear that they were
disinclined to allow Garbus in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the other pending lawsuits name Ms. Oliver as an
individual defendant. They include a suit filed in Florida by one
of the soldiers who did reconnaissance on the Tailwind mission and
a California suit filed by veterans of the Special Operations
Group. CNN's report charged that the Special Forces used nerve gas
in a mission targeting deserters.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ms. Oliver is drafting a 2,000-word response to
a round-table discussion about Tailwind published in the magazine
Brill's Content. All the parties involved in the round table shared
the view that the story should not have been broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
</TEXT>
