<HEADLINE>
AFTER LOSS, GALAXY FACING ELIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This Major League Soccer season has become a one-game affair for
the Galaxy, which is one game from elimination after falling
Saturday to the Chicago Fire in the Western Conference finals
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 90 minutes of dominance meant nothing after Chicago's
Jesse Marsch slotted home a rebound of Lubos Kubik's free kick in
the 86th minute to deliver a 1-0 victory and move the Fire to
within one win _ possibly Friday at Soldier Field _ of MLS's
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a critical victory for the Fire players, who used superb
defense to nullify L.A.'s control of the match, but they're well
aware their task won't be easy in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be another hard-fought game,'' Fire coach Bob Bradley
said. ``We saw the kind of character L.A. has when they were down
two goals the last game against Dallas (and rallied in the final
10{ minutes for a 3-2 victory). This is only one game.''
</P>
<P>
   The second game in the best-of-three series could be a replica
of the first, which looked like a chess match: The Galaxy owned
possession of the ball and sought openings into the Fire box.
Chicago built a fort around its goal, waiting to take advantage of
one L.A. mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go to Chicago and find a way to win,'' said Galaxy
defender Robin Fraser. ``If you look at the way Chicago defends,
there's no set way to beat them.... Nothing will be given to us. We
have to go there and gut out a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough game against 11 guys who only defended, and
they had one opportunity and converted,'' said Galaxy coach Octavio
Zambrano, whose team also played superb defense for all but perhaps
three seconds, when defender Steve Jolley failed to stay with
Marsch on Kubik's free kick. ``We are not yet out of the playoffs.
We can't put our heads down, and we are going to go into Chicago
and play hard. Never in my life will I believe, or let the guys
feel, that this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be soon unless L.A. takes care of its chances as Chicago
did. Twice the Galaxy got into the Fire goalmouth _ Welton from a
Carlos Hermosillo throughball in the 56th minute, and Martin Machon
on a bicycle kick during a last-minute scramble _ and neither time
could L.A. put a shot on target. The Fire managed just two shots on
goal: Kubik's free kick, slapped away by goalkeeper Kevin Hartman,
and Marsch's rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be smart (in Chicago),'' Zambrano said. ``We can't
be panicky about the situation. We still have 90 minutes to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
