<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STRUGGLES ON SIDELINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two months ago, if you told a USC coach, player or
fan that the Trojans would be 4-2 today, and they were forced to
give an honest answer, most of those people would probably be
fairly satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   So why are so many feeling numb following Saturday's 32-31 loss
to California?
</P>
<P>
   It's a little more complicated than pinning it all on the
21-point lead that the Trojans blew in the game's final 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is if several subtle but crucial decisions
will be made in time for USC to remain a factor in the Pacific-10
Conference race the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has character. We're not going to allow ourselves to
be down,'' tailback Petros Papadakis said. ``You take the good,
correct the bad and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The good part is that the Trojans play hard and are in excellent
physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The bad part is what seems to be happening on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, USC seems mired in a close-to-the-vest mentality.
Even coach Paul Hackett was second-guessing himself for kicking a
field goal with seven seconds left and the ball inside the Cal
1-yard line at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That's plenty of time for one more pass and then the field goal.
If the Trojans had run and failed to score the touchdown, it's
unlikely too many people would fault them for their courage.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Abrams had certainly never kicked a shorter field goal in
his career, and there's a logical reason why: You go for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one's gonna haunt me,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hackett could have taken as much heat going for the
extra point while trailing Arizona State 24-19. The Sun Devils
committed a penalty and he changed his mind and went for two. But
Hackett said later that he had a ``momentary'' lapse by going for
two points, because the ``chart'' said you go for one point in that
situation, and you don't take points off the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to see what the ``chart'' says about
teams that average 10 penalties a game. Last year, it was
considered one of the reasons John Robinson wasn't getting the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the penalty issue, we've been able to dodge the bullet,''
Hackett said. ``But tonight, we weren't able to dodge the bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   The inordinate amount of penalties the offensive line commits
will probably never improve this season, but USC has not yet
responded to this problem.
</P>
<P>
   As Florida State and even Cal proved, the Trojans can be easily
overwhelmed by a solid pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is no fan of the shotgun, but if the offensive line is
mediocre at best, something has to be done to give the quarterback
_ whoever it is _ more time to throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   This might have also been the first game in which the
two-quarterback system went awry. Mike Van Raaphorst lost his
rhythm and Carson Palmer never had a chance to establish one
against the Bears. No matter who was playing quarterback, he would
have been better served playing the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   And why is there so much confusion halfway through the season
that timeouts are burned and delay- of-game penalties occur in key
moments of the second half?
</P>
<P>
   Whether these issues are corrected should determine which
direction the season takes.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Hackett said Sunday he was hopeful tailback Chad Morton
would return for Saturday's game against Washington State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 2227EDT &QL; 
