<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANTZ' DEFENDS SPOT ATOP BOX OFFICE HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Moviegoers continued marching to the nation's
multiplexes for ``Antz'' as the computer-animated comedy topped the
weekend box office with an estimated $15.4 million at 2,813
theaters during Friday-Sunday, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz,'' the first animated film from DreamWorks SKG, has drawn
$36.3 million in 10 days after setting a record for an October
debut. It should easily top ``Beavis &AMP; Butt-head Do America's'' $63
million record as the top non-Disney animated film by the end of
its run.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressively, the weekend-to-weekend decline of ``Antz''
was a mere 11 percent as the studio added 364 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approval ratings on `Antz' have been over 90 percent, so
it should continue to do well and gross about $75 million,'' said
Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Antz'' will benefit from many children being
out of school today for Columbus Day, which was expected to lead to
heavier-than-usual Sunday moviegoing. ``With a Monday holiday,
Sunday is almost like a Saturday for kids,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks distribution chief James Tharp said ``Antz'' is
drawing from a broad audience. ``We're getting about 50 percent
nonfamily viewers, which is pretty good for an animated film,'' he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Holdover films took the next three slots, led by New Line's
fourth weekend of hit comedy ``Rush Hour'' with $11.2 million at
2,701 theaters to edge PolyGram's second weekend of spiritual drama
``What Dreams May Come,'' with $10.9 million at 2,526 theaters.
``Rush Hour,'' with $98.4 million in 24 days, could take in an
additional $30 million by the end of its run.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's slapstick comedy ``A Night at the Roxbury'' repeated
its fourth-place finish with $6.2 million at 2,169 sites as
moviegoers ignored some of the worst reviews of the year. With
$17.8 million after 10 days, it has already topped its estimated
$17 million production cost.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's only major opening, Eddie Murphy's ``Holy Man,''
debuted in fifth place with a disappointing $5.2 million at 2,013
theaters for Disney. Bucksbaum said the comedy, with Murphy playing
a televangelist turned loose on a shopping channel, suffered from
Murphy's lack of promotional work on the movie, an ineffective
trailer and Disney's apparent focus on coming potential hits _
Oprah Winfrey's ``Beloved'' and its computer-animated ``A Bug's
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum forecast ``Holy Man'' will gross about $25 million
overall, or less than a fifth of Murphy's last entry, ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' which took in $142 million over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lackluster opening for ``Holy Man,'' the weekend
continued the market's strong performance during what is
traditionally a slow period. Weekend overall grosses were in the
$72 million range and up 8 percent over the same weekend last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like people were interested this weekend in seeing
films they missed last weekend,'' Bucksbaum observed.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of thrillers in their third weekends took the next two
spots with Sony's ``Urban Legend'' grossing $4.8 million to edge
MGM's ``Ronin'' with $4.6 million. Finishing a still-strong eighth
was ``There's Something About Mary'' with $3 million at 1,933
theaters to bring the comedy's 89-day total to $162.1 million for
20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary,'' now in its 13th week, has become the 50th-highest
domestic grosser ever after ``Batman Returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were the fourth weekend of Universal's
family drama ``One True Thing'' with $1.9 million at 1,565 theaters
and DreamWorks' 12th weekend of ``Saving Private Ryan'' with $1.4
million at 1,230 screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' has grossed $186.3 million after 80 days
and is now the 28th-highest domestic grosser after ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratosphere's limited opening of police drama ``One Tough Cop''
generated little interest with $578,000 at 417 theaters, while
Miramax's family drama ``The Mighty'' debuted with a respectable
$86,000 at nine sites and will move into wide release later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business is near $5.2 billion and 12 percent ahead
of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz,'' ``What Dreams May Come'' and ``Rush Hour'' will face
competition next weekend from the opening of ``Beloved'' and Warner
Bros.' debut of ``Practical Magic,'' a comic romance starring
Sandra Bullock and Nicole Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
