<HEADLINE>
PLAY THE GAME, FOR PETE'S SAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one seems to know if UCLA athletic
decision-maker
</P>
<P>
   Pete Dalis will order the boys to Miami in early December to
make up that football game, but he's supposed to flip a coin as
soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   As the fans in the Astrodome chanted when the Bad News Bears
were told to get their sorry team off the field, let them play.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges has blown through, but there'll be a topical
storm a-brewin' if the second-ranked Bruins tear through the season
Ten-n-Oh and then try to match up their credentials against Ohio
State, Kansas State, Florida State and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The system used to determine the country's Nos. 1 and 2 teams
these days will be complicated enough. Don't skew around and take
your chances the computer will spit out the right numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're all content with a non-Fiesta Bowl appearance.
Then go ahead, file it away under ``Playing it Safe.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Overheard at a USC alumni postgame gathering: ``Mr. Jenkins,
your Tanqueray. It'll take away the sting.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ So Kevin Malone has to go back to his buddy list of ``Guys I
Know Who Can Manage'' after Jim Leyland flicked his ashes at the
Dodgers and Felipe Alou bid adieu.
</P>
<P>
   (Yeah, and Bob Watson coulda got us Bucky Dent in a second, but
that's another rebuilding process).
</P>
<P>
   So whoozit gonna be? Davey Johnson ? Kevin Kennedy ? Will
someone throw in Davey Lopes' name?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would be a real quick fix for Fox. Lopes would be a
long-term gem. In between, we have home-grown Kennedy, who can't
see this situation as Camelot but you gotta believe wants this job
the most.
</P>
<P>
   The electorial college repeats: Kennedy in '99. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Chan Ho Park will reportedly be excused from his military
obligation if he pitches for his home country of South Korea in
December's Asian Games. Oh, and the team has to win, too. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Angels skipper Terry Collins , trying to coax his old pal Dave
Wallace out of the Mets front office and back onto the field as his
throwin' coach, would also give the team a better chance at signing
Mike Piazza if he can pull it off. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Padres in six. In the !ital!big series. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday's the day college-educated scholars on both sides of
the NBA table cancel the limo service for Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Early congratulations _ you've managed see that labor strife may
have knocked the NFL, NHL and major league baseball on their rear
sides, but each rallied after a few down years and put smiles back
on the fans' faces. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The NBA season doesn't start until March anyway. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ For all the inside stuff on the NBA lockout, don't let the
kids watch ``NBA Inside Stuff.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ At an informal rally last week at UCLA that was supposed to
show some sort of NBA player solidarity, Elden Campbell
</P>
<P>
   showed up about an hour late. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Adding Steve Fisher to the Sac Kings coaching staff should: a)
show Chris Webber the team would eventually like him to make an
appearance and b) end any trade rumors about Webber going to the
Lakers for Campbell. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The master of hyperbole, Terry Donahue , spent the opening of
the Tennessee-Georgia CBS telecast blathering on about how 'Dogs QB
Quincy Carter is ``the best freshman quarterback I've seen since
John Elway '' and WR/DB Champ Bailey is a ``better offensive player
than Charles Woodson
</P>
<P>
   and is just as good on defense.'' Oh, Georgia lost 22-3. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Sir Rupert Murdoch has moved his ``base of operations'' from
L.A. to Manhattan, says the New York Times, and he has moved into
the trendy Mercer Hotel in SoHo. &QL;
</P>
