<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Losses are heavy in victory
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ First, the Florida Gators lost their leading
passer to a season-ending knee injury. Now they'll have to play at
least one game _ and maybe more _ without their top runner.
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Terry Jackson will miss Saturday's home game
against Auburn with a severly sprained ankle. Jackson, the SEC's
third-leading rusher with 577 yards, was hurt Saturday night in the
third quarter of Florida's 22-10 victory over LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry's going to be out two-to-three weeks,'' UF coach Steve
Spurrier said. ``Hopefully, he'll be back for the (Oct. 31) Georgia
game. But it could be longer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's loss isn't good news to an offense that lost starter
Jesse Palmer with a broken right clavicle in the second quarter
against LSU. He will be replacd by Robert Gillespie, a true
freshman who led UF with 13 carries for 72 yards against LSU. He
has 34 carries for 175 yards and 11 catches for 219 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier said Palmer and All-America defensive tackle Ed Chester
(dislocated knee) both will miss the rest of the regular season,
though Palmer likely would be available for Florida's bowl game.
When he was hurt, Palmer was the SEC's most efficient passer (and
third in the nation), having completed 73-of-123 for 1,246 yards,
14 TDs and five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Johnson, who alternated with Palmer the previous three
games, looked shaky against LSU. He completed 13-of-22 for 156
yards, a touchdown and no interceptions. But he had at least two
interceptions that were dropped and another that was nullifed by a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't recovered three of our four fumbles, and they
don't drop those interceptions, we could have lost,'' Spurrier
said. ``We've got to do a better job of taking care of the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier a no-show: Why the Gators threw a pass and called three
runs instead of taking a knee three times when they got the ball
back with 1:51 left remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier wasn't available to answer that question because he
skipped his regular Sunday teleconference with reporters. Spurrier
instead attended the Florida's soccer team's 1-1 tie with
top-ranked North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier taped a short interview with a school official that was
made available to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard update: Spurrier said he will wait until mid-week to
decide whether starting cornerback Dock Pollard will play against
Auburn. He was suspended from the LSU game by the university for
skipping classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look during the week and see if he deserves another
(suspension) from the coaches,'' Spurrier said. ``We tell our
players to go to class and don't let your teammates down by getting
suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier said true freshman Robert Cromartie likely would start
against Auburn, anyway. Cromartie and sophomore Benny Alexander
both played well against LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
