A1012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FSU-FOLLOWUP-COX     10-11 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-FOLLOWUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UM's Warren suffers seizure on trip home
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sophomore defensive end David Warren had
a scary trip home from Miami on Saturday, but he was not
hospitalized after having a mild seizure on the airplane, FSU
spokesman Rob Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second seizure in less than 10 weeks for Warren, who
was credited unofficially with one tackle against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure happened about halfway through the 80-minute flight
from Miami to Tallahassee aboard the team plane, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players thought he was cramping up but then one of them yelled
he was having a seizure,'' said Wilson, who was on the plane. ``The
doctors were four or five rows away so they got to him in 20
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   A team official stayed with Warren throughout Saturday night to
watch him.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyler, Texas, native is scheduled today to begin a battery
of tests, including an MRI, CAT scan and blood work.
</P>
<P>
   He is out of practice at least until the tests are completed,
Wilson said. Doctors also told him that if no cause for the
seizures is found, Warren will receive medication to treat them.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 USA Today Defensive Player of the Year also had what
doctors believe was a seizure Aug.5 during two-a-day practices. His
roommate, Donald Heaven, found him unconscious on their dorm room
floor. He was released from Tallahassee Memorial Regional Hospital
after doctors found no cause.
</P>
<P>
   Neurologists and other doctors did exhaustive tests in the
following days but also found nothing. He had had no history of
seizures and was cleared to play three days later.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Warren, who turns 20 on Wednesday, was not
unconscious during Saturday's attack, but he ``didn't know what was
happening to him.'' Coaches and teammates were unsettled, Wilson
said, but not overwhelmed with worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any look of panic on the doctor's faces,''
Wilson said. ``And that was reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Weinke release: Coach Bobby Bowden was so pleased with
quarterback Chris Weinke's performance in FSU's 26-14 win at Miami
that he intends to turn over more control of the offense to him in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I liked best about it was we were able to throw and
kill them,'' Bowden said. ``It took the guy that has been taking
all the criticism this year and he goes out and he beats them.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Weinke's six interceptions against North Carolina State,
that hasn't been Weinke's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to take the game out of the quarterback's hands,''
he said. ``We've given it to the tailback. We've given it to the
fullback. We've faked throws more than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   But no more, Bowden said Sunday. The Seminoles (5-1) improved to
No.6 in the Associated Press poll and No.7 in the coaches poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) is the first time I felt we made a step forward,
that we might be getting to where I want us to be,'' Bowden said.
``Now (offensive coordinator Mark) Richt is going to want to put
more offense back into the quarterback's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Injury report: LB Lamont Green (dislocated left elbow) is out
this week at least. Doctors will determine how much longer his
injury will need later this week. Other injuries: P Keith Cottrell
(right hip flexor strain), FS Shawn McCorkel (left shoulder
separation), FS Dexter Jackson (left hamstring reinjury), FB Billy
Rhodes (lower back bruise) and WR Ron Dugans (let hip pointer) will
be out of contact at least early this week.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
