Teresa B., 24, shown in the back yard of her home, and her
4-year-old daughter both have AIDS, but live far from needed
services. As the HIV virus becomes more common in women nationally,
health experts are especially worried about rural women because
they are often more isolated, less independent and less assertive
than other people. Rural AIDS victims now make up an increasing
share of the nation's AIDS cases. (Bill Stover/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOWRY CITY, Mo. -- Oct. 11, 1998 -- RURAL-AIDS-1, 10-11
-- Ronda Elliott, 30, has AIDS, and in this dusty country town
brushing the Ozarks, she has found it to be something people have a
hard time accepting. Ms. Elliott, a mother of two, tried to keep it
quiet, but with a population of only 700, she says, if ``you know
something, the other side of town knows it.'' Both of Ms. Elliot's
children have had to fend off taunts about their mother. (Roy
Inman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 11, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS, 10-11 --
The Yankees David Wells, taunted by Cleveland fans for most of Game
5 of the AL championship series, tipping his hat to the crowd after
being taken out of the game in the eighth-inning Sunday. The
Yankees defeated the Cleveland Indians 5-3 to take a 3-2 lead in
the series. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VOSKRESENSK, Russia -- Oct. 11, 1998 -- RUSSIA-FACTORIES,
10-11 -- In Voskresensk, 50 miles east of Moscow, one of Russia's
biggest fertilizer plants languishes in a state far from state of
the art. It was taken over by a bank, and, like other Russian
factories, the plant's future looks bleak. (Jacqueline Mia
Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW DELHI, India -- Oct. 11, 1998 -- INDIA-ONIONS, 10-11
-- Shoppers trying to buy subsidized onions from a federal
government cooperative selling a limited supply of the onions from
a flatbed truck. An onion shortage in India is producing long
lines, high prices and short tempers in many cities. The price of
the lowly onion, an essential ingredient of the flavor base, or
masala, of almost every dish cooked here, is seven times higher
than it was this time last year. (Celia Dugger/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
