</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH BRUINS STEP IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the most impressive win of Bob Toledo's
tenure _ yes, more impressive than USC in '96 and Washington in '97
_ one question: If not Arizona, then who?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took Arizona's best shot Saturday night. They
staggered momentarily, regained their balance, then responded with
a devastating fourth-quarter flurry that put an undefeated season
squarely into focus.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA lacks the type of dominating defense necessary to beat
Oregon, Washington and USC on a bad day. But if the Bruins play as
they did in Arizona Stadium _ if they avoid turnovers, make big
plays and physically overwhelm opponents _ it'll take a fabulous
performance to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have the Bruins been more vulnerable than they were on
Saturday night, playing a hot team in a hostile environment without
their big-play receiver (Freddie Mitchell), their starting tailback
(Jermaine Lewis), their top defensive lineman (Kenyon Coleman), two
starting linebackers (Ramogi Huma and Mike Wiley).
</P>
<P>
   And yet . . .
</P>
<P>
   What made Saturday's 52-28 victory unique _ aside from being
UCLA's first in Tucson in 10 years _ was its subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-largest crowd in Arizona Stadium history (58,738)
wasn't so much disappointed as dazed. One minute, Wildcats receiver
Jeremy McDaniel makes a spectacular touchdown catch for a 28-24
lead. The next, UCLA scores on three consecutive plays and takes an
insurmountable lead.
</P>
<P>
   The game was so close for so long _ 47 minutes, to be exact _
and then, BAM! The Bruins bolted away. A long pass here, a turnover
there, and they're out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody had gone to the bathroom, they might not have
believed what happened,'' Arizona coach Dick Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins ended with a 28-0 surge and outgained Arizona 229-68
in the fourth quarter _ a marked contrast from their previous
visits, when the Bruins were not only beaten but beaten up. Above
all, this was a victory for strength coach Kevin Yoxall, who stands
behind only Toledo as the reason for UCLA's resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA was tougher and more physical, and we have to admit
that,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   More physical, and more resourceful. DeShaun Foster's
performance (118 yards) as Lewis' replacement was one example. Ryan
Nece for Huma at linebacker was another. Someone goes down, someone
fills in, the No. 2-ranked Bruins don't miss a beat. All those
September substitutions are paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Cade McNown's performance (10 of 24) was the subject
of much scrutiny during and after the game. But he didn't make
mistakes _ Arizona's quarterbacks were intercepted twice _ and he
made the biggest play: a 64-yard pass to Danny Farmer that gave
UCLA a 38-28 lead with 11 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps McNown won't complete 60 percent of his passes this
season. But if he completes 45 percent of the routine plays and 90
percent of the big ones, victories will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Few people remember Jake Plummer's completion percentage in
Arizona State's 1996 comeback over UCLA. But everyone remembers
Plummer catching a trick pass and scampering through the UCLA
defense. It was the signature play of ASU's Rose Bowl season.
</P>
<P>
   So if not Arizona, then who? Oregon won't be easy. The Ducks
have one of the most potent offenses in the nation. Winning in
Husky Stadium is a chore, especially in November. USC? Anybody's
game.
</P>
<P>
   That was the theory Saturday night _ anybody's game _ and it
was. For 47 minutes. Can anyone hang with UCLA for 60?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
