</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE-CRUSHING BLAKE DELIVERS FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ On the flight late Saturday night from Edmonton to
Vancouver, the Kings watched a video.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't watching Spice Girls, but they did see some pop in
the form of repeated replays of one of Rob Blake's greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven seconds into Saturday night's season-opening 2-1
victory in Edmonton, Oilers forward Andrei Kovalenko carried the
puck into the Kings' zone while committing the cardinal hockey sin
of keeping his head down.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalenko was being covered by Mattias Norstrom, and skated to
his right. Little did he know Norstrom was setting him up. Blake
backed into Kovalenko, dropping him to the ice with a crushing but
clean check. It was several minutes before Kovalenko got up, though
he was able to remain in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get too many opportunities like that,'' said Blake,
whose team is the visitor for the Vancouver Canucks' season opener
at 2 p.m. this afternoon at GM Place. ``Mattie Norstrom brought him
right to me. It felt pretty nice. We've got to hit. That's the way
we're going to win. We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr to play: Stephane Fiset was excellent in goal Saturday,
but coach Larry Robinson said Jamie Storr will start today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't play him (today), we could be looking at two weeks
until we get him in again,'' Robinson said. ``I think Steph
deserves to be in the home opener (Friday against the Boston
Bruins).''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is contemplating a couple of changes to combat the
Canucks' size. Steve McKenna, who is 6-foot-8, 247 pounds, and 6-3,
223-pound Roman Vopat may be moved into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor mill: At some point, it's expected the Kings will try to
acquire a proven goal-scorer, not only to add some punch to their
offense but to help draw fans to the Staples Center when it opens
next season.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Vancouver Province, the Kings are rumored to
have offered the New York Islanders $20 million for free-agent
winger Zigmund Palffy, who scored 45 goals last season. The
Province also reported that for holdout winger Pavel Bure, the
Kings offered the Canucks their choice of two of these three
players: Aki Berg, Olli Jokinen and Glen Murray. According to the
Province, the Canucks rejected the Kings' offer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither scenario seems in accordance with the Kings' commitment
to rebuilding. And Bure's questionable attitude, given that he has
refused to report to the Canucks despite being under contract, also
seems out of step with the Kings' focus on team chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Palffy or Bure certainly would add a
dimension the Kings lack and lift them a rung closer to being
contenders in the NHL's Western Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-11-98 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981011.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1166 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-PLANE-LADN     10-11 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-PLANE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES PREPARING FOR SPACE PLANE'S ROAD TRIP BACK TO LAUNCH SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHARLES F. BOSTWICK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. -- Lockheed Martin's X-33 space
plane will rocket from Southern California to Montana in 24
minutes, skimming the edge of space.
</P>
<P>
   But coming home will be almost as big an adventure -- though
considerably slower.
</P>
<P>
   As wide as eight big rigs placed side by side, the 32.5-ton
space plane will be trucked back to California over hundreds of
miles of two-lane highways -- crossing mountains, desert and the
Continental Divide, contending with overpasses, highway signs,
roadside trees and small towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest load we've ever planned on moving on our
state highways,'' Department of Transportation spokesman Scott
Magruder said in Nevada, where officials may hold public hearings
to inform residents of the hamlets the behemoth will pass beginning
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly the size of the space shuttle but piloted by computers on
the ground, the wingless, wedge-shaped rocket plane will blast off
from a launch site now under construction at Edwards Air Force Base
in Southern California's Antelope Valley, north of Los Angeles. Its
purpose is to test technology needed for the VentureStar reusable
spacecraft -- Lockheed Martin's proposed entry in the commercial
space race.
</P>
<P>
   The X-33 is scheduled to make its maiden flight in late summer
to an Army air field at the Dugway Proving Grounds in western Utah.
The next five flights also will be to Dugway -- a 450-mile flight
that will take 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Its seventh flight will go to Malmstrom Air Force Base near
Great Falls, Mont., 950 miles from Edwards. That flight will take
24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketing in a steep arc toward Montana, the X-33 will zoom as
high as 250,000 feet -- 47 miles, or about six miles below the
280,000 feet at which the Air Force awarded its X-15 pilots
astronaut wings in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is not saying much about its transportation plan
for the return trip. The company is awaiting bids this week from
two unidentified companies to do the actual moving and doesn't want
to say anything until then that could affect the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still in a competitive nature,'' spokesman Ron Lindeke
said.
</P>
<P>
   But documents and interviews show that Lockheed Martin officials
originally planned to fly the X-33 back to Edwards piggyback on the
NASA 747 that regularly ferries space shuttles back and forth
between Florida's Kennedy Space Center and Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   The company eventually concluded flying would cost too much, and
there were problems with the availability of the 747, Lindeke said.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the X-33 back to Edwards presents its own problems:
bridges, for example.
</P>
<P>
   As it sits atop its custom transport trailer, the craft's
vertical tail fins reach 26 feet above the pavement -- far too tall
to fit under highway bridges with an average 13 to 16 feet of
clearance, highway officials say.
</P>
<P>
   To negotiate the overpasses, an initial idea was to fabricate a
set of mobile ramps, each hauled by its own tractor-trailer. One
set of ramps would pull up to one side of an overpass, another set
to the back side.
</P>
<P>
   The X-33's tractor would drive up one set of ramps, across the
roadway atop the overpass, then down the ramps on the other side.
That idea also was rejected, again as too expensive, Lindeke said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the plan is to bypass bridges using highway on- and
off-ramps, frontage roads, secondary roads and judicious route
selection -- a map which still isn't finished.
</P>
<P>
   Entering California, for example, the space plane's trailer will
cross the state line just east of Death Valley and cruise at 25 or
30 mph for about 80 miles down lightly traveled Highway 127.
</P>
<P>
   Before the craft reaches the town of Baker on Interstate 15, it
turns west onto county roads and eventually cuts across the Army's
Fort Irwin training grounds on the last leg to Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the widest load, to the best of anybody's memory, that
we've ever had,'' said Caltrans spokesman Jim Drago.
</P>
<P>
   Highway 127 will be shut down to let the craft pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road is wide enough to accommodate the X-33, but not
anything else,'' Drago said.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes that Gov. Pete Wilson and the state Legislature
have recognized the commercial space industry -- of which the X-33
is a harbinger -- as important to California's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always are going to have an impact on somebody,'' he said.
``What we do is try to minimize that impact.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, the craft's likely route is Highway 95, which passes
through towns including Beatty, Tonapah and Goldfield. Nevada
highway officials said they've asked Lockheed Martin officials
whether the size of the craft will require cutting down roadside
trees or building detours, and whether it can pull over
periodically to let traffic go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously realize this is a important project and we are
trying to do everything we can to work with Lockheed Martin, but
obviously there are some concerns that need to be addressed,''
Magruder said.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, two-lane highways are typically 36 feet wide --
barely more than half the X-33's width from canted tail fin to
canted tail fin. But officials believe it will fit, though maybe at
the expense of a few trees, and all the overpasses on the projected
route can be scaled by off- and on-ramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had stuff heavier and taller. I don't think we have had
anything as wide,'' said Dave Galt, Montana motor carrier service
division administrator.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes: ``It's going to be a considerable undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
