<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: FOR THE ISLANDERS' OPENER, PICTURE WAS TRULY DARK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howie Rose and Joe Micheletti sat together Saturday night in
their Fox Sports New York aerie at Nassau Coliseum. Rose was to
start his fourth season with the Islanders; Micheletti, his first.
But they had nothing to do.
</P>
<P>
   They watched the Islanders lose to Pittsburgh, 4-3. They talked
hockey to each other and to the visiting Ed Westfall, Micheletti's
predecessor. They had media guides, game programs and stat sheets.
All around the press level, where television monitors normally
showed the Islanders, the baseball playoffs were on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we're in a vacuum that we will ultimately be
released from,'' Rose said. ``It's unusual not to be able to
release the passion I have for the game on the night it's supposed
to be released.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who also calls the Mets for FSNY-TV (Fox Sports New York),
added: ``You gear up to this night for months. As involved as I am
in baseball, by Labor Day, I'm getting excited about hockey.
Opening day in baseball and opening night in hockey are two of the
365 nights a year I look forward to most.'
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Micheletti endured their one-game limbo because Madison
Square Garden, FSNY's parent, opted to show the Devils play the
Blackhawks on the cable channel and not create a second one for the
Islanders' opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that in the past, when the Devils and Islanders
played at the same time, FSNY (or, its predecessor, SportsChannel
New York) did not quibble about adding a second channel. This time,
there were quiet rumblings that advertising sales for the Islanders
were poor, and that sponsors would get even worse value if the game
were shifted to Fox Sports New York 2.
</P>
<P>
   But you could also read the Garden's action as a message to the
Islanders' ownership, which is locked in a nasty, public fight with
Nassau County and SMG, the arena's landlord, over the coliseum's
safety, and a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the resolute Islander owners are unlikely to back down from
a position that apparently irks the Garden and its majority owner,
Cablevision Systems, which pays the Islanders $13 million annually
for their cable rights.
</P>
<P>
   But not carrying Saturday's game will not keep the team from
pursuing its case in federal court against SMG.. So the result of
Saturday night's action _ taken on a day's notice _ was to punish
Islander fans on opening night. This damnation is likely to
continue, as it is unlikely the Islanders will start playing like
the Flyers and become a magnet for advertisers like the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday and Saturday nights, when the Islanders and Devils
play at virtually the same times, only the Devils' game is likely
to be seen _ unless Garden officials start viewing subscribers with
anything less than disdain. Through October, two more
Islanders-Devils conflicts remain to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Rose and Micheletti, idled Saturday night, may be hockey
announcers without hockey to announce on a semiregular basis. (With
no conflict Sunday, they will call the Islanders game from Boston
at 1:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people couldn't care less about hockey, but
I've always been proud to be associated with it,'' Rose said. ``Not
to have the vehicle to release the passion is disappointing. I feel
awful for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rose walked downstairs from the press box at the end of the
game, an usher shouted: ``Missed you on the game, Howie. But the
Mets start soon!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPONSOR SQUABBLE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you watched Fox's National Football League pregame show
Sunday, you saw Terry Bradshaw and Howie Long cover the ``NFL on
Fox'' logo with a Fox Sports sign. Bradshaw gabbed about wanting to
adhere to rules, and there being ``certain things you can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   What was all this unexplained business posturing about?
</P>
<P>
   A translation: This season, Energizer began sponsoring the ``Fox
Energizer Playbook,'' a weekly segment done on Fox's studio
football field. In certain shots, the Energizer field logo and an
``NFL on Fox'' wall sign can be viewed together _ a league taboo
because Energizer is not a league sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lighthearted way of letting everyone know we're
following the terms of our contract with the NFL,'' said Fox
spokesman Vince Wladika.
</P>
<P>
   New rules that protect official sponsors bar the commingling of
the NFL name, trademark or logo with those of companies that are
not league sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate Fox's willingness to live by the same rules as
everyone else,'' said Greg Aiello, an NFL spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fox undoubtedly believes it must find ways to earn back the $550
million a year it is paying for NFL rights. Its devotion to
Energizer was made evident by co-host James Brown, who said, ``We
love Energizer at Fox.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
